INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-02-lesson-01','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','What Is a Market Cycle? and Psychology During Expansion','cmf-module-2-02','text','### Learning Objectives\n\nBy the end of this module, you should be able to:\n\nExplain what a cryptocurrency market cycle is\n\nIdentify the common phases of a market cycle\n\nUnderstand how investor psychology changes during each phase\n\nExplain how fear, greed and social influence affect market behaviour\n\nRecognise common cognitive biases in investment decisions\n\nUnderstand how liquidity, leverage and market narratives amplify cycles\n\nDistinguish between a market cycle and a guaranteed repeating pattern\n\nApply a disciplined framework when markets become emotionally extreme\n\n### Introduction\n\nCryptocurrency markets rarely move in a straight line.\n\nPrices rise, fall, stabilise and sometimes recover. Periods of optimism can develop into excitement and eventually euphoria. Fear may then replace confidence, causing prices to decline far more quickly than many participants expected.\n\nThese movements are often described as market cycles.\n\nA market cycle is a broad pattern in which asset prices and investor behaviour move through recognisable phases over time.\n\nAlthough market cycles are influenced by technology, adoption, economic conditions and liquidity, they are also strongly shaped by human psychology.\n\nParticipants commonly move between emotions such as:\n\nDoubt\n\nHope\n\nConfidence\n\nGreed\n\nFear\n\nPanic\n\nDespair\n\nThe technology may be digital, but the emotional forces driving market behaviour are deeply human.\n\nUnderstanding these forces will not allow you to predict every market turning point. It can, however, help you recognise emotional extremes, question popular narratives and make more disciplined decisions.\n\n### What Is a Market Cycle?\n\nA market cycle is the movement of a market through periods of expansion, peak activity, contraction and recovery.\n\nA simplified cycle may include:\n\nAccumulation\n\nExpansion\n\nEuphoria\n\nDistribution\n\nDecline\n\nCapitulation\n\nRecovery\n\nThese phases are not fixed rules.\n\nA market may:\n\nMove through them quickly or slowly\n\nRepeat a phase\n\nReverse before completing the cycle\n\nExperience several smaller cycles within a larger one\n\nBehave differently across different assets\n\nMarket-cycle models are analytical tools. They are not clocks or guaranteed forecasting systems.\n\n### Why Markets Move in Cycles\n\nMarkets move in cycles because expectations, capital and behaviour change over time.\n\nDuring an early recovery, prices may remain low because most participants are still cautious.\n\nAs prices begin to rise:\n\nConfidence improves\n\nNew capital enters\n\nMedia attention increases\n\nPositive narratives spread\n\nRisk-taking expands\n\nEventually, prices may rise faster than the underlying fundamentals justify.\n\nAt that point, early participants may begin taking profits.\n\nWhen demand weakens, prices decline. Falling prices reduce confidence, trigger leveraged liquidations and cause participants to withdraw capital.\n\nAfter excessive speculation has been removed, the market may stabilise and begin another period of accumulation.\n\nThe cycle is therefore influenced by a feedback loop between:\n\nPrice\n\nConfidence\n\nLiquidity\n\nParticipation\n\nExpectations\n\n### Phase 1: Accumulation\n\nAccumulation commonly occurs after a prolonged market decline.\n\nPrices may have stabilised, but public interest remains low.\n\nTypical conditions include:\n\nNegative or indifferent media coverage\n\nReduced trading volume\n\nLimited retail participation\n\nLow expectations\n\nStrong distrust following previous losses\n\nGradual buying by patient participants\n\nMany people who were enthusiastic near the previous market peak may no longer be interested.\n\nThe market may appear inactive or irrelevant.\n\nMore experienced participants may begin acquiring assets because they believe prices no longer reflect long-term potential.\n\nHowever, accumulation is difficult to identify in real time.\n\nA market that appears to be stabilising may still decline further.\n\nLow prices do not automatically mean that an asset is undervalued. Some projects remain low because they are failing.\n\n### Psychology During Accumulation\n\nCommon emotions include:\n\nDisbelief\n\nExhaustion\n\nCaution\n\nIndifference\n\nFear of another decline\n\nParticipants may say:\n\n“The market is finished.”\n\n“Nobody cares about cryptocurrency anymore.”\n\n“Prices will never recover.”\n\n“I was wrong to become involved.”\n\nIronically, this pessimism may exist when risk has already reduced significantly from the previous peak.\n\nHowever, widespread negativity alone is not a reason to buy. The asset’s fundamentals must still be evaluated.\n\n### Phase 2: Expansion or Mark-Up\n\nDuring the expansion phase, prices begin rising more consistently.\n\nEvidence of improvement may include:\n\nIncreased trading volume\n\nHigher market liquidity\n\nRenewed development activity\n\nPositive regulatory or institutional developments\n\nStronger user growth\n\nImproved market sentiment\n\nEarly buyers begin showing profits.\n\nAs confidence grows, more participants enter.\n\nThe market may form a pattern of:\n\nHigher highs\n\nHigher lows\n\nStronger demand during declines\n\nIncreasing public attention\n\nAt first, many observers doubt that the recovery is sustainable.\n\nAs the trend continues, doubt gradually changes into optimism.\n\n### Psychology During Expansion\n\nCommon emotions include:\n\nHope\n\nOptimism\n\nCuriosity\n\nGrowing confidence\n\nParticipants may say:\n\n“Perhaps the market is recovering.”\n\n“This asset may have genuine potential.”\n\n“I should buy during the next pullback.”\n\n“The fundamentals are improving.”\n\nDuring this phase, decisions may still be relatively analytical.\n\nHowever, rising prices begin influencing how participants interpret information.\n\nPositive developments receive more attention, while risks may gradually be discounted.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,1,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-02-lesson-02','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Phase 3: Public Participation and Phase 7: Capitulation','cmf-module-2-02','text','### Phase 3: Public Participation\n\nAs prices rise further, broader participation develops.\n\nNew investors enter after observing previous gains.\n\nMedia coverage becomes more frequent, and cryptocurrency discussions expand across:\n\nSocial media\n\nNews platforms\n\nWorkplaces\n\nFamilies\n\nOnline communities\n\nProjects find it easier to raise capital.\n\nNew tokens are launched, trading activity increases and speculative behaviour expands.\n\nParticipants begin expecting declines to be temporary buying opportunities.\n\nThis phase can contain strong fundamental growth, but it can also create overconfidence.\n\n### The Feedback Loop of Rising Prices\n\nRising prices can create their own demand.\n\nThe process may look like this:\n\nPrices rise\n\nHolders report profits\n\nPublic interest increases\n\nNew buyers enter\n\nPrices rise further\n\nConfidence strengthens\n\nEven more buyers enter\n\nThis is an example of market reflexivity.\n\nPrice is no longer only reflecting the ecosystem.\n\nIt is influencing the ecosystem by attracting:\n\nCapital\n\nDevelopers\n\nUsers\n\nMedia attention\n\nBusiness partnerships\n\nThe same feedback loop can later operate in reverse.\n\n### Phase 4: Euphoria\n\nEuphoria is the emotionally extreme stage of a market expansion.\n\nPrices may rise rapidly, and participants begin believing that traditional valuation principles no longer apply.\n\nCommon characteristics include:\n\nParabolic price increases\n\nHeavy retail participation\n\nWidespread use of leverage\n\nExtreme social-media activity\n\nLarge numbers of new token launches\n\nUnrealistic price forecasts\n\nDeclining attention to risk\n\nSpeculative assets outperforming established projects\n\nPeople who previously showed little interest may begin buying because they fear missing the opportunity.\n\nSuccessful investors may assume that profits resulted entirely from skill rather than favourable market conditions.\n\n### Psychology During Euphoria\n\nCommon emotions include:\n\nExcitement\n\nGreed\n\nOverconfidence\n\nUrgency\n\nFear of missing out\n\nParticipants may say:\n\n“This time is different.”\n\n“The price cannot fall because adoption is growing.”\n\n“Everyone who buys will make money.”\n\n“I should borrow more before the price rises again.”\n\n“Traditional valuation no longer matters.”\n\nRisk is often highest when it feels lowest.\n\nRapid gains create the illusion that buying is safe because previous buyers have been rewarded.\n\nIn reality, expectations may already be built into the price, leaving little margin for disappointment.\n\n### Phase 5: Distribution\n\nDistribution may occur when early holders begin reducing their positions while public enthusiasm remains high.\n\nPrices may continue rising or move sideways.\n\nThe market may appear healthy, but internal conditions begin weakening.\n\nPossible signs include:\n\nLarge holders selling into strong demand\n\nFailed attempts to reach new highs\n\nGreater volatility\n\nNegative news receiving stronger reactions\n\nDeclining participation beneath headline prices\n\nIncreasing disagreements between market indicators\n\nMore aggressive promotion by token insiders\n\nOptimistic buyers may interpret every decline as another opportunity.\n\nMeanwhile, experienced or early participants may be transferring risk to newer buyers.\n\nDistribution is rarely obvious at the time.\n\nA sideways market can also be a temporary consolidation before another increase.\n\n### Psychology During Distribution\n\nCommon emotions include:\n\nConfidence\n\nDenial\n\nConfusion\n\nContinued greed\n\nParticipants may say:\n\n“The market is only resting.”\n\n“This is the last chance to buy before the next rally.”\n\n“The decline is being manipulated.”\n\n“Weak investors are being removed.”\n\nSome of these statements may be correct.\n\nThe problem is that participants often use them automatically to protect an existing belief.\n\n### Phase 6: Decline or Mark-Down\n\nThe decline phase begins when selling pressure becomes stronger than buying demand.\n\nPrices form:\n\nLower highs\n\nLower lows\n\nFailed recoveries\n\nIncreasing selling volume\n\nAt first, many participants believe the decline is temporary.\n\nThey may continue buying because previous declines recovered quickly.\n\nAs prices fall further:\n\nConfidence weakens\n\nLeverage is liquidated\n\nNew capital disappears\n\nProjects experience funding pressure\n\nNegative news receives greater attention\n\nThe market’s emotional narrative shifts from optimism to concern.\n\n### Leverage and the Decline\n\nLeverage can accelerate falling markets.\n\nConsider the following sequence:\n\nPrices decline\n\nLeveraged long positions lose collateral value\n\nExchanges liquidate those positions\n\nLiquidations create additional market selling\n\nPrices decline further\n\nMore positions are liquidated\n\nThis is called a liquidation cascade.\n\nThe resulting price movement may be far greater than the original selling pressure would have caused on its own.\n\n### Phase 7: Capitulation\n\nCapitulation occurs when participants sell because they can no longer tolerate further loss.\n\nThe objective changes from earning a return to escaping the market.\n\nCapitulation may involve:\n\nRapid price declines\n\nExtremely high selling volume\n\nForced liquidations\n\nExchange or project failures\n\nWidespread fear\n\nAbandonment of previously popular narratives\n\nParticipants selling without considering valuation\n\nSome holders sell after enduring most of the decline because the emotional pressure becomes unbearable.\n\nOthers may be forced to sell because they used leverage, borrowed money or invested funds needed for essential expenses.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,2,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-02-lesson-03','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Psychology During Capitulation and The Disposition Effect','cmf-module-2-02','text','### Psychology During Capitulation\n\nCommon emotions include:\n\nPanic\n\nDespair\n\nRegret\n\nAnger\n\nShame\n\nParticipants may say:\n\n“I need to sell before everything goes to zero.”\n\n“Cryptocurrency was a complete fraud.”\n\n“I will never invest again.”\n\n“I cannot tolerate another decline.”\n\nCapitulation can create attractive prices for surviving assets, but it is dangerous to assume that every severe decline marks the bottom.\n\nA failing asset can continue falling even after losing most of its value.\n\n### Phase 8: Recovery\n\nAfter excessive leverage and speculation have been removed, the market may begin stabilising.\n\nVolatility may decline and selling pressure may weaken.\n\nA recovery often begins quietly.\n\nPossible signs include:\n\nPrices holding above previous lows\n\nImproved market structure\n\nGradual return of liquidity\n\nContinued development despite low attention\n\nStronger assets separating from weaker ones\n\nReduced emotional reaction to negative news\n\nPublic confidence may remain low.\n\nMany former participants are unwilling to return because the memory of losses remains strong.\n\nRecovery can eventually lead back into accumulation and expansion, beginning another cycle.\n\n### Cycles Within Cycles\n\nCryptocurrency markets do not operate through one single cycle.\n\nThere may be:\n\nMulti-year market cycles\n\nMonthly cycles\n\nWeekly cycles\n\nIntraday cycles\n\nAsset-specific cycles\n\nSector cycles\n\nFor example, the broader market may be expanding while one category of tokens declines.\n\nA single asset may experience a speculative cycle even when the overall market is stable.\n\nThis means participants must define the timeframe being analysed.\n\nA bearish weekly movement can occur within a bullish multi-year trend.\n\nA short-term price increase can occur within a longer-term decline.\n\n### Cryptocurrency-Specific Cycle Drivers\n\nCryptocurrency cycles can be influenced by several distinctive factors.\n\n### New Token Issuance\n\nToken launches and unlocks can introduce new supply.\n\n### Network Development\n\nUpgrades, scaling improvements and applications can create new demand.\n\n### Mining and Staking Economics\n\nChanges in rewards affect participant incentives and potential selling pressure.\n\n### Stablecoin Liquidity\n\nGrowth or contraction in stablecoin supply can influence market liquidity.\n\n### Exchange Access\n\nListings, delistings and banking relationships affect market participation.\n\n### Regulation\n\nLegal developments can change investor confidence and accessibility.\n\n### Leverage\n\nDerivatives and perpetual contracts can amplify both expansions and declines.\n\n### Narratives\n\nThemes such as decentralised finance, NFTs, gaming or artificial intelligence can attract concentrated speculative capital.\n\n### Market Narratives\n\nA market narrative is a widely shared explanation for why an asset or category should increase in value.\n\nNarratives simplify complex markets into understandable stories.\n\nExamples may include:\n\nDigital gold\n\nThe future of finance\n\nThe next generation of the internet\n\nTokenisation of real-world assets\n\nBlockchain gaming\n\nArtificial intelligence combined with cryptocurrency\n\nNarratives can direct attention and capital toward genuine innovation.\n\nThey can also produce excessive speculation.\n\nDuring a strong cycle, participants may value projects based on their connection to a popular theme rather than their actual development or adoption.\n\nA persuasive story is not the same as economic value.\n\n### Investor Psychology\n\nMarket cycles are amplified by predictable patterns in human decision-making.\n\nThese patterns are called cognitive and emotional biases.\n\nUnderstanding them does not make a person immune.\n\nIt creates an opportunity to recognise them before acting.\n\n### Herd Behaviour\n\nHerd behaviour occurs when people follow the actions of a group.\n\nThey assume that a large number of participants must possess useful information.\n\nThe logic becomes:\n\nEveryone is buying\n\nTherefore, the asset must be good\n\nTherefore, I should buy\n\nThe group may be correct, but popularity is not proof.\n\nHerd behaviour often becomes strongest near market extremes.\n\n### Fear of Missing Out\n\nFear of missing out, or FOMO, is the anxiety that others are benefiting from an opportunity that may soon disappear.\n\nFOMO can cause participants to:\n\nBuy after large price increases\n\nAbandon position limits\n\nUse leverage\n\nIgnore research\n\nEnter low-quality tokens\n\nFollow influencers without verification\n\nA useful response to FOMO is to ask:\n\nWould I still buy this asset if its recent price chart were hidden from me?\n\nIf the answer is no, the decision may be driven primarily by momentum and emotion.\n\n### Loss Aversion\n\nLoss aversion describes the tendency for losses to feel more painful than equivalent gains feel rewarding.\n\nA person may react more strongly to losing 1,000 units than to gaining 1,000 units.\n\nLoss aversion can cause investors to:\n\nRefuse to sell failing assets\n\nTake profits too early\n\nAvoid admitting that the original analysis was wrong\n\nIncrease risk to recover losses\n\nThe desire to avoid emotional discomfort can produce financially irrational decisions.\n\n### The Disposition Effect\n\nThe disposition effect is the tendency to:\n\nSell winning investments too quickly\n\nHold losing investments too long\n\nSelling winners creates the satisfaction of confirming a successful decision.\n\nHolding losers postpones the emotional pain of admitting failure.\n\nA disciplined participant should evaluate current evidence rather than the emotional label of being in profit or loss.\n\nThe market does not know the price at which an individual purchased the asset.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,3,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-02-lesson-04','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Anchoring and Market Cycles Are Not Guaranteed Schedules','cmf-module-2-02','text','### Anchoring\n\nAnchoring occurs when a person relies too heavily on one reference point.\n\nExamples include:\n\nThe purchase price\n\nA previous all-time high\n\nAn analyst’s forecast\n\nA round number\n\nA person who bought at 100 may refuse to sell at 60 because they are waiting to “get their money back.”\n\nBut the purchase price does not determine the asset’s future value.\n\nThe relevant question is:\n\nWould I choose to own this asset at today’s price based on today’s information?\n\n### Confirmation Bias\n\nConfirmation bias is the tendency to seek information that supports an existing belief while avoiding contradictory evidence.\n\nA token holder may:\n\nFollow only supportive commentators\n\nDismiss criticism as manipulation\n\nIgnore negative project developments\n\nInterpret every event positively\n\nOnline communities can reinforce confirmation bias because members may punish scepticism and reward optimism.\n\nA strong investment process actively searches for evidence that could prove the original thesis wrong.\n\n### Recency Bias\n\nRecency bias gives excessive importance to recent events.\n\nAfter a long price increase, participants may believe that prices will continue rising.\n\nAfter a severe decline, they may believe that recovery is impossible.\n\nRecent performance feels more representative than it really is.\n\nMarket conditions change, and recent trends do not continue indefinitely.\n\n### Overconfidence\n\nOverconfidence occurs when participants overestimate their knowledge or skill.\n\nIt may develop after several profitable trades.\n\nThe person may then:\n\nIncrease position sizes\n\nUse more leverage\n\nTrade more frequently\n\nIgnore risk controls\n\nAttribute luck entirely to skill\n\nA rising market can make many poor strategies temporarily profitable.\n\nSkill should be evaluated across different market conditions, not only during a favourable cycle.\n\n### Survivorship Bias\n\nSurvivorship bias occurs when people focus on successful assets or participants while ignoring those that failed.\n\nMedia stories may highlight:\n\nInvestors who became wealthy\n\nTokens that increased dramatically\n\nTraders who predicted a major move\n\nFar less attention is given to:\n\nFailed projects\n\nLiquidated accounts\n\nLost seed phrases\n\nTraders who made incorrect predictions\n\nTokens that became worthless\n\nThis creates an exaggerated impression of how easy success is.\n\n### Sunk-Cost Fallacy\n\nThe sunk-cost fallacy occurs when previous time or money influences a decision that should be based on future prospects.\n\nA participant may say:\n\n“I have already lost too much to sell.”\n\n“I spent months researching this project.”\n\n“I must continue until the price recovers.”\n\nPast costs cannot be recovered by continuing automatically.\n\nThe decision should depend on expected future risk and value.\n\n### Narrative Fallacy\n\nThe narrative fallacy is the tendency to prefer simple stories over complex or uncertain explanations.\n\nFor example:\n\n“The price fell because of one news event.”\n\n“This token will succeed because blockchain adoption is inevitable.”\n\n“The market rises after every particular event.”\n\nMarket movements usually result from several interacting factors.\n\nA convincing explanation may be created after the price move without having genuine predictive power.\n\n### Fear and Greed\n\nFear and greed are often described as the dominant emotions in financial markets.\n\n### Greed\n\nGreed can cause participants to:\n\nIncrease risk after gains\n\nRefuse to take profit\n\nUse excessive leverage\n\nIgnore valuation\n\nAssume a trend will continue indefinitely\n\n### Fear\n\nFear can cause participants to:\n\nSell during panic\n\nAvoid strong assets after a decline\n\nabandon long-term plans\n\nAccept poor execution\n\nFollow rumours\n\nThe objective is not to remove emotion completely.\n\nIt is to prevent emotion from controlling position size and decision-making.\n\n### Social Media and Market Psychology\n\nCryptocurrency markets are strongly influenced by online communication.\n\nSocial platforms can spread:\n\nNews\n\nResearch\n\nRumours\n\nPromotions\n\nManipulation\n\nFear\n\nExcitement\n\nAlgorithms often promote emotionally engaging content.\n\nExtreme claims receive more attention than cautious analysis.\n\nA statement such as “this asset may offer moderate long-term potential with considerable risk” is less likely to spread than “this token will increase one hundred times.”\n\nPopularity should not be confused with accuracy.\n\n### Reflexivity and Self-Fulfilling Behaviour\n\nInvestor beliefs can temporarily influence reality.\n\nIf enough people believe a token will rise and buy it, the price may rise.\n\nThe rising price then appears to confirm the original belief.\n\nThis can create a self-reinforcing cycle.\n\nHowever, the cycle requires continued demand.\n\nWhen new buyers stop arriving, the price may decline sharply because the narrative was supported mainly by momentum rather than lasting value.\n\nReflexivity explains why prices can move far above or below conservative estimates of fundamental value.\n\n### Market Cycles Are Not Guaranteed Schedules\n\nParticipants often search for a simple timetable that predicts market peaks and bottoms.\n\nThis is dangerous.\n\nCycles may change because of:\n\nRegulation\n\nMacroeconomic conditions\n\nInstitutional participation\n\nTechnology\n\nMarket maturity\n\nLiquidity\n\nUnexpected crises\n\nAn event that influenced a previous cycle may have a different effect in the future because market participants already expect it.\n\nWhen everyone anticipates the same pattern, they may act earlier, changing the pattern itself.\n\nHistorical cycles provide context, not certainty.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,4,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-02-lesson-05','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Recognising Emotional Extremes and Key Takeaway','cmf-module-2-02','text','### Recognising Emotional Extremes\n\nNo single indicator confirms that a market has reached a peak or bottom.\n\nHowever, emotional extremes may be reflected through combinations of:\n\nRapid price acceleration\n\nExtreme leverage\n\nUnrealistic forecasts\n\nWidespread public attention\n\nRejection of risk\n\nPanic selling\n\nVery low market participation\n\nComplete loss of confidence\n\nThese conditions should encourage greater analysis.\n\nThey should not trigger an automatic opposite trade.\n\nExtreme optimism can persist longer than expected, and extreme pessimism can accompany genuine project failure.\n\n### A Disciplined Cycle Framework\n\nWhen assessing the market, ask:\n\n### Price Structure\n\nIs the market forming higher highs and higher lows?\n\nIs the trend weakening?\n\nAre recoveries failing?\n\n### Participation\n\nIs volume increasing or declining?\n\nAre new users entering?\n\nIs activity concentrated in speculative assets?\n\n### Liquidity and Leverage\n\nIs leverage unusually high?\n\nAre funding conditions extreme?\n\nAre market makers reducing liquidity?\n\n### Valuation and Fundamentals\n\nHas price risen faster than adoption?\n\nAre network activity and development improving?\n\nIs token supply increasing?\n\n### Psychology\n\nIs the dominant emotion fear, optimism, greed or despair?\n\nAre participants questioning risk?\n\nIs criticism being dismissed automatically?\n\n### Personal Behaviour\n\nAm I changing my plan because of price movement?\n\nAm I increasing risk after gains?\n\nAm I acting because others appear successful?\n\nThis framework promotes observation without pretending to identify the exact market phase with certainty.\n\n### Practical Ways to Manage Cycle Psychology\n\n\n\n### Use a Written Plan\n\nDefine:\n\nEntry conditions\n\nPosition size\n\nTime horizon\n\nReview points\n\nExit conditions\n\n### Limit Position Size\n\nA manageable position reduces emotional pressure.\n\n### Avoid Excessive Leverage\n\nLeverage can remove the ability to wait through ordinary volatility.\n\n### Take Decisions Gradually\n\nStaged buying or selling can reduce the pressure to identify one perfect price.\n\n### Maintain Independent Information Sources\n\nFollow both supportive and critical analysis.\n\n### Keep a Decision Journal\n\nRecord:\n\nWhy the decision was made\n\nWhat evidence supported it\n\nWhat risks were recognised\n\nWhat would invalidate it\n\n### Step Away From Constant Monitoring\n\nContinuous price checking can increase anxiety and impulsive decisions.\n\n### Review Fundamentals\n\nDo not allow price alone to determine whether the original investment case remains valid.\n\n### Common Misunderstandings\n\n#### “Market Cycles Repeat Exactly”\n\nCycles show broad behavioural patterns, not fixed schedules.\n\n#### “A Severe Decline Means the Bottom Has Arrived”\n\nWeak assets can continue falling or fail completely.\n\n#### “Rising Prices Prove That Fundamentals Are Improving”\n\nPrice may rise because of speculation, leverage or narrative momentum.\n\n#### “Everyone Is Buying, So the Asset Must Be Safe”\n\nHerd behaviour is often strongest near emotional extremes.\n\n#### “This Time Is Different”\n\nEvery cycle has unique characteristics, but human fear and greed remain influential.\n\n#### “Long-Term Holding Removes the Need to Review an Asset”\n\nThe project, technology and market can change.\n\n#### “A Profitable Trade Proves Skill”\n\nA favourable market cycle can temporarily reward poor decisions.\n\n#### “Selling Below My Purchase Price Is Always Wrong”\n\nThe purchase price is irrelevant if the future outlook has deteriorated.\n\n### Module Summary\n\nA market cycle is the movement of prices and investor behaviour through phases of expansion, euphoria, decline and recovery.\n\nCommon phases include:\n\nAccumulation\n\nExpansion\n\nPublic participation\n\nEuphoria\n\nDistribution\n\nDecline\n\nCapitulation\n\nRecovery\n\nThese phases are not fixed or guaranteed.\n\nCryptocurrency cycles are amplified by:\n\nMarket narratives\n\nSocial media\n\nLeverage\n\nLiquidity\n\nToken issuance\n\nRegulation\n\nHuman psychology\n\nImportant behavioural biases include:\n\nHerd behaviour\n\nFear of missing out\n\nLoss aversion\n\nAnchoring\n\nConfirmation bias\n\nRecency bias\n\nOverconfidence\n\nSurvivorship bias\n\nThe sunk-cost fallacy\n\nUnderstanding these patterns does not reveal the exact market peak or bottom.\n\nIt helps participants recognise when emotion may be replacing analysis.\n\n### Key Takeaway\n\nCryptocurrency market cycles are driven by more than technology, supply and demand.\n\nThey are intensified by human emotion.\n\nFear encourages selling when confidence is lowest. Greed encourages buying when risk may be highest.\n\nYou cannot control the cycle, but you can control your position size, research process and response to emotional pressure.\n\nThe next module is 2.4: Bull Markets, Bear Markets and Consolidation.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,5,0,0,0,'',NULL,5,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-02-lesson-06','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Check your understanding','cmf-module-2-02','text','### Check your understanding\n\nAnswer these questions to self-assess your understanding before moving on.\n\n1. What is a market cycle?\n\n2. What commonly occurs during the accumulation phase?\n\n3. How does investor psychology change during market expansion?\n\n4. What characteristics are commonly associated with euphoria?\n\n5. What is distribution?\n\n6. How can leverage accelerate a market decline?\n\n7. What is capitulation?\n\n8. Why are market cycles not reliable clocks?\n\n9. What is herd behaviour?\n\n10. How does fear of missing out affect decision-making?\n\n11. What is loss aversion?\n\n12. What is the disposition effect?\n\n13. How can anchoring influence an investor?\n\n14. What is confirmation bias?\n\n15. Why can several profitable trades create overconfidence?\n\n16. What is market reflexivity?\n\n17. Why should extreme optimism or pessimism not be used as an automatic trading signal?\n\n18. How can a decision journal improve discipline?','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,6,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `course_sections` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`position`,`created_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-03','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Module 2.3: Market Sentiment, Narratives and Evidence',3,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-03-lesson-01','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Education and Risk Note and Attention Is Not Conviction','cmf-module-2-03','text','### Education and Risk Note\n\nThis module teaches an analytical process. It does not recommend any asset, trade or investment strategy.\n\nSentiment data can be incomplete, delayed, manipulated or misunderstood. Social-media activity can include bots, paid promotion, coordinated campaigns and fraudulent impersonation. Search interest measures attention, not whether that attention is positive, informed or likely to produce buying.\n\nNo sentiment measure should be used as a stand-alone reason to commit capital.\n\n---\n\n### Learning Objectives\n\nBy the end of this module, you should be able to:\n\n- Define market sentiment without confusing it with price direction\n- Distinguish sentiment, attention, narrative, positioning and fundamental evidence\n- Explain how a market narrative develops, spreads and weakens\n- Evaluate search, social-media and sentiment data with appropriate caution\n- Recognise manipulation risks in thin or highly promoted crypto-asset markets\n- Combine several independent evidence categories into a balanced assessment\n- Document uncertainty and contradictory evidence instead of forcing a conclusion\n- Use a repeatable process that does not depend on one influencer, index or indicator\n\n---\n\n### Introduction\n\nThe previous module explained how market cycles interact with human behaviour. It examined fear, greed, loss aversion, anchoring, herd behaviour and other biases that can influence decisions.\n\nThis module addresses the next question:\n\n**How can we observe market mood without mistaking noise for evidence?**\n\nDigital-asset markets produce a continuous stream of posts, videos, search activity, headlines, price forecasts, memes and community discussion. A popular token can appear to have overwhelming support because the same claim is repeated across hundreds of accounts. A falling market can appear hopeless because negative messages receive more attention during stress.\n\nNeither volume nor confidence makes a statement true.\n\nThe objective of sentiment analysis is not to count excitement. It is to understand what participants appear to believe, how widely the belief has spread, whether real market behaviour supports it, and what evidence could disprove it.\n\nA disciplined analyst therefore separates five different ideas:\n\n1. **Sentiment** — the prevailing emotional or directional attitude.\n2. **Attention** — the amount of interest a topic is receiving.\n3. **Narrative** — the story used to explain why an asset or sector matters.\n4. **Positioning** — the exposure participants have actually taken.\n5. **Fundamentals** — evidence about use, economics, security and value capture.\n\nThese ideas can reinforce one another, but they are not interchangeable.\n\n---\n\n### What Is Market Sentiment?\n\nMarket sentiment is the combined attitude participants express toward an asset, sector or market.\n\nSentiment may be described as:\n\n- Optimistic or pessimistic\n- Confident or uncertain\n- Risk-seeking or defensive\n- Calm or fearful\n- Interested or indifferent\n\nSentiment is not directly visible. Analysts infer it from observable information such as surveys, commentary, search activity, price behaviour and positioning.\n\nThat inference contains uncertainty.\n\nTen thousand positive posts do not necessarily represent ten thousand independent people. One participant may operate many accounts. A community may reward positive commentary and discourage criticism. Automated accounts may repeat messages. Paid promoters may fail to disclose conflicts.\n\nSentiment should therefore be treated as an estimate rather than a fact.\n\n---\n\n### Sentiment Is Not Price Direction\n\nA rising price often improves sentiment, and positive sentiment can attract additional buyers. However, price and sentiment can diverge.\n\nPrice may rise while experienced participants become cautious. This can happen when liquidity is thin, leverage is increasing or a small number of transactions move the market.\n\nPrice may fall while long-term conviction remains stable. This can happen during broad risk reduction, forced liquidation or a temporary loss of liquidity.\n\nA single price movement cannot reveal why participants acted.\n\nThe analyst should ask:\n\n- Did spot participation broaden or narrow?\n- Was the movement supported by meaningful volume?\n- Did liquidity improve or deteriorate?\n- Did fundamental information change?\n- Did the move follow verified news or an unverified claim?\n- Was leverage expanding or being removed?\n\nSentiment provides context. It does not replace market, fundamental or risk analysis.\n\n---\n\n### Attention Is Not Conviction\n\nAttention measures how much a topic is being noticed.\n\nPossible attention measures include:\n\n- Search activity\n- Website visits\n- Social-media mentions\n- Video views\n- Newsletter coverage\n- App downloads\n- New account creation\n\nAttention can rise for many reasons.\n\nA protocol may have launched an important product. A token may have risen sharply. A security failure may have occurred. A public figure may have mentioned the project. A fraud investigation may have become public.\n\nThe same attention spike can therefore accompany enthusiasm, fear, curiosity or criticism.\n\nAttention data should answer:\n\n**Are more people examining the topic?**\n\nIt does not automatically answer:\n\n**Do they believe the asset is valuable?**\n\n---','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,1,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-03-lesson-02','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','What Is a Market Narrative? and Using Search-Interest Data','cmf-module-2-03','text','### What Is a Market Narrative?\n\nA market narrative is a simplified story that explains why a technology, asset or sector may become important.\n\nExamples could include:\n\n- A network becoming a settlement layer\n- Tokenisation moving traditional assets on-chain\n- A protocol creating a new source of financial yield\n- A scarce asset protecting purchasing power\n- A scaling technology making blockchains cheaper to use\n\nNarratives help people organise complex information. They can direct attention toward genuine technological or economic change.\n\nThey can also hide uncertainty.\n\nA strong narrative often compresses several assumptions into one memorable claim. The claim may overlook competition, supply growth, governance, legal constraints, security failures or the difference between network use and token-holder return.\n\nThe correct question is not whether the narrative sounds plausible.\n\nThe correct question is:\n\n**Which observable facts must become true for this narrative to create durable value?**\n\n---\n\n### The Narrative Lifecycle\n\nA narrative often moves through recognisable stages. These stages are not guaranteed and may overlap.\n\n### 1. Emergence\n\nA new technology, policy change or market development creates a possible theme.\n\nAt this stage, evidence may be limited. Discussion is concentrated among developers, researchers or specialist participants.\n\n### 2. Validation\n\nEarly evidence begins to support the theme. Products launch, users appear, infrastructure improves or credible institutions become involved.\n\nThe narrative becomes more than a proposal, although success remains uncertain.\n\n### 3. Diffusion\n\nThe story spreads to a wider audience. Media coverage, social discussion and market attention increase.\n\nSimplified versions of the narrative may replace the original technical explanation.\n\n### 4. Monetisation\n\nNew tokens, products or services are created around the theme. Capital and talent enter the sector.\n\nThis stage can produce genuine innovation and opportunistic imitation at the same time.\n\n### 5. Saturation\n\nThe narrative becomes widely accepted. Valuations may reflect optimistic future outcomes before those outcomes have occurred.\n\nProjects with weak economics may receive attention merely because they use the correct terminology.\n\n### 6. Fracture or Maturity\n\nEvidence begins to separate durable projects from promotional ones. The narrative may weaken after disappointments, or mature into a less dramatic but more useful technology category.\n\nThe narrative lifecycle should not be treated as a price forecast. It is a framework for asking which evidence should exist at each stage.\n\n---\n\n### Building an Evidence Ladder\n\nSentiment analysis becomes more reliable when information is ranked by how directly it relates to the question.\n\n### Level 1: Primary Evidence\n\nPrimary evidence comes closest to the underlying event or behaviour.\n\nExamples include:\n\n- Protocol code and official technical documentation\n- On-chain transactions and network data\n- Audited financial information\n- Official regulatory publications\n- Verified governance proposals\n- Actual market prices, spreads and traded volume\n\nPrimary evidence can still be misinterpreted, but it is generally more useful than commentary about what may have happened.\n\n### Level 2: Reputable Analysis\n\nThis includes research that explains its data, assumptions and limitations.\n\nUseful analysis should allow the reader to identify:\n\n- Who produced it\n- Which data was used\n- How the measure was calculated\n- Which conflicts may exist\n- What could make the conclusion wrong\n\n### Level 3: Public Commentary\n\nCommentary can reveal what people are discussing. It may identify a new theme before formal research exists.\n\nIt should not be treated as verified evidence merely because it is popular.\n\n### Level 4: Anonymous or Promotional Claims\n\nClaims without identifiable sources, disclosed methods or verifiable evidence belong at the lowest level.\n\nThey may still influence price. That makes them relevant to market risk, not reliable evidence of value.\n\n---\n\n### Using Search-Interest Data\n\nSearch data can help identify changes in public attention.\n\nGoogle explains that Trends data is sampled, anonymised, categorised, aggregated and normalised. Values are scaled relative to the selected place and period; they are not absolute search totals. Low-volume topics may also contain statistical noise.[1]\n\nThis creates several interpretation rules:\n\n- A value of 100 means peak relative interest in the selected comparison, not universal popularity.\n- Different time windows can produce different-looking charts.\n- Different regions with the same score may have different absolute search volumes.\n- A search spike does not reveal whether interest is positive or negative.\n- Low-volume terms may be too noisy for confident conclusions.\n\nA useful search analysis records the exact term, category, geography, time window and comparison set.\n\nWithout that context, the chart cannot be reproduced reliably.\n\n---','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,2,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-03-lesson-03','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Evaluating Social-Media Data and Manipulation and Thin Markets','cmf-module-2-03','text','### Evaluating Social-Media Data\n\nSocial-media analysis may consider:\n\n- Number of mentions\n- Unique contributors\n- Rate of change\n- Engagement\n- Positive and negative language\n- Network concentration\n- Repeated phrases\n- Account age and authenticity\n\nEach measure has limitations.\n\nEngagement can be purchased. One group can coordinate identical messages. Automated accounts can exaggerate activity. Sarcasm can confuse language models. A community may discuss a token mainly because its price has already moved.\n\nThe SEC warns that fraudsters can use social platforms to appear credible, hide behind anonymity and reach large audiences cheaply.[2] The CFTC has specifically warned that promoters can use messaging apps and online forums to organise pump-and-dump campaigns in thinly traded digital assets.[3]\n\nSocial activity should therefore be examined for authenticity and incentives, not merely counted.\n\nUseful questions include:\n\n- How many genuinely distinct contributors are present?\n- Is activity concentrated around a few accounts?\n- Are promoters paid or financially exposed?\n- Did discussion begin before or after the price move?\n- Are claims linked to primary evidence?\n- Are critical questions answered or removed?\n\n---\n\n### Sentiment Scores and Composite Indices\n\nA sentiment index combines several inputs into one score.\n\nInputs may include volatility, momentum, surveys, search activity or social data.\n\nThe convenience of one number creates risk.\n\nBefore using an index, identify:\n\n- Its exact inputs\n- The weight assigned to each input\n- How often it updates\n- Whether historical methods changed\n- Whether the data can be revised\n- Whether similar inputs are counted repeatedly\n\nIf an index combines price momentum, volatility caused by price movement and social discussion caused by the same price movement, the final score may look diversified while mostly measuring one event.\n\nAn index is a summary of a methodology. It is not an objective measurement of fear or greed.\n\n---\n\n### Positioning Is Not the Same as Opinion\n\nA participant can express optimism without owning an asset. Another participant can hold an asset while publicly expressing caution.\n\nPositioning concerns exposure rather than words.\n\nPossible positioning evidence includes:\n\n- Spot flows\n- Futures open interest\n- Funding rates\n- Options skew\n- Exchange balances\n- Stablecoin deployment\n- Concentration among holders\n\nThese measures require careful interpretation and will be studied more deeply later in the pathway.\n\nFor now, remember:\n\n**Opinion shows what participants say. Positioning shows part of what they have done.**\n\nNeither reveals the complete motive.\n\n---\n\n### Independent Confirmation\n\nA stronger assessment uses evidence from separate dimensions.\n\nSuppose a new blockchain narrative is gaining attention.\n\nEvidence could be organised as follows:\n\n1. **Attention:** Search interest and distinct public discussion are rising.\n2. **Use:** Verified network activity or paying users are increasing.\n3. **Economics:** Fees, revenue or another relevant value measure are improving.\n4. **Market participation:** Liquidity and spot participation are broadening.\n5. **Risk:** Leverage and concentration remain within defensible limits.\n\nFive social-media measures do not equal five independent confirmations.\n\nEvidence is independent when it comes from meaningfully different processes and could disagree with the other evidence.\n\n---\n\n### Contradictory Evidence Matters\n\nGood analysis actively searches for information that conflicts with the preferred conclusion.\n\nA narrative may be receiving more attention while:\n\n- Active use is declining\n- Token supply is expanding\n- Fees are falling\n- Liquidity is concentrated\n- Insiders are approaching an unlock date\n- Security concerns remain unresolved\n\nContradiction does not always make the narrative false. It should reduce confidence, change the time horizon or require a smaller risk budget.\n\nIgnoring contradictory evidence turns analysis into promotion.\n\n---\n\n### Manipulation and Thin Markets\n\nThin markets can move sharply when relatively little capital enters or leaves.\n\nThis makes them attractive targets for coordinated promotion.\n\nA simplified pump-and-dump sequence may involve:\n\n1. Organisers accumulate an illiquid token.\n2. Promotional accounts create urgency and apparent agreement.\n3. New buyers respond to the rising price and repeated claims.\n4. Organisers sell into the demand they helped create.\n5. Liquidity disappears and later participants struggle to exit.\n\nThe CFTC warns that these schemes can be organised through social channels and may complete rapidly.[3] South Africa''s FSCA has also warned about fraudulent investment schemes promoted through social platforms, impersonation and unrealistic return claims.[4]\n\nPossible warning signs include:\n\n- Guaranteed or unusually precise return claims\n- Pressure to act immediately\n- Undisclosed paid promotion\n- Anonymous organisers\n- Very low liquidity\n- Repeated copy-and-paste messages\n- Claims that criticism proves a conspiracy\n- No primary evidence supporting the story\n- Difficulty selling after buying\n\nMarket excitement does not remove fraud, liquidity or legal risk.\n\n---','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,3,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-03-lesson-04','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','A Repeatable Sentiment-and-Narrative Workflow and Module Summary','cmf-module-2-03','text','### A Repeatable Sentiment-and-Narrative Workflow\n\n### Step 1: State the Question\n\nAvoid asking whether the market is simply bullish or bearish.\n\nUse a testable question such as:\n\n**Has interest in this sector broadened beyond price-driven speculation into measurable use?**\n\n### Step 2: Define the Timeframe\n\nSentiment can change within hours, while adoption may develop over years. The timeframe determines which evidence matters.\n\n### Step 3: Record the Narrative\n\nWrite the narrative in one sentence without promotional language.\n\nThen list the assumptions required for it to create value.\n\n### Step 4: Collect Independent Evidence\n\nUse at least three different categories, such as attention, usage, economics, market participation and risk.\n\nRecord the data source and collection time.\n\n### Step 5: Check Authenticity and Incentives\n\nIdentify who produced each claim and how they may benefit.\n\n### Step 6: Search for Contradictions\n\nDocument evidence that weakens the narrative.\n\n### Step 7: Assign Confidence, Not Certainty\n\nUse a description such as low, moderate or high confidence and explain why.\n\n### Step 8: Define What Would Change the Assessment\n\nList the evidence that would strengthen, weaken or invalidate the conclusion.\n\nThis converts sentiment from a feeling into a reviewable analytical record.\n\n---\n\n### Worked Example: A Fictional Scaling Narrative\n\nAssume a fictional project claims that its network will become the leading low-cost settlement layer.\n\nSearch interest and social discussion have increased after its token price doubled.\n\nA weak assessment says:\n\n**Everyone is talking about it, so adoption must be growing.**\n\nA stronger assessment separates the evidence.\n\n### Attention\n\nSearch interest and distinct discussion increased, but most activity began after the price rise.\n\n### Use\n\nTransaction count increased. Further inspection shows that a small incentive programme generated much of the activity.\n\n### Economics\n\nFees remain low and do not yet cover the token incentives distributed to users.\n\n### Market Participation\n\nVolume increased, but liquidity remains concentrated on one venue.\n\n### Risk\n\nA large insider unlock is scheduled within three months.\n\nThe narrative may still succeed. The present evidence does not justify treating popularity as proven adoption.\n\nThe analyst records moderate attention, early use, weak economic validation, concentrated liquidity and significant supply risk.\n\nThis conclusion is less exciting and more useful.\n\n---\n\n### Sentiment Evidence Worksheet\n\nFor each assessment, record:\n\n### Question\n\nWhat exactly are you trying to determine?\n\n### Narrative\n\nWhat story is the market using to explain the opportunity?\n\n### Attention Evidence\n\nWhich search or discussion measures changed? Are they relative or absolute?\n\n### Behavioural Evidence\n\nWhat are users, holders or developers verifiably doing?\n\n### Economic Evidence\n\nWhich fees, revenue, supply or value-capture measures support the narrative?\n\n### Market Evidence\n\nIs participation liquid, broad and primarily spot-driven, or narrow and leveraged?\n\n### Contradictory Evidence\n\nWhich facts weaken the conclusion?\n\n### Data Limitations\n\nWhich labels, estimates, samples or proprietary methods could be wrong?\n\n### Confidence\n\nLow, moderate or high—with a written explanation.\n\n### Review Trigger\n\nWhat new evidence would require reassessment?\n\n---\n\n### Common Misunderstandings\n\n### “More Mentions Mean More Buyers”\n\nMentions can reflect criticism, bots, promotion or attention after a price move.\n\n### “A Search Score of 100 Means Everyone Is Interested”\n\nGoogle Trends values are normalised relative to the selected comparison. They are not absolute search totals.[1]\n\n### “Positive Sentiment Is Bullish”\n\nExtreme optimism can appear after substantial price appreciation, when expectations and positioning are already crowded.\n\n### “Negative Sentiment Means the Bottom Is Near”\n\nFear can persist, and deteriorating fundamentals can justify caution.\n\n### “Several Sentiment Indicators Provide Independent Confirmation”\n\nThey may all be transformations of the same price movement or social discussion.\n\n### “A Popular Narrative Proves Product-Market Fit”\n\nPopularity must be separated from sustained use and defensible economics.\n\n### “Influencers Are Independent Because They Disagree”\n\nDifferent accounts may share financial incentives, sponsors or information sources.\n\n### “On-Chain Activity Reveals Intent”\n\nIt records observable movements, not the full identity or motivation behind them.\n\n### “Sentiment Analysis Predicts Price”\n\nIt describes one part of the current environment. It does not remove uncertainty.\n\n---\n\n### Module Summary\n\nMarket sentiment describes the attitude participants appear to express toward a market or asset.\n\nAttention, sentiment, narrative, positioning and fundamentals are related but distinct.\n\nSearch and social data can reveal changes in interest. They cannot automatically reveal motive, conviction or future demand.\n\nNarratives help people understand complex developments, but they also compress assumptions and can spread faster than evidence.\n\nThe most useful analysis combines independent categories such as attention, use, economics, market participation and risk.\n\nContradictory evidence should be recorded rather than removed.\n\nSentiment indices must be understood through their inputs, weights, update rules and limitations.\n\nSocial activity can be manipulated, particularly in thinly traded assets. Urgency, guaranteed returns, anonymous promotion and poor liquidity are warning signs.\n\nA repeatable process begins with a clear question, defines the timeframe, records the narrative, collects independent evidence, checks incentives, searches for contradictions and identifies what would change the conclusion.\n\n---','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,4,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-03-lesson-05','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Key Takeaway and Source Register','cmf-module-2-03','text','### Key Takeaway\n\nSentiment is useful when it is treated as uncertain evidence rather than a prediction.\n\nThe analyst''s task is not to follow the loudest story. It is to determine who is paying attention, what participants are verifiably doing, which economics support the narrative, which risks remain hidden and what evidence would prove the current interpretation wrong.\n\n---\n\n### Source Register\n\nReviewed 21 July 2026. These sources support the module''s treatment of search-data limitations, social promotion, manipulation and retail-investor risk.\n\n1. [Google Trends Help — FAQ about Google Trends data](https://support.google.com/trends/answer/4365533?hl=en-GB)\n2. [U.S. SEC Investor.gov — Internet and Social Media Fraud](https://www.investor.gov/protect-your-investments/fraud/types-fraud/internet-and-social-media-fraud)\n3. [U.S. CFTC — Beware Virtual Currency Pump-and-Dump Schemes](https://www.cftc.gov/LearnAndProtect/AdvisoriesAndArticles/beware_virtual_currency_pump_dump.html)\n4. [South African FSCA — Public warning on impersonation and fraudulent investment schemes, 24 November 2025](https://www.fsca.co.za/News%20Documents/FSCA%20Press%20Release%20-%20FSCA%20public%20warning%20Surge%20in%20impersonation%20and%20fraudulent%20investment%20schemes.pdf)\n5. [FINRA — Social Media-Influenced Investing: Overview](https://www.finra.org/rules-guidance/key-topics/fintech/report/social-media-influenced-investing/overview)\n6. [BIS Working Paper 1049 — Crypto trading and Bitcoin prices: evidence from a new database of retail adoption](https://www.bis.org/publ/work1049.htm)\n7. [IOSCO — Investor Education on Crypto-Assets](https://www.iosco.org/library/pubdocs/pdf/IOSCOPD769.pdf)','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,2,0,0,0,'',NULL,5,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-03-lesson-06','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Check your understanding','cmf-module-2-03','quiz','### Scored knowledge check\n\nUse this check as a live analysis drill, not a memory quiz.\n\n### Case scenario\n\nA token named CoreLedger surged 42% in six days after one influencer described a “decentralised exchange upgrade” narrative before official announcements were finalized.\n\nIn the same week:\n\n- Google Trends interest rose sharply.\n- Social posts increased by 300%.\n- Futures open interest increased 35%.\n- Funding rates moved to an extreme reading.\n- A large unlock date was within 72 hours.\n- Spot volume was strong on one venue and weak on others.\n\nBefore judging the outcome, write down:\n\n1. What is attention versus conviction?\n2. What is the most likely role of each signal?\n3. Which signal can be manipulated or repeated quickly?\n4. Which evidence would invalidate a pure upside narrative?\n\nThe pass mark is 80%.\n\nThe goal is disciplined interpretation, not predicting the “obvious” future.\n','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,4,0,0,0,'',NULL,6,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
