INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-24-lesson-01','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','What Is Decentralised Finance? and Decentralised Applications','cmf-module-2-24','text','### Learning Objectives\n\nBy the end of this module, you should be able to:\n\nDefine decentralised finance\n\nExplain how DeFi applications use blockchains and smart contracts\n\nDistinguish between decentralised and centralised financial services\n\nIdentify the main categories of DeFi applications\n\nUnderstand the roles of wallets, collateral, liquidity pools, stablecoins and oracles\n\nExplain where DeFi yields may come from\n\nRecognise the importance of composability and permissionless access\n\nIdentify major DeFi risks, including smart contract, liquidation, governance and bridge risk\n\nEvaluate a DeFi protocol using a structured framework\n\nParticipate more cautiously in decentralised financial applications\n\n### Introduction\n\nTraditional financial services are generally provided through institutions such as:\n\nBanks\n\nStock exchanges\n\nBrokers\n\nPayment companies\n\nInsurers\n\nAsset managers\n\nClearing houses\n\nThese institutions maintain records, verify users, approve transactions and enforce contractual obligations.\n\nDecentralised finance, commonly called DeFi, attempts to provide some financial services through blockchain networks and smart contracts.\n\nDeFi applications may allow users to:\n\nExchange digital assets\n\nLend and borrow\n\nEarn staking or liquidity rewards\n\nCreate or use stablecoins\n\nPurchase tokenised assets\n\nAccess derivatives\n\nTransfer value across networks\n\nParticipate in protocol governance\n\nInstead of opening a conventional account, a user may connect a cryptocurrency wallet to a decentralised application.\n\nThe smart contracts then apply the protocol’s rules.\n\nThis can increase accessibility and transparency, but it also transfers greater responsibility to the user.\n\nThere may be no customer-service department able to reverse an incorrect transaction, restore a lost private key or reimburse funds lost through a faulty smart contract.\n\nDeFi replaces some institutional intermediaries with software.\n\nIt does not remove risk, trust or human influence.\n\n### What Is Decentralised Finance?\n\nDecentralised finance refers to blockchain-based financial applications that allow users to interact with digital assets through smart contracts.\n\nA DeFi protocol may provide rules for:\n\nAsset exchange\n\nLending\n\nBorrowing\n\nCollateral management\n\nInterest distribution\n\nLiquidation\n\nInsurance-like coverage\n\nAsset issuance\n\nGovernance\n\nThese rules are encoded in software and deployed on a blockchain.\n\nUsers generally interact directly from their wallets rather than transferring permanent custody to a conventional financial institution.\n\nHowever, the degree of decentralisation varies significantly between protocols.\n\nA project may be described as decentralised while still depending on:\n\nA small development team\n\nAdministrator keys\n\nCentralised price feeds\n\nOne website\n\nA concentrated governance token\n\nCentralised stablecoin issuers\n\nA limited group of validators\n\nDeFi should therefore be evaluated on a spectrum rather than treated as a simple decentralised-or-centralised category.\n\n### The Main Components of DeFi\n\nMost DeFi systems depend on several interconnected components.\n\nThese commonly include:\n\nA blockchain network\n\nSmart contracts\n\nUser wallets\n\nDigital assets\n\nLiquidity providers\n\nPrice oracles\n\nGovernance systems\n\nFront-end applications\n\nStablecoins\n\nBridges or interoperability tools\n\nA weakness in one component may affect the entire application.\n\nUnderstanding DeFi requires examining the full system rather than only the protocol’s advertised service.\n\n### Blockchain Networks\n\nA DeFi application is deployed on a blockchain that executes and records transactions.\n\nThe underlying network provides:\n\nTransaction ordering\n\nSettlement\n\nSecurity\n\nData availability\n\nSmart contract execution\n\nWallet ownership records\n\nA protocol inherits many risks from its blockchain.\n\nThese may include:\n\nNetwork congestion\n\nHigh transaction fees\n\nValidator centralisation\n\nChain reorganisations\n\nSoftware failures\n\nNetwork outages\n\nGovernance disputes\n\nA DeFi protocol can function correctly while the underlying blockchain experiences problems.\n\nThe protocol and network risks should therefore be analysed separately.\n\n### Smart Contracts\n\nA smart contract is software deployed on a blockchain.\n\nIt executes predefined rules when specified conditions are met.\n\nFor example, a lending smart contract may:\n\nAccept collateral from a user\n\nCalculate how much may be borrowed\n\nTrack interest\n\nMonitor collateral value\n\nPermit repayment\n\nLiquidate the collateral if required\n\nSmart contracts can reduce the need for manual processing.\n\nThey may also make transactions:\n\nTransparent\n\nConsistent\n\nAvailable continuously\n\nAutomatically settled\n\nHowever, smart contracts can contain:\n\nCoding errors\n\nEconomic design flaws\n\nIncorrect assumptions\n\nVulnerable administrative functions\n\nUnexpected interactions with other protocols\n\n“Code is law” does not mean code is always correct.\n\nIt means the deployed code may execute even when the outcome is harmful or unintended.\n\n### Decentralised Applications\n\nA decentralised application, or dApp, is a user-facing service that interacts with blockchain smart contracts.\n\nA dApp commonly includes:\n\nA website or mobile interface\n\nWallet connection functionality\n\nSmart contracts\n\nBlockchain data\n\nSupporting infrastructure\n\nThe visible website is not necessarily decentralised.\n\nA central team may control:\n\nThe domain\n\nThe interface\n\nThe server\n\nThe branding\n\nThe default settings\n\nEven when the website becomes unavailable, experienced users may still interact directly with the smart contracts.\n\nMost users, however, depend heavily on the front-end interface.\n\nThis creates an additional operational and security risk.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,1,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-24-lesson-02','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Cryptocurrency Wallets in DeFi and Decentralised Exchanges','cmf-module-2-24','text','### Cryptocurrency Wallets in DeFi\n\nA self-custodial wallet acts as the user’s identity and transaction-signing tool.\n\nWhen a wallet connects to a DeFi application, the protocol may recognise:\n\nThe wallet address\n\nToken balances\n\nPrevious activity\n\nProtocol positions\n\nGovernance rights\n\nThe wallet does not normally reveal the private key to the application.\n\nInstead, it signs transaction requests.\n\nConnecting a wallet does not always move funds.\n\nApproving and signing later transactions may grant the smart contract authority to use particular tokens.\n\nUsers must distinguish between:\n\nConnecting a wallet\n\nSigning a message\n\nApproving token spending\n\nConfirming an on-chain transaction\n\nEach action has different consequences.\n\n### Token Approvals\n\nMany token standards require users to approve a smart contract before it can transfer tokens from their wallet.\n\nAn approval may authorise:\n\nA specific amount\n\nAn unlimited amount\n\nOne token\n\nA collection of assets\n\nUnlimited approvals are convenient because the user does not need to approve every future transaction.\n\nThey also create risk.\n\nIf the approved smart contract is exploited or malicious, it may be able to transfer the approved tokens.\n\nUsers should:\n\nRead approval requests\n\nLimit approvals where practical\n\nReview old permissions\n\nRevoke unused approvals\n\nUse separate wallets for higher-risk activity\n\nAn approval is not a harmless technical formality.\n\nIt grants authority over assets.\n\n### Permissionless Access\n\nMany DeFi protocols are described as permissionless.\n\nThis means a user may be able to interact without:\n\nApplying for an account\n\nReceiving approval\n\nMeeting a minimum geographic requirement\n\nProviding conventional identity documents\n\nDepending on business hours\n\nA blockchain wallet and network access may be sufficient.\n\nPermissionless access can support:\n\nGlobal participation\n\nFinancial experimentation\n\nFaster product integration\n\nAccess for people underserved by conventional institutions\n\nHowever, legal restrictions, front-end controls and blockchain monitoring may still affect access.\n\nPermissionless does not mean consequence-free, anonymous or outside the law.\n\n### Non-Custodial Finance\n\nMany DeFi applications are non-custodial.\n\nThis generally means users retain control of their wallets and authorise transactions themselves.\n\nThe protocol’s smart contracts may temporarily or permanently hold deposited assets according to encoded rules.\n\nNon-custodial does not mean the assets remain entirely outside the protocol.\n\nWhen a user deposits tokens into a smart contract, they become exposed to:\n\nContract risk\n\nProtocol governance\n\nLiquidation rules\n\nOracle failures\n\nAsset restrictions\n\nThe user controls the wallet, but the deposited position operates according to the contract.\n\n### DeFi Versus Centralised Finance\n\nCentralised finance and DeFi use different operating models.\n\n### Centralised Finance\n\nA company may:\n\nMaintain user accounts\n\nHold customer assets\n\nApprove withdrawals\n\nSet lending terms\n\nMatch trades internally\n\nResolve disputes\n\nProvide customer support\n\nUsers trust the institution, its employees, systems and legal obligations.\n\n### Decentralised Finance\n\nA protocol may:\n\nRecord positions on a blockchain\n\nHold assets in smart contracts\n\nExecute predefined rules\n\nAllow direct wallet interaction\n\nDistribute governance through tokens\n\nUsers trust a combination of:\n\nSmart contract code\n\nBlockchain security\n\nProtocol economics\n\nOracles\n\nGovernance\n\nTheir own operational decisions\n\nDeFi changes where trust is placed. It does not eliminate trust.\n\n### Transparency\n\nDeFi can make certain information publicly observable.\n\nDepending on the protocol, users may inspect:\n\nSmart contract code\n\nWallet balances\n\nCollateral positions\n\nTransactions\n\nLiquidity pools\n\nGovernance proposals\n\nTreasury addresses\n\nThis transparency can support independent verification.\n\nHowever, public data does not guarantee that users understand what it means.\n\nImportant risks may remain hidden in:\n\nComplex code\n\nProxy contracts\n\nAdministrator permissions\n\nOff-chain agreements\n\nCentralised infrastructure\n\nUnverified identities\n\nMisleading dashboards\n\nTransparency provides evidence. It does not automatically produce safety.\n\n### Composability\n\nComposability describes the ability of DeFi protocols to connect and interact with one another.\n\nThis is sometimes described as money Lego.\n\nFor example, a user might:\n\nDeposit a base asset into a staking protocol\n\nReceive a liquid-staking token\n\nDeposit that token into a lending protocol\n\nBorrow a stablecoin\n\nPlace the stablecoin into a liquidity pool\n\nReceive another token representing the pool position\n\nEach step builds on the previous one.\n\nComposability enables rapid innovation.\n\nIt also creates interconnected risk.\n\nA failure in one layer may affect every protocol that depends on it.\n\n### DeFi Building Blocks\n\nCommon DeFi building blocks include:\n\nDecentralised exchanges\n\nLending markets\n\nStablecoins\n\nStaking systems\n\nDerivatives\n\nLiquidity pools\n\nAsset-management vaults\n\nInsurance-like protocols\n\nBridges\n\nOracles\n\nGovernance organisations\n\nDevelopers can combine these components to create new products.\n\nThe ease of integration can accelerate both useful innovation and systemic risk.\n\n### Decentralised Exchanges\n\nA decentralised exchange, or DEX, enables users to exchange digital assets through smart contracts.\n\nIt may use:\n\nAn automated market maker\n\nAn on-chain order book\n\nA hybrid model\n\nAggregated liquidity from several venues\n\nUsers generally trade from their own wallets.\n\nDEXs can provide access to a wide range of tokens without requiring a central exchange to list each asset.\n\nRisks include:\n\nMalicious tokens\n\nPoor liquidity\n\nSlippage\n\nSmart contract vulnerabilities\n\nFront-running\n\nFake interfaces\n\nDecentralised exchanges will be examined in the next module.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,2,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-24-lesson-03','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Automated Market Makers and Liquid Staking','cmf-module-2-24','text','### Automated Market Makers\n\nAn automated market maker, or AMM, enables trading against a pool of assets rather than requiring a direct buyer and seller to meet.\n\nLiquidity providers deposit assets into the pool.\n\nTraders exchange assets through a mathematical pricing formula.\n\nThe pool automatically adjusts the exchange rate as its asset balances change.\n\nAMMs allow markets to exist continuously.\n\nHowever, they can create:\n\nPrice impact\n\nSlippage\n\nImpermanent loss\n\nArbitrage opportunities\n\nSmart contract exposure\n\nLiquidity pools and AMMs will be explored in greater detail later in the course.\n\n### Lending and Borrowing\n\nDeFi lending protocols allow users to supply digital assets and earn interest.\n\nBorrowers may deposit collateral and borrow another asset.\n\nThe process may involve:\n\nDepositing collateral\n\nReceiving a borrowing limit\n\nBorrowing within that limit\n\nPaying variable interest\n\nMaintaining sufficient collateral value\n\nRepaying the loan to recover the collateral\n\nUnlike conventional consumer credit, DeFi borrowing is commonly overcollateralised.\n\nThe borrower deposits assets worth more than the amount borrowed.\n\n### Why DeFi Loans Are Often Overcollateralised\n\nA permissionless protocol may not know:\n\nThe borrower’s identity\n\nIncome\n\nCredit score\n\nEmployment\n\nLegal address\n\nAbility to repay from future earnings\n\nThe smart contract therefore protects lenders through collateral.\n\nSuppose a borrower deposits assets worth 15,000 units and borrows 10,000 units.\n\nIf the collateral falls too far in value, the protocol may liquidate it.\n\nOvercollateralisation reduces credit risk but limits access for people who do not already own valuable assets.\n\n### Collateral Ratios\n\nA collateral ratio compares the value of deposited collateral with the outstanding debt.\n\nThe simplified formula is:\n\nCollateral ratio = Collateral value ÷ Debt value × 100\n\nSuppose:\n\nCollateral value: 15,000\n\nDebt: 10,000\n\nCollateral ratio:\n\n15,000 ÷ 10,000 × 100 = 150 percent\n\nIf the collateral value falls to 12,000 while the debt remains 10,000, the ratio falls to:\n\n120 percent\n\nThe protocol may require liquidation before the ratio becomes dangerously low.\n\nExact calculations and thresholds differ between protocols.\n\n### Liquidation\n\nLiquidation occurs when a borrower’s collateral position no longer satisfies the protocol’s risk requirements.\n\nA liquidator may repay part of the borrower’s debt and receive collateral at a discount.\n\nLiquidation protects the protocol from bad debt.\n\nFor the borrower, it may result in:\n\nLoss of collateral\n\nA liquidation penalty\n\nRealised tax consequences\n\nRemaining debt in extreme cases\n\nForced sale during a market decline\n\nA position may be liquidated even if the user expects the collateral price to recover later.\n\nThe smart contract applies the current rules and prices.\n\n### Liquidation Cascades\n\nA liquidation cascade can occur when falling prices trigger many leveraged positions simultaneously.\n\nThe process may be:\n\nAsset prices decline\n\nCollateral ratios weaken\n\nProtocols liquidate positions\n\nCollateral is sold\n\nAdditional selling pushes prices lower\n\nMore positions become undercollateralised\n\nThis feedback loop can increase volatility.\n\nLiquidity shortages, oracle delays and network congestion may intensify the event.\n\nDeFi borrowing should therefore be evaluated under severe market conditions, not only normal volatility.\n\n### Flash Loans\n\nA flash loan is an uncollateralised loan that must be borrowed and repaid within one blockchain transaction.\n\nIf the borrower cannot repay by the transaction’s end, the entire transaction is reversed.\n\nFlash loans may be used for:\n\nArbitrage\n\nRefinancing\n\nCollateral swaps\n\nLiquidation\n\nComplex trading strategies\n\nThey demonstrate the programmable nature of DeFi.\n\nThey have also been used in attacks involving:\n\nOracle manipulation\n\nGovernance exploits\n\nWeak protocol economics\n\nLow-liquidity markets\n\nThe flash loan is often the funding mechanism rather than the underlying vulnerability.\n\n### Stablecoins in DeFi\n\nStablecoins are central to many DeFi applications.\n\nThey may be used for:\n\nTrading pairs\n\nLoans\n\nCollateral\n\nPayments\n\nLiquidity pools\n\nYield strategies\n\nAccounting units\n\nDifferent stablecoins may be backed by:\n\nCash and financial reserves\n\nCryptocurrency collateral\n\nAlgorithmic mechanisms\n\nHybrid structures\n\nStablecoins introduce risks including:\n\nDepegging\n\nReserve failure\n\nIssuer insolvency\n\nRegulatory intervention\n\nSmart contract flaws\n\nCentralised freezing powers\n\nA protocol may appear decentralised while depending heavily on centrally issued stablecoins.\n\n### Staking\n\nStaking involves committing assets to support a proof-of-stake blockchain or a related protocol function.\n\nParticipants may earn rewards for:\n\nValidating transactions\n\nDelegating to validators\n\nSupporting network security\n\nLocking assets for a specified period\n\nStaking is sometimes included within the broader DeFi category.\n\nHowever, native blockchain staking differs from depositing tokens into a separate yield protocol.\n\nRisks may include:\n\nSlashing\n\nValidator failure\n\nLock-up periods\n\nToken inflation\n\nSmart contract risk\n\nLiquid-staking-token depegging\n\nThe source of the reward should be understood clearly.\n\n### Liquid Staking\n\nLiquid staking allows users to stake assets while receiving a transferable token representing the staked position.\n\nThe liquid-staking token may be used in other DeFi protocols.\n\nThis improves capital flexibility.\n\nIt also creates additional layers of risk:\n\nStaking provider risk\n\nSmart contract risk\n\nValidator risk\n\nRedemption delays\n\nToken-price divergence\n\nDependency on secondary-market liquidity\n\nA liquid-staking token is not always equivalent to the underlying asset at every moment.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,3,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-24-lesson-04','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Yield Farming and Oracles','cmf-module-2-24','text','### Yield Farming\n\nYield farming generally refers to moving or allocating assets across DeFi protocols to earn rewards.\n\nRewards may come from:\n\nTrading fees\n\nBorrower interest\n\nStaking issuance\n\nProtocol incentives\n\nGovernance tokens\n\nLiquidity-mining programmes\n\nYield farming can involve several protocols and token layers.\n\nHigh advertised yields may be offset by:\n\nToken-price decline\n\nInflation\n\nImpermanent loss\n\nSmart contract exploits\n\nNetwork fees\n\nTax obligations\n\nUnsustainable incentives\n\nThe percentage yield is only one part of the return calculation.\n\n### Liquidity Mining\n\nLiquidity mining rewards users for supplying assets to a market.\n\nA protocol may distribute governance or incentive tokens to attract liquidity.\n\nThis can help a new protocol:\n\nLaunch markets\n\nReduce spreads\n\nIncrease total value locked\n\nAttract users\n\nHowever, incentive-driven liquidity may be temporary.\n\nWhen rewards decline:\n\nLiquidity providers may leave\n\nTrading conditions may deteriorate\n\nToken prices may fall\n\nThe protocol’s apparent growth may reverse\n\nA protocol should eventually create value beyond issuing new tokens to participants.\n\n### Where Does DeFi Yield Come From?\n\nA legitimate yield should have an identifiable source.\n\nPossible sources include:\n\n### Borrower Interest\n\nBorrowers pay for access to capital.\n\n### Trading Fees\n\nTraders pay fees to liquidity providers or the protocol.\n\n### Network Issuance\n\nA blockchain creates new tokens to reward validators or stakers.\n\n### Protocol Revenue\n\nUsers pay for a service, and part of the income is distributed.\n\n### Token Incentives\n\nThe protocol issues tokens to attract participation.\n\n### Real-World Income\n\nTokenised assets may generate interest, rent or other external cash flows.\n\nThe source affects sustainability.\n\nYield created mainly through token issuance may decline when:\n\nToken inflation becomes excessive\n\nMarket price falls\n\nNew demand weakens\n\nIncentive programmes end\n\n### Nominal Yield Versus Real Yield\n\nA nominal yield measures how many additional tokens are earned.\n\nA real economic return should also consider:\n\nToken-price changes\n\nInflation\n\nFees\n\nTaxes\n\nOpportunity cost\n\nSmart contract losses\n\nCurrency purchasing power\n\nSuppose a user earns twenty percent more tokens while the token’s price falls fifty percent.\n\nThe token balance increased, but the portfolio value declined.\n\nMore tokens do not necessarily mean greater wealth.\n\n### Annual Percentage Rate and Annual Percentage Yield\n\n\n\n### Annual Percentage Rate\n\nAPR generally expresses a simple annualised rate without assuming compounding.\n\n### Annual Percentage Yield\n\nAPY generally includes the effect of compounding.\n\nFor example, rewards reinvested frequently may produce an APY higher than the stated APR.\n\nHowever, DeFi rates frequently change.\n\nAn annualised figure based on a brief period can be misleading.\n\nA protocol displaying a high APY today does not promise that the rate will remain available for a year.\n\n### Variable Interest Rates\n\nDeFi lending and borrowing rates are often determined by supply and demand.\n\nWhen borrowing demand increases relative to supplied liquidity:\n\nBorrowing rates may rise\n\nLender returns may rise\n\nWhen supplied liquidity exceeds borrowing demand:\n\nRates may fall\n\nRates can change rapidly.\n\nA borrowing position that appears affordable may become expensive.\n\nA lending yield that appears attractive may decline soon after deposit.\n\nUsers should understand the rate model and stress-test substantial changes.\n\n### Vaults and Automated Strategies\n\nA DeFi vault pools user assets and applies an automated strategy.\n\nA vault may:\n\nReinvest rewards\n\nMove capital between protocols\n\nProvide liquidity\n\nBorrow against collateral\n\nHedge exposure\n\nOptimise fees\n\nVaults can simplify complex activities.\n\nThey also introduce additional risk because users depend on:\n\nVault smart contracts\n\nThe strategy design\n\nExternal protocols\n\nStrategy managers\n\nOracles\n\nAutomation systems\n\nA simple interface may conceal a highly complex chain of dependencies.\n\n### Synthetic Assets and Derivatives\n\nDeFi protocols may create tokens or contracts whose value tracks another asset.\n\nExamples may include exposure to:\n\nCryptocurrencies\n\nCommodities\n\nCurrencies\n\nInterest rates\n\nMarket indexes\n\nThese products may rely on:\n\nCollateral\n\nOracles\n\nLiquidation mechanisms\n\nArbitrage\n\nGovernance\n\nSynthetic assets can increase financial access.\n\nThey also create complex risks involving collateral quality, legal status and price-feed accuracy.\n\n### DeFi Insurance and Risk Coverage\n\nSome protocols offer insurance-like protection against specified events.\n\nCoverage may relate to:\n\nSmart contract exploits\n\nStablecoin depegging\n\nCustodian failure\n\nValidator penalties\n\nThe user may pay a premium in return for a potential claim.\n\nImportant questions include:\n\nWhat events are covered?\n\nWho decides whether a claim is valid?\n\nIs sufficient capital available?\n\nAre exclusions clear?\n\nIs payment automatic or discretionary?\n\nIs the insurer itself exposed to smart contract risk?\n\nThe word “insurance” should not be assumed to carry the same legal protections as a regulated insurance policy.\n\n### Oracles\n\nBlockchains cannot independently know external information such as:\n\nThe current market price of an asset\n\nInterest rates\n\nWeather\n\nSporting results\n\nReal-world asset values\n\nAn oracle provides external data to a smart contract.\n\nDeFi protocols often use price oracles to calculate:\n\nCollateral values\n\nBorrowing limits\n\nLiquidations\n\nDerivative settlement\n\nStablecoin backing\n\nAn incorrect or manipulated oracle can cause the protocol to execute harmful transactions even when the smart contract code functions as designed.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,4,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-24-lesson-05','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Oracle Risk and Smart Contract Risk','cmf-module-2-24','text','### Oracle Risk\n\nOracle risk may arise from:\n\nLow-liquidity price sources\n\nDelayed updates\n\nIncorrect configuration\n\nCentralised data providers\n\nManipulated markets\n\nNetwork congestion\n\nSoftware errors\n\nA robust oracle may use:\n\nMultiple data sources\n\nTime-weighted prices\n\nIndependent providers\n\nCircuit breakers\n\nFallback mechanisms\n\nA protocol’s security depends partly on the quality of the data it receives.\n\n### Governance Tokens\n\nMany DeFi protocols issue governance tokens.\n\nToken holders may be able to vote on:\n\nInterest-rate models\n\nCollateral assets\n\nFee structures\n\nTreasury spending\n\nProtocol upgrades\n\nIncentive programmes\n\nRisk parameters\n\nGovernance can distribute decision-making beyond the development team.\n\nHowever, voting power may be concentrated among:\n\nFounders\n\nEarly investors\n\nLarge funds\n\nDelegates\n\nExchanges\n\nTreasury-controlled wallets\n\nA protocol can be technically open while governance remains highly concentrated.\n\n### Governance Risk\n\nGovernance decisions can change the economic and security characteristics of a protocol.\n\nPotential risks include:\n\nMalicious proposals\n\nLow voter participation\n\nWhale control\n\nVote buying\n\nGovernance-token borrowing\n\nEmergency powers\n\nPoorly tested upgrades\n\nSome protocols use time delays before approved changes take effect.\n\nThis gives users time to review or withdraw.\n\nGovernance should be analysed as an active source of risk, not merely a community feature.\n\n### Administrator Keys\n\nA protocol may contain privileged functions controlled by administrator keys.\n\nThese powers may allow authorised parties to:\n\nPause the protocol\n\nUpgrade contracts\n\nChange fees\n\nAdd collateral\n\nFreeze activity\n\nRecover funds\n\nAlter risk parameters\n\nAdministrator powers can help respond to emergencies.\n\nThey can also create centralisation and abuse risk.\n\nQuestions include:\n\nWho controls the keys?\n\nIs a multisignature wallet used?\n\nHow many approvals are required?\n\nAre the signers independent?\n\nIs there a public time delay?\n\nCan users exit before changes take effect?\n\nA protocol described as decentralised may still depend heavily on a few administrators.\n\n### Multisignature Control\n\nA multisignature wallet requires several authorised parties to approve a transaction.\n\nFor example, a three-of-five arrangement may require any three of five signers.\n\nThis is generally safer than one person controlling an administrator key.\n\nHowever, multisignature security depends on:\n\nSigner independence\n\nKey protection\n\nGeographic distribution\n\nPublic identities\n\nCollusion risk\n\nReplacement procedures\n\nA multisignature wallet reduces single-key risk but does not automatically create decentralised governance.\n\n### Timelocks\n\nA timelock delays the execution of certain protocol changes.\n\nFor example, an approved upgrade may become active after forty-eight hours.\n\nThis can allow:\n\nSecurity researchers to inspect the change\n\nUsers to withdraw\n\nGovernance participants to object\n\nEmergency action if malicious code is detected\n\nTimelocks improve transparency and response time.\n\nThey are effective only when:\n\nThe delay is meaningful\n\nUsers are informed\n\nThe front end cannot hide the proposal\n\nEmergency authorities cannot bypass the delay without justification\n\n### Total Value Locked\n\nTotal value locked, or TVL, estimates the value of assets deposited in a DeFi protocol or ecosystem.\n\nIt may include:\n\nLending deposits\n\nLiquidity pools\n\nStaked assets\n\nVault balances\n\nCollateral\n\nTVL can indicate the scale of participation.\n\nHowever, it does not automatically measure:\n\nRevenue\n\nProfitability\n\nSecurity\n\nUser numbers\n\nLiquidity\n\nAsset quality\n\nTVL may also be distorted when:\n\nAsset prices rise\n\nThe same collateral is counted across several protocols\n\nIncentives attract temporary deposits\n\nThe protocol’s own token dominates the deposits\n\nTVL should be interpreted cautiously.\n\n### Protocol Revenue and Fees\n\nDeFi dashboards may distinguish between:\n\n### Trading or Usage Fees\n\nThe total amounts paid by users.\n\n### Protocol Revenue\n\nThe portion retained by the protocol or distributed to token holders.\n\n### Liquidity-Provider Revenue\n\nThe portion paid to capital providers.\n\nA protocol can generate high fees while its governance token captures little value.\n\nWhen evaluating a token, ask:\n\nWho receives the fees?\n\nAre rewards paid in newly issued tokens?\n\nDoes the token have a legal or technical claim?\n\nCan governance change the distribution?\n\nAre expenses and incentives sustainable?\n\nProtocol activity does not automatically create token-holder value.\n\n### Composability Risk\n\nWhen one protocol depends on another, the risks combine.\n\nSuppose a vault:\n\nAccepts a stablecoin\n\nDeposits it into a lending protocol\n\nBorrows another asset\n\nSupplies that asset to a liquidity pool\n\nUses an oracle from a third project\n\nBridges rewards to another blockchain\n\nThe user may be exposed to:\n\nStablecoin risk\n\nLending protocol risk\n\nLiquidation risk\n\nAMM risk\n\nOracle risk\n\nBridge risk\n\nVault strategy risk\n\nBlockchain risk\n\nThe advertised product may appear simple while the actual system is highly interconnected.\n\n### Smart Contract Risk\n\nSmart contract risk is the possibility that software fails or is exploited.\n\nPotential causes include:\n\nCoding errors\n\nAccess-control failures\n\nIncorrect arithmetic\n\nRe-entrancy vulnerabilities\n\nUpgrade errors\n\nEconomic exploits\n\nUnsafe integrations\n\nAn audit can reduce risk but cannot eliminate it.\n\nA protocol may have:\n\nSeveral audits\n\nA bug-bounty programme\n\nYears of operating history\n\nand still experience an exploit.\n\nRisk decreases through multiple protections rather than one security label.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,5,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-24-lesson-06','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Audit Limitations and Maximum Extractable Value','cmf-module-2-24','text','### Audit Limitations\n\nA smart contract audit examines code for potential weaknesses.\n\nBefore relying on an audit, ask:\n\nWhich contracts were reviewed?\n\nWas the final deployed version audited?\n\nWere serious issues resolved?\n\nHow experienced was the auditor?\n\nHas the protocol changed since the audit?\n\nDid the audit cover economic design?\n\nWas the report made public?\n\nAn audit is not insurance.\n\nIt is a professional review conducted within a limited scope and period.\n\n### Bug Bounties\n\nA bug-bounty programme rewards security researchers for responsibly reporting vulnerabilities.\n\nA meaningful programme may indicate that the project:\n\nEncourages external testing\n\nHas a process for disclosure\n\nAllocates resources to security\n\nRecognises that audits are insufficient\n\nThe bounty amount should be large enough to compete with the potential value of exploiting the vulnerability.\n\nEven a strong bounty cannot guarantee that every researcher will report the issue rather than use it.\n\n### Economic Exploits\n\nA protocol can lose funds even when the software executes exactly as written.\n\nAn attacker may exploit:\n\nWeak collateral rules\n\nManipulable prices\n\nIncentive design\n\nGovernance procedures\n\nThin liquidity\n\nIncorrect assumptions about user behaviour\n\nThese are economic or design exploits.\n\nSecurity analysis must therefore include both:\n\nCode safety\n\nEconomic mechanism safety\n\nCorrect code can implement a flawed system perfectly.\n\n### Stablecoin Risk\n\nA stablecoin used throughout DeFi may fail to maintain its intended value.\n\nThis can affect:\n\nLoans\n\nLiquidity pools\n\nCollateral\n\nVaults\n\nDerivatives\n\nProtocol treasuries\n\nIf a stablecoin depegs, automated systems may:\n\nLiquidate positions\n\nMisprice collateral\n\nCreate arbitrage\n\nSpread losses across protocols\n\nA stablecoin is not risk-free merely because its price has historically remained stable.\n\n### Impermanent Loss\n\nImpermanent loss may occur when a liquidity provider deposits two assets into an AMM and their relative prices change.\n\nThe pool automatically adjusts the quantity of each asset.\n\nCompared with simply holding the original tokens, the provider may end with:\n\nMore of the weaker-performing asset\n\nLess of the stronger-performing asset\n\nTrading fees and incentives may offset some or all of the difference.\n\nThe term “impermanent” can be misleading.\n\nIf the user withdraws while the price difference remains, the loss relative to holding becomes realised.\n\nImpermanent loss will be covered in more detail in Module 2.26.\n\n### Bridge Risk\n\nA blockchain bridge transfers or represents assets across different networks.\n\nBridges may use:\n\nLocked assets\n\nWrapped tokens\n\nValidators\n\nMultisignature wallets\n\nSmart contracts\n\nMessage-passing systems\n\nBridge failures have historically represented a major category of blockchain security risk.\n\nPotential problems include:\n\nContract exploits\n\nCompromised signers\n\nIncorrect messages\n\nAsset-backing failure\n\nCentralised custody\n\nDestination-chain failure\n\nA token received through a bridge may carry both asset and bridge risk.\n\n### Wrapped Assets\n\nA wrapped asset is a token representing another asset on a different network or within another protocol.\n\nFor example, a blockchain may use a wrapped form of an asset that is native elsewhere.\n\nThe wrapped token depends on a mechanism that preserves its backing.\n\nThis may involve:\n\nCustody\n\nSmart contracts\n\nBridges\n\nIssuers\n\nRedemption procedures\n\nA wrapped asset is not always equivalent in risk to the original asset.\n\nUsers should understand who or what maintains the connection.\n\n### Front-End Risk\n\nA legitimate protocol can be accessed through a compromised website.\n\nAttackers may:\n\nReplace wallet addresses\n\nRequest malicious approvals\n\nDisplay fake transaction information\n\nRedirect users to fraudulent contracts\n\nAlter domain records\n\nUsers should:\n\nVerify website addresses\n\nUse trusted bookmarks\n\nReview contract interactions\n\nAvoid links from unsolicited messages\n\nCheck announcements through several official sources\n\nA secure smart contract cannot protect a user who signs a malicious transaction through a fraudulent interface.\n\n### Wallet and Key Risk\n\nDeFi users control their own transaction authorisation.\n\nThis creates risks including:\n\nLost seed phrases\n\nCompromised private keys\n\nMalicious browser extensions\n\nFake wallet software\n\nAddress poisoning\n\nIncorrect network selection\n\nSigning unreadable messages\n\nSelf-custody offers control and responsibility together.\n\nA protocol cannot reverse a transaction signed by a compromised wallet simply because the user did not intend it.\n\n### Phishing and Social Engineering\n\nDeFi users are frequent targets of:\n\nFake airdrops\n\nFraudulent support accounts\n\nImpersonated governance websites\n\nMalicious token-approval requests\n\nCounterfeit applications\n\nFake security warnings\n\nScammers often create urgency by claiming:\n\nA wallet must be verified\n\nFunds are at risk\n\nA reward will expire\n\nA protocol migration is required\n\nThe user must reveal a seed phrase\n\nLegitimate support representatives should never require a seed phrase or private key.\n\n### Maximum Extractable Value\n\nMaximum Extractable Value, or MEV, refers to value that block producers, validators or specialised traders may obtain by influencing transaction ordering.\n\nPossible activities include:\n\nArbitrage\n\nLiquidations\n\nFront-running\n\nBack-running\n\nSandwich attacks\n\nIn a sandwich attack:\n\nAn attacker detects a pending trade\n\nTrades before it\n\nThe victim’s trade moves the price\n\nThe attacker trades again afterward\n\nThis can worsen the user’s execution price.\n\nHigh slippage settings and low-liquidity trades can increase exposure.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,6,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-24-lesson-07','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Network Fees and Failed Transactions and DeFi Safety Practices','cmf-module-2-24','text','### Network Fees and Failed Transactions\n\nDeFi transactions require blockchain fees.\n\nA user may pay fees for:\n\nToken approval\n\nDepositing\n\nBorrowing\n\nRepaying\n\nClaiming rewards\n\nWithdrawing\n\nRevoking permissions\n\nA transaction can fail while the network fee is still spent.\n\nHigh fees may make small positions uneconomic.\n\nBefore entering a DeFi strategy, calculate the full cost of:\n\nEntry\n\nPosition maintenance\n\nEmergency action\n\nExit\n\nA high nominal yield may not cover these costs.\n\n### Regulatory and Legal Risk\n\nDeFi operates across jurisdictions with different legal frameworks.\n\nPotential issues include:\n\nSecurities laws\n\nLending regulations\n\nTax reporting\n\nSanctions\n\nConsumer protection\n\nAnti-money-laundering rules\n\nDerivative restrictions\n\nStablecoin regulation\n\nA protocol may operate through decentralised contracts while its developers, governance participants or front-end operators remain subject to law.\n\nUsers may also have reporting and tax obligations.\n\nTechnical accessibility does not guarantee legal permission.\n\n### Protocol Failure and Recovery\n\nWhen a DeFi protocol loses funds, possible outcomes include:\n\nNo reimbursement\n\nPartial reimbursement\n\nTreasury compensation\n\nGovernance-approved recovery tokens\n\nLegal action\n\nNegotiation with the attacker\n\nProtocol closure\n\nRecovery depends on the protocol’s resources, governance and legal structure.\n\nThere may be no deposit insurance or guaranteed claims process.\n\nUsers should assume that smart contract losses may be permanent.\n\n### Emergency Pauses\n\nSome protocols include an emergency-pause function.\n\nIt may stop:\n\nDeposits\n\nWithdrawals\n\nBorrowing\n\nTrading\n\nContract interactions\n\nAn emergency pause can reduce losses during an exploit.\n\nIt also means a central or governance-controlled party may temporarily prevent access.\n\nThe feature involves a trade-off between:\n\nRapid security response\n\nDecentralisation\n\nUser access\n\nAdministrator power\n\nThe protocol should disclose who can activate it and under what conditions.\n\n### DeFi Risk Is Layered\n\nA DeFi position may contain several types of risk simultaneously.\n\nFor example, depositing a bridged stablecoin into a lending protocol may involve:\n\nWallet risk\n\nBlockchain risk\n\nStablecoin issuer risk\n\nBridge risk\n\nSmart contract risk\n\nOracle risk\n\nLiquidation risk\n\nGovernance risk\n\nFront-end risk\n\nRegulatory risk\n\nThe displayed interest rate does not describe these layers.\n\nThe return should be evaluated against the entire risk structure.\n\n### DeFi and Anonymity\n\nBlockchains may allow participation through wallet addresses rather than real names.\n\nHowever, transactions are commonly public and permanent.\n\nA wallet’s activity may be analysed using:\n\nTransaction history\n\nExchange records\n\nNetwork data\n\nAddress clustering\n\nPublic disclosures\n\nDeFi is often pseudonymous rather than truly anonymous.\n\nUsers should not assume that wallet activity cannot be connected to their identity.\n\n### Advantages of DeFi\n\nPotential advantages include:\n\n### Accessibility\n\nUsers may interact globally through a wallet and internet connection.\n\n### Transparency\n\nTransactions and contract balances may be publicly verifiable.\n\n### Programmability\n\nFinancial rules can be automated through smart contracts.\n\n### Composability\n\nProtocols can connect to create new services.\n\n### Continuous Operation\n\nBlockchains can operate outside conventional business hours.\n\n### Self-Custody\n\nUsers may retain control over transaction authorisation.\n\n### Innovation\n\nDevelopers can create and deploy new financial applications rapidly.\n\nEach advantage creates corresponding responsibilities and risks.\n\n### Limitations of DeFi\n\nPotential limitations include:\n\nTechnical complexity\n\nIrreversible transactions\n\nVolatile collateral\n\nHigh network fees\n\nLimited consumer protection\n\nSmart contract vulnerabilities\n\nPoor user interfaces\n\nUncertain regulation\n\nCentralised dependencies\n\nDifficult tax reporting\n\nLiquidity fragmentation\n\nDeFi is not simply a more efficient version of every traditional financial service.\n\nSome institutional functions exist to manage risks that software alone does not solve.\n\n### Assessing DeFi Decentralisation\n\nA decentralisation review may consider:\n\n### Smart Contract Control\n\nCan contracts be upgraded or paused?\n\n### Governance Distribution\n\nWho holds and votes with governance tokens?\n\n### Network Dependency\n\nHow decentralised is the underlying blockchain?\n\n### Oracle Design\n\nAre several independent data sources used?\n\n### Front-End Dependency\n\nCan the protocol be accessed without one website?\n\n### Developer Influence\n\nCan the founding team change essential parameters?\n\n### Treasury Control\n\nWho controls protocol funds?\n\nA protocol can be decentralised in one area and highly centralised in another.\n\n### Evaluating a DeFi Protocol\n\nA structured review may include the following areas.\n\n### Purpose\n\nWhat service does the protocol provide?\n\nIs there genuine demand?\n\n### Smart Contracts\n\nIs the code public?\n\nHas it been audited?\n\nCan it be upgraded?\n\n### Operating History\n\nHow long has the protocol operated?\n\nHas it survived volatile markets?\n\n### Team and Governance\n\nWho developed it?\n\nWho controls upgrades and treasury funds?\n\n### Economic Model\n\nWhere does yield come from?\n\nAre incentives sustainable?\n\n### Collateral and Liquidity\n\nWhich assets support the system?\n\nAre they liquid and reliable?\n\n### Oracles\n\nHow are prices obtained?\n\nWhat happens if the data fails?\n\n### Dependencies\n\nWhich stablecoins, bridges and external protocols are required?\n\n### Security\n\nAre there audits, bug bounties and emergency procedures?\n\n### User Exit\n\nCan funds be withdrawn under stress?\n\nAre lock-ups or queues involved?\n\n### DeFi Safety Practices\n\nUsers can reduce, but not eliminate, risk by:\n\nStarting with small amounts\n\nUsing a separate DeFi wallet\n\nVerifying contract addresses\n\nReading transaction prompts\n\nLimiting token approvals\n\nRevoking unused permissions\n\nAvoiding unknown links\n\nUnderstanding every protocol layer\n\nMonitoring collateral ratios\n\nMaintaining funds for network fees\n\nTesting withdrawals early\n\nAvoiding excessive leverage\n\nDiversifying protocol exposure\n\nKeeping records for tax purposes\n\nAssuming advertised yields can change\n\nThe appropriate response to a system that cannot be understood may be not to use it.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,7,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-24-lesson-08','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Testing With a Small Transaction and Common Misunderstandings','cmf-module-2-24','text','### Testing With a Small Transaction\n\nBefore depositing a significant amount, a user may:\n\nVerify the official application\n\nConnect a low-value wallet\n\nApprove only a small amount\n\nMake a small deposit\n\nConfirm the position appears correctly\n\nTest part of the withdrawal process\n\nReview the blockchain record\n\nA successful small test does not prove the protocol is safe.\n\nIt can identify operational mistakes before greater capital is exposed.\n\n### Separate Wallets for Separate Purposes\n\nA wallet structure may include:\n\n### Long-Term Storage Wallet\n\nUsed for assets that rarely interact with applications.\n\n### DeFi Wallet\n\nUsed for established protocol activity.\n\n### Experimental Wallet\n\nUsed for new or higher-risk applications with limited funds.\n\nThis separation can reduce the amount exposed if one approval or application is compromised.\n\nIt also adds record-keeping and recovery complexity.\n\nThe structure should remain secure and manageable.\n\n### DeFi Position Records\n\nA DeFi position record may include:\n\nProtocol\n\nBlockchain\n\nWallet address\n\nAssets deposited\n\nPosition size\n\nYield source\n\nCollateral ratio\n\nLiquidation level\n\nLock-up period\n\nSmart contract addresses\n\nToken approvals\n\nDependencies\n\nEntry date\n\nFees paid\n\nExit procedure\n\nTax information\n\nDo not record private keys, seed phrases or passwords in the position document.\n\nA clear record is especially valuable when a strategy involves several protocols.\n\n### A Basic DeFi Participation Process\n\n\n\n### Step 1: Define the Objective\n\nDetermine whether the goal is:\n\nTrading\n\nLending\n\nBorrowing\n\nStaking\n\nLiquidity provision\n\nLearning\n\n### Step 2: Understand the Protocol\n\nExplain in plain language:\n\nWhat is deposited\n\nWhat the protocol does\n\nWhere the return comes from\n\nHow funds are withdrawn\n\n### Step 3: Map Dependencies\n\nIdentify:\n\nBlockchain\n\nWallet\n\nStablecoin\n\nOracle\n\nBridge\n\nExternal protocols\n\n### Step 4: Review Security\n\nExamine:\n\nAudits\n\nBug bounties\n\nAdministrator powers\n\nUpgradeability\n\nOperating history\n\n### Step 5: Evaluate the Economics\n\nAssess:\n\nYield source\n\nToken inflation\n\nFees\n\nLiquidity\n\nCollateral requirements\n\n### Step 6: Model Adverse Scenarios\n\nConsider:\n\nAsset-price decline\n\nStablecoin depeg\n\nSmart contract exploit\n\nNetwork congestion\n\nWithdrawal delays\n\nLiquidation\n\n### Step 7: Determine Position Size\n\nAssume that the full amount exposed to a smart contract could be lost.\n\n### Step 8: Test With a Small Amount\n\nConfirm that deposits and withdrawals function as expected.\n\n### Step 9: Monitor the Position\n\nTrack:\n\nCollateral\n\nGovernance changes\n\nSecurity alerts\n\nRate changes\n\nToken approvals\n\n### Step 10: Maintain an Exit Plan\n\nKnow how to unwind the position before an emergency develops.\n\n### DeFi Evaluation Checklist\n\nBefore using a DeFi protocol, ask:\n\nWhat service does the protocol provide?\n\nWhy is a smart contract necessary?\n\nWhich blockchain does it use?\n\nWho developed and controls the protocol?\n\nCan contracts be upgraded or paused?\n\nWho controls administrator keys?\n\nHave the deployed contracts been audited?\n\nIs there an active bug-bounty programme?\n\nHow long has the protocol operated?\n\nWhere does the advertised yield come from?\n\nIs the yield based on real fees or token issuance?\n\nWhich assets must be deposited?\n\nWhat are their liquidity and stablecoin risks?\n\nIs borrowing or leverage involved?\n\nWhat is the liquidation threshold?\n\nWhich oracle provides prices?\n\nDoes the position depend on a bridge?\n\nWhich other protocols are involved?\n\nCan funds be withdrawn at any time?\n\nAre there withdrawal queues or lock-ups?\n\nWhat permissions will the wallet grant?\n\nCan those permissions be limited or revoked?\n\nWhat happens if the website becomes unavailable?\n\nWhat happens if the protocol is exploited?\n\nIs there any guaranteed compensation?\n\nHow much can be lost?\n\nIs the position size appropriate?\n\nHave transaction fees been included?\n\nWhat tax or legal obligations may apply?\n\nCan the full strategy be explained clearly without promotional language?\n\n### Common DeFi Mistakes\n\n\n\n### Chasing the Highest Yield\n\nThe participant compares percentages without analysing where the yield comes from.\n\n### Assuming Smart Contracts Remove Trust\n\nTrust remains in code, governance, oracles, developers and infrastructure.\n\n### Using One Wallet for Everything\n\nA malicious approval can expose a large portion of the user’s holdings.\n\n### Ignoring Token Approvals\n\nUnlimited permissions remain active after the immediate transaction.\n\n### Borrowing Too Close to Liquidation\n\nOrdinary volatility triggers forced collateral sales.\n\n### Ignoring Stablecoin Risk\n\nA stable asset is treated as equivalent to guaranteed cash.\n\n### Counting Incentive Tokens as Certain Profit\n\nThe reward token may decline rapidly or remain locked.\n\n### Relying Only on an Audit Badge\n\nThe scope, date and unresolved findings are not examined.\n\n### Ignoring Protocol Dependencies\n\nA failure in a bridge, oracle or external protocol damages the position.\n\n### Using a Protocol Without Testing the Exit\n\nThe user learns how withdrawals work only during an emergency.\n\n### Common Misunderstandings\n\n#### “DeFi Eliminates Intermediaries”\n\nIt replaces some institutions with smart contracts, validators, oracles, interfaces and governance systems.\n\n#### “Decentralised Means Nobody Controls the Protocol”\n\nAdministrator keys, developers or large token holders may retain significant control.\n\n#### “Non-Custodial Means My Funds Cannot Be Lost”\n\nAssets deposited into a vulnerable smart contract can still be stolen or locked.\n\n#### “A High APY Means a High Return”\n\nToken-price decline, inflation, fees and losses may outweigh the rewards.\n\n#### “Audited Means Safe”\n\nAn audit reduces certain risks but cannot guarantee security.\n\n#### “Overcollateralised Loans Are Risk-Free”\n\nCollateral can fall rapidly, oracles can fail and liquidations can produce bad debt.\n\n#### “Stablecoins Remove Volatility”\n\nThey add issuer, reserve, depegging and regulatory risks.\n\n#### “TVL Shows How Valuable a Protocol Is”\n\nTVL measures deposits, not necessarily revenue, security or sustainable demand.\n\n#### “Code Is Law Means the Rules Cannot Change”\n\nUpgradeable contracts and governance may alter the protocol.\n\n#### “Permissionless Means Anonymous and Unregulated”\n\nBlockchain activity may be traceable, and legal obligations can still apply.\n\n#### “Smart Contract Yield Is Passive”\n\nPositions may require continuous monitoring of rates, collateral, governance and security.\n\n#### “Small Network Fees Make Any Strategy Profitable”\n\nMultiple approvals, deposits, claims and withdrawals can make small positions uneconomic.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,8,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-24-lesson-09','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Module Summary and Key Takeaway','cmf-module-2-24','text','### Module Summary\n\nDecentralised finance uses blockchains and smart contracts to provide financial services involving:\n\nTrading\n\nLending\n\nBorrowing\n\nStaking\n\nLiquidity\n\nStablecoins\n\nDerivatives\n\nAsset management\n\nGovernance\n\nUsers commonly interact through self-custodial wallets.\n\nDeFi can provide:\n\nPermissionless access\n\nTransparency\n\nProgrammability\n\nContinuous operation\n\nComposability\n\nThese benefits also create greater individual responsibility.\n\nDeFi does not eliminate trust.\n\nIt relocates trust into:\n\nSmart contract code\n\nBlockchain security\n\nOracles\n\nGovernance\n\nAdministrator controls\n\nStablecoins\n\nUser wallets\n\nYields may come from borrower interest, trading fees, network issuance, protocol revenue or incentive tokens.\n\nThe source and sustainability of the yield must be evaluated.\n\nMajor risks include:\n\nSmart contract exploits\n\nLiquidation\n\nStablecoin failure\n\nOracle manipulation\n\nGovernance capture\n\nBridge failure\n\nFront-end attacks\n\nMalicious approvals\n\nNetwork congestion\n\nRegulatory uncertainty\n\nComposability can multiply both innovation and risk.\n\nA position using several protocols may contain many interconnected failure points.\n\nResponsible participation requires understanding the complete transaction, limiting position size, testing withdrawals, managing approvals and preparing for the possibility of total loss.\n\n### Key Takeaway\n\nDeFi can make financial services open, programmable and globally accessible.\n\nIt can also combine smart contracts, volatile collateral, oracles, governance systems, bridges and user-controlled wallets into one complex chain of risk.\n\nDo not judge a DeFi opportunity by its advertised yield.\n\nUnderstand the complete system, identify every dependency and expose only capital that can survive the failure of any one layer.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,2,0,0,0,'',NULL,9,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-24-lesson-10','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Check your understanding','cmf-module-2-24','text','### Check your understanding\n\nAnswer these questions to self-assess your understanding before moving on.\n\n1. What is decentralised finance?\n\n2. How does DeFi differ from centralised finance?\n\n3. What role does a blockchain play in a DeFi protocol?\n\n4. What is a smart contract?\n\n5. What is a decentralised application?\n\n6. What does a cryptocurrency wallet do when interacting with DeFi?\n\n7. What is a token approval?\n\n8. Why can unlimited approvals create risk?\n\n9. What does permissionless access mean?\n\n10. Does permissionless mean that no laws apply?\n\n11. What is non-custodial finance?\n\n12. What is composability?\n\n13. Why can composability create systemic risk?\n\n14. What is a decentralised exchange?\n\n15. What is an automated market maker?\n\n16. Why are many DeFi loans overcollateralised?\n\n17. How is a collateral ratio calculated?\n\n18. What is liquidation?\n\n19. How can a liquidation cascade develop?\n\n20. What is a flash loan?\n\n21. Why are stablecoins important to DeFi?\n\n22. How does liquid staking differ from ordinary token holding?\n\n23. What is yield farming?\n\n24. Where can legitimate DeFi yield come from?\n\n25. Why can a high nominal yield produce a negative economic return?\n\n26. How does APR differ from APY?\n\n27. What is an oracle?\n\n28. How can oracle failure damage a lending protocol?\n\n29. What is a governance token?\n\n30. What risks arise from administrator keys?\n\n31. What is the purpose of a timelock?\n\n32. What does total value locked measure?\n\n33. Why does TVL not prove protocol safety or profitability?\n\n34. What is smart contract risk?\n\n35. Why does an audit not guarantee security?\n\n36. What is an economic exploit?\n\n37. What is impermanent loss?\n\n38. What is bridge risk?\n\n39. How does a wrapped asset differ in risk from the original asset?\n\n40. What is front-end risk?\n\n41. What is maximum extractable value?\n\n42. Why should network fees be included in return calculations?\n\n43. What are the main factors in evaluating a DeFi protocol?\n\n44. Why should users test a protocol with a small amount?\n\n45. What information should be included in a DeFi position record?','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,10,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `course_sections` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`position`,`created_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-25','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Module 2.25: Decentralised Exchanges',25,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-25-lesson-01','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','What Is a Decentralised Exchange? and Connecting a Wallet','cmf-module-2-25','text','### Learning Objectives\n\nBy the end of this module, you should be able to:\n\nDefine a decentralised exchange\n\nExplain how DEXs differ from centralised cryptocurrency exchanges\n\nDistinguish between order-book, automated market maker and hybrid DEX models\n\nUnderstand how wallets, smart contracts and liquidity pools support decentralised trading\n\nExplain slippage, price impact and routing\n\nUnderstand how DEX aggregators search for improved execution\n\nIdentify token-approval, front-end, smart contract and liquidity risks\n\nRecognise common fraudulent-token and counterfeit-interface techniques\n\nExplain front-running, sandwich attacks and other transaction-ordering risks\n\nEvaluate a DEX before using it\n\nComplete a decentralised token swap more cautiously\n\n### Introduction\n\nA centralised cryptocurrency exchange usually operates through company-controlled accounts.\n\nUsers deposit assets with the exchange, place orders and depend on the company to:\n\nHold balances\n\nMatch trades\n\nProcess withdrawals\n\nMaintain records\n\nSecure private keys\n\nResolve operational problems\n\nA decentralised exchange, or DEX, uses blockchain-based smart contracts to facilitate cryptocurrency trading.\n\nInstead of depositing assets permanently into a company account, a user normally:\n\nOpens a self-custodial wallet\n\nConnects it to a decentralised application\n\nSelects the assets to exchange\n\nApproves the required smart contract permissions\n\nSigns the transaction\n\nReceives the purchased asset directly in the wallet\n\nA DEX can make token markets open and programmable.\n\nIt may allow almost any compatible token to be traded without receiving approval from a central listing committee.\n\nThis accessibility creates both opportunity and danger.\n\nA token appearing on a DEX has not necessarily been:\n\nAudited\n\nVerified\n\nApproved\n\nReviewed by a regulator\n\nEvaluated by the DEX operator\n\nConfirmed as legitimate\n\nDecentralised trading transfers much of the verification, custody and transaction responsibility to the user.\n\n### What Is a Decentralised Exchange?\n\nA decentralised exchange is a blockchain-based protocol that enables users to exchange digital assets through smart contracts.\n\nA DEX may use:\n\nLiquidity pools\n\nAutomated market makers\n\nOn-chain order books\n\nOff-chain order matching with on-chain settlement\n\nAggregated liquidity from several protocols\n\nA combination of these models\n\nUsers generally trade directly from self-custodial wallets.\n\nThe smart contracts determine:\n\nWhich assets can be exchanged\n\nHow prices are calculated\n\nWhich fees apply\n\nHow liquidity providers are compensated\n\nHow transactions are settled\n\nThe degree of decentralisation varies.\n\nA DEX may have decentralised settlement while relying on a central organisation for:\n\nThe website\n\nSoftware development\n\nContract upgrades\n\nFee settings\n\nToken lists\n\nGovernance\n\nEmergency controls\n\nThe word “decentralised” should therefore be analysed rather than accepted as an absolute description.\n\n### DEXs Versus Centralised Exchanges\n\n\n\n### Centralised Exchange\n\nA centralised exchange commonly provides:\n\nUser accounts\n\nInternal account balances\n\nCustodial storage\n\nOrder matching\n\nCustomer support\n\nPassword recovery\n\nIdentity verification\n\nFiat deposits and withdrawals\n\nThe exchange controls the infrastructure and often holds the private keys associated with customer assets.\n\n### Decentralised Exchange\n\nA DEX commonly provides:\n\nWallet-based access\n\nSmart contract settlement\n\nBlockchain-recorded transactions\n\nUser-controlled transaction signing\n\nPermissionless token markets\n\nContinuous on-chain operation\n\nThe user generally retains control of the wallet until a transaction is approved.\n\nHowever, assets supplied to a liquidity pool or other DEX contract become exposed to the contract’s rules and security.\n\n### Key Differences\n\n| Feature | Centralised Exchange | Decentralised Exchange |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Custody | Exchange often holds assets | User normally trades from a wallet |\n| Account | Company-controlled account | Blockchain wallet |\n| Trade settlement | Internal exchange records | Usually settled on-chain |\n| Token listing | Selected by the exchange | Often permissionless |\n| Identity checks | Commonly required | May not be required by the protocol |\n| Customer support | Usually available | Often limited or absent |\n| Transaction reversal | Sometimes operationally possible | Generally irreversible |\n| Transparency | Internal systems may be private | Contracts and transactions may be public |\n| Main trust | Company and custodians | Code, blockchain, liquidity and wallet security |\n\nNeither model is automatically safer.\n\nThey contain different risks.\n\n### Self-Custody and DEX Trading\n\nDEX users normally authorise trades using a self-custodial wallet.\n\nThe wallet holds or controls the keys required to sign transactions.\n\nA DEX does not normally need to know the user’s password or seed phrase.\n\nThe user should never enter a seed phrase into:\n\nA DEX website\n\nA support chat\n\nA token claim page\n\nA wallet-verification form\n\nA transaction-recovery service\n\nA legitimate DEX interaction requires transaction signatures—not disclosure of the private key or recovery phrase.\n\nSelf-custody gives the user greater control, but errors may be permanent.\n\n### Connecting a Wallet\n\nConnecting a wallet allows the application to view public information associated with the selected address.\n\nThis may include:\n\nToken balances\n\nTransaction history\n\nNetwork\n\nExisting protocol positions\n\nConnecting a wallet does not necessarily allow the application to transfer funds.\n\nHowever, the user may later be asked to approve token spending or sign transactions.\n\nThe main actions should be distinguished carefully.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,1,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-25-lesson-02','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Wallet Connection and AMM Pricing and Arbitrage','cmf-module-2-25','text','### Wallet Connection\n\nAllows the application to recognise the wallet address.\n\n### Message Signature\n\nMay prove wallet ownership or authorise a specific off-chain action.\n\n### Token Approval\n\nAllows a smart contract to spend a particular token.\n\n### Transaction Signature\n\nAuthorises an on-chain action that may transfer assets or change permissions.\n\nUsers should read each request rather than treating every wallet prompt as identical.\n\n### Token Approvals\n\nBefore exchanging many blockchain tokens, the user must approve the DEX smart contract to access the token being sold.\n\nThe approval may allow:\n\nOnly the amount required for one transaction\n\nA larger predefined amount\n\nUnlimited future spending of that token\n\nUnlimited approval can reduce future transaction costs and steps.\n\nIt can also increase exposure if:\n\nThe contract is exploited\n\nThe approval is granted to a fraudulent contract\n\nThe DEX is later compromised\n\nThe user forgets the permission exists\n\nWhere practical, users may limit approvals and revoke permissions that are no longer required.\n\nApproval transactions usually require a separate network fee.\n\n### How a DEX Trade Works\n\nA typical token swap may involve the following process:\n\nThe user selects the correct blockchain network\n\nThe wallet connects to the DEX interface\n\nThe user selects the token being sold\n\nThe user selects the token being received\n\nThe DEX calculates an estimated exchange rate\n\nThe user reviews fees, slippage and price impact\n\nThe user grants token approval if required\n\nThe user signs the swap transaction\n\nValidators or block producers process the transaction\n\nThe smart contract completes the exchange\n\nThe received token appears in the wallet\n\nThe transaction may fail if:\n\nThe price changes too much\n\nGas is insufficient\n\nSlippage tolerance is too low\n\nLiquidity is insufficient\n\nThe token contract restricts trading\n\nThe network is congested\n\nThe smart contract encounters an error\n\nA failed blockchain transaction may still consume a network fee.\n\n### Types of Decentralised Exchanges\n\nSeveral DEX structures exist.\n\nThe main models include:\n\nAutomated market makers\n\nOn-chain order-book exchanges\n\nOff-chain order matching with on-chain settlement\n\nDEX aggregators\n\nHybrid models\n\nEach model creates different liquidity, execution and operational characteristics.\n\n### Automated Market Makers\n\nAn automated market maker, or AMM, enables trading against a pool of assets.\n\nInstead of matching one buyer directly with one seller, the user trades with a smart contract containing liquidity.\n\nLiquidity providers deposit assets into the pool.\n\nThe AMM uses a mathematical rule to determine the exchange rate.\n\nAs traders buy one asset from the pool and add another, the pool balances change.\n\nThe price changes automatically.\n\n### A Simplified Constant-Product Model\n\nA common AMM model can be represented as:\n\nx × y = k\n\nWhere:\n\nx is the quantity of one asset\n\ny is the quantity of the other asset\n\nk is a value the pool attempts to maintain\n\nSuppose a pool contains:\n\n100 units of Asset A\n\n10,000 units of Asset B\n\nThe implied relationship is approximately:\n\n1 Asset A = 100 Asset B\n\nIf a trader buys Asset A from the pool:\n\nThe quantity of Asset A decreases\n\nThe quantity of Asset B increases\n\nAsset A becomes more expensive within the pool\n\nLarger trades change the pool ratio more significantly and therefore create greater price impact.\n\nThe real calculation includes fees and may differ according to the AMM design.\n\n### Liquidity Pools\n\nA liquidity pool is a smart contract containing assets available for trading.\n\nA pool may contain:\n\nTwo tokens\n\nSeveral tokens\n\nStablecoins\n\nAssets with related values\n\nAssets with very different volatility profiles\n\nThe pool’s depth influences:\n\nAvailable trading capacity\n\nSlippage\n\nPrice impact\n\nFee generation\n\nMarket stability\n\nA pool containing a large amount of valuable assets generally supports larger trades more efficiently than a shallow pool.\n\nLiquidity-pool mechanics will be explored in detail in Module 2.26.\n\n### Liquidity Providers\n\nLiquidity providers deposit assets into a pool so other users can trade.\n\nThey may receive:\n\nA share of trading fees\n\nProtocol incentive tokens\n\nA token representing the pool position\n\nGovernance rewards\n\nLiquidity providers face risks including:\n\nImpermanent loss\n\nSmart contract exploits\n\nToken-price declines\n\nIncentive-token inflation\n\nLiquidity withdrawal by other providers\n\nA DEX user depends on liquidity providers even when they never interact with them directly.\n\n### AMM Pricing and Arbitrage\n\nAn AMM’s internal price can differ from the price on other markets.\n\nArbitrage traders attempt to profit from this difference.\n\nFor example:\n\nAn asset is cheaper in the AMM pool\n\nAn arbitrage trader buys it from the pool\n\nThe trader sells it elsewhere\n\nThe pool ratio changes\n\nThe DEX price moves closer to the wider market price\n\nArbitrage helps keep decentralised market prices aligned with external markets.\n\nHowever, the process does not guarantee perfect pricing, particularly when:\n\nLiquidity is weak\n\nNetwork fees are high\n\nMarkets move rapidly\n\nBridges or exchanges are unavailable','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,2,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-25-lesson-03','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Concentrated Liquidity and Slippage','cmf-module-2-25','text','### Concentrated Liquidity\n\nSome AMMs allow liquidity providers to concentrate capital within selected price ranges.\n\nInstead of providing liquidity across every possible price, the provider may choose a narrower interval.\n\nPotential advantages include:\n\nGreater capital efficiency\n\nMore depth near the current price\n\nHigher fee potential\n\nPotential disadvantages include:\n\nActive management requirements\n\nLiquidity becoming inactive when price leaves the range\n\nGreater exposure to impermanent loss\n\nReduced market depth outside selected ranges\n\nA DEX may display high total liquidity while only part of it is active near the current trading price.\n\n### Stable-Swap AMMs\n\nStable-swap protocols are designed for assets expected to trade near similar values.\n\nExamples may include:\n\nDifferent stablecoins\n\nWrapped and underlying versions of an asset\n\nClosely related staking tokens\n\nTheir pricing formulas may provide lower slippage near the expected price relationship.\n\nHowever, if one asset loses its peg or backing, the pool may become imbalanced.\n\nLiquidity providers and traders can then become concentrated in the weaker asset.\n\nLow expected volatility does not remove asset or smart contract risk.\n\n### On-Chain Order-Book DEXs\n\nAn order-book DEX allows users to place bids and asks, similar to a traditional exchange.\n\nThe order book may be stored and executed directly on the blockchain.\n\nAdvantages may include:\n\nFamiliar limit-order functionality\n\nVisible bids and asks\n\nGreater price control\n\nAdvanced trading features\n\nLimitations may include:\n\nHigher transaction costs\n\nSlower order changes\n\nNetwork congestion\n\nExposure of orders to transaction-ordering strategies\n\nLess efficiency on blockchains with limited capacity\n\nHigh-performance blockchain networks may make on-chain order books more practical.\n\n### Off-Chain Matching and On-Chain Settlement\n\nSome DEXs match orders outside the blockchain but settle completed trades on-chain.\n\nThis model may provide:\n\nFaster order placement\n\nLower transaction costs\n\nImproved trading interfaces\n\nBlockchain-based settlement\n\nHowever, users may depend on centralised or semi-centralised systems for:\n\nOrder matching\n\nAvailability\n\nData\n\nSequencing\n\nThe protocol may be decentralised in settlement while retaining centralised operational components.\n\n### Hybrid DEXs\n\nHybrid exchanges combine features from several models.\n\nA hybrid DEX might use:\n\nAn off-chain order book\n\nOn-chain asset custody\n\nSmart contract settlement\n\nCentralised user interfaces\n\nDecentralised governance\n\nHybrid designs attempt to balance:\n\nSpeed\n\nLiquidity\n\nTransparency\n\nCost\n\nSelf-custody\n\nThe user should identify which elements are decentralised and which depend on a company or operator.\n\n### DEX Aggregators\n\nA DEX aggregator searches several decentralised exchanges or liquidity sources for an efficient route.\n\nThe aggregator may compare:\n\nExchange rates\n\nPool liquidity\n\nTrading fees\n\nNetwork costs\n\nSlippage\n\nPrice impact\n\nIt may divide one trade across several pools.\n\nFor example, a large trade could be routed:\n\n40 percent through Pool A\n\n35 percent through Pool B\n\n25 percent through Pool C\n\nThis may improve the average execution price.\n\n### Smart Order Routing\n\nSmart order routing determines how a trade should move through available markets.\n\nA direct route may exchange:\n\nToken A → Token B\n\nAn indirect route may produce a better result:\n\nToken A → Stablecoin → Token B\n\nA more complex route may involve several DEXs and intermediary assets.\n\nThe best quoted route should be evaluated after considering:\n\nNetwork fees\n\nSmart contract complexity\n\nExecution risk\n\nAdditional token approvals\n\nExpected minimum received\n\nA marginally better quote may not justify a significantly more complex route.\n\n### DEX Aggregator Risks\n\nAn aggregator introduces additional dependencies.\n\nThese may include:\n\nAggregator smart contracts\n\nRouting algorithms\n\nExternal DEX contracts\n\nToken approvals\n\nFront-end security\n\nPrice-estimation errors\n\nAn aggregator can improve pricing while increasing the number of contracts involved.\n\nUsers should confirm:\n\nWhich protocols will be used\n\nWhat approvals are required\n\nWhether the contracts are verified\n\nWhether the quoted savings exceed the additional costs\n\n### Price Impact\n\nPrice impact is the change in the exchange rate caused by the trade itself.\n\nIt becomes greater when:\n\nThe order is large\n\nThe liquidity pool is small\n\nThe market is imbalanced\n\nThe token is illiquid\n\nSuppose the displayed price suggests that 1,000 units of Token A should buy 10,000 units of Token B.\n\nA large order may receive only 9,200 units because the pool price changes during execution.\n\nThe difference reflects price impact and fees.\n\nA high price-impact warning should not be ignored merely because the transaction remains technically possible.\n\n### Slippage\n\nSlippage is the difference between the expected result and the actual execution.\n\nIt may arise because:\n\nOther trades occur first\n\nThe market moves\n\nLiquidity changes\n\nThe user’s order affects the pool\n\nTransaction processing takes time\n\nDEX interfaces commonly allow users to set a slippage tolerance.\n\nIf the final result falls below the minimum acceptable amount, the transaction may fail rather than execute at a worse rate.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,3,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-25-lesson-04','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Slippage Tolerance and MEV Protection','cmf-module-2-25','text','### Slippage Tolerance\n\nSuppose the quoted output is 1,000 tokens.\n\nWith a one-percent slippage tolerance, the transaction may require a minimum result close to 990 tokens.\n\nIf the expected output falls below this level before execution, the transaction may revert.\n\nA low tolerance may protect execution quality but create more failed transactions.\n\nA high tolerance may improve the chance of execution but expose the user to:\n\nPoor pricing\n\nSandwich attacks\n\nExtreme token taxes\n\nManipulated liquidity\n\nThe appropriate tolerance depends on:\n\nToken liquidity\n\nMarket volatility\n\nTransaction size\n\nNetwork conditions\n\nRepeatedly increasing slippage to force a suspicious trade through is dangerous.\n\n### Minimum Amount Received\n\nThe minimum amount received is the lowest token quantity the user accepts under the selected slippage tolerance.\n\nThis value should be reviewed before confirming the transaction.\n\nA user should compare:\n\nExpected output\n\nMinimum output\n\nValue in a familiar unit\n\nNetwork fee\n\nDEX fee\n\nPrice impact\n\nThe final decision should be based on the complete cost, not only the quoted exchange rate.\n\n### DEX Trading Fees\n\nA DEX transaction may contain several costs.\n\n### Protocol or Pool Fee\n\nPaid according to the DEX’s trading model.\n\nIt may go to:\n\nLiquidity providers\n\nThe protocol treasury\n\nGovernance participants\n\nToken-burning mechanisms\n\n### Network Fee\n\nPaid to the blockchain validators or block producers.\n\n### Price Impact\n\nCaused by the order relative to available liquidity.\n\n### Slippage\n\nCreated by market changes and execution conditions.\n\n### Aggregator Fee\n\nSome routing platforms charge an additional fee.\n\nThe total effective trading cost may be materially higher than the displayed protocol fee.\n\n### Network Fees\n\nEvery on-chain action may require a network fee.\n\nA complete DEX interaction may include:\n\nToken approval\n\nToken swap\n\nRevocation of approval\n\nBridging or withdrawal\n\nAdditional wallet transfers\n\nEach step can create a cost.\n\nDuring congestion, network fees may increase sharply.\n\nSmall trades can become uneconomic when transaction costs represent a large percentage of the position.\n\n### Gas Estimation\n\nWallets usually estimate the fee required for a transaction.\n\nThe user may sometimes select:\n\nA slower, lower-cost option\n\nA standard option\n\nA faster, higher-cost option\n\nIf the fee is set too low:\n\nThe transaction may remain pending\n\nLater transactions may be delayed\n\nThe trade may execute after market conditions change\n\nThe user may need to replace or cancel it\n\nFee management should be handled carefully, particularly on networks with variable congestion.\n\n### Failed Transactions\n\nA DEX transaction may fail because:\n\nSlippage limits were exceeded\n\nGas was insufficient\n\nThe contract rejected the trade\n\nThe token had unusual transfer rules\n\nLiquidity changed\n\nThe route became invalid\n\nA deadline expired\n\nThe blockchain still performed computational work.\n\nThe user may therefore lose the network fee despite receiving no tokens.\n\nRepeated failed transactions can materially increase the total cost of trading.\n\n### Transaction Deadlines\n\nSome DEXs include a transaction deadline.\n\nThe trade must execute before a specified time.\n\nThis can reduce the risk of an old pending transaction executing much later under unfavourable conditions.\n\nHowever, a very short deadline may increase failure rates during congestion.\n\nThe deadline and slippage tolerance together define important execution limits.\n\n### Maximum Extractable Value\n\nMaximum Extractable Value, or MEV, refers to value obtained by influencing transaction inclusion or ordering.\n\nBlockchain transactions may be visible before they are confirmed.\n\nSpecialised traders or block producers may use this information to:\n\nArbitrage price differences\n\nExecute liquidations\n\nTrade before or after other users\n\nReorder transactions\n\nSome MEV activity improves market efficiency.\n\nOther forms can produce worse execution for ordinary users.\n\n### Front-Running\n\nFront-running occurs when another participant detects a pending transaction and submits a competing transaction intended to execute first.\n\nFor example:\n\nA large DEX purchase becomes visible\n\nAnother trader buys before it\n\nThe original trade pushes the price higher\n\nThe first trader profits from the movement\n\nThe original user may receive fewer tokens than expected.\n\nTransaction privacy tools, protected routing and lower slippage limits may reduce some exposure.\n\n### Sandwich Attacks\n\nA sandwich attack surrounds a user’s transaction with two attacker transactions.\n\nA simplified sequence is:\n\nThe attacker detects a large pending buy order\n\nThe attacker buys first\n\nThe user’s trade executes and raises the price\n\nThe attacker sells immediately afterward\n\nThe user receives a worse exchange rate\n\nThe user’s broad slippage tolerance creates room for the attacker.\n\nSandwich-attack risk may increase when:\n\nLiquidity is weak\n\nThe trade is large\n\nSlippage tolerance is high\n\nThe transaction is publicly visible\n\nProtected execution is unavailable\n\n### MEV Protection\n\nSome wallets, DEXs and aggregators provide protected transaction routing.\n\nPossible mechanisms include:\n\nPrivate transaction submission\n\nEncrypted or hidden order flow\n\nBatch auctions\n\nIntent-based trading\n\nProtected remote procedure call services\n\nThese tools may reduce certain forms of front-running.\n\nThey introduce new dependencies and do not remove every execution risk.\n\nUsers should understand what protection is offered and which party processes the transaction.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,4,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-25-lesson-05','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Limit Orders on a DEX and Fake DEX Interfaces','cmf-module-2-25','text','### Limit Orders on a DEX\n\nSome DEXs support limit orders.\n\nA user specifies the price at which they are willing to trade.\n\nPotential benefits include:\n\nGreater price control\n\nReduced need to monitor continuously\n\nAvoidance of immediate market impact\n\nPotential limitations include:\n\nThe order may never fill\n\nPartial execution may occur\n\nNetwork fees may apply\n\nThe execution mechanism may rely on third-party keepers\n\nThe market may move away before confirmation\n\nA limit order manages price, not the quality or legitimacy of the token.\n\n### Stop and Conditional Orders\n\nMore advanced decentralised trading protocols may support:\n\nStop-loss orders\n\nTake-profit orders\n\nTrailing stops\n\nTrigger-based swaps\n\nPerpetual futures orders\n\nThese functions may rely on:\n\nOracles\n\nAutomation networks\n\nKeepers\n\nOff-chain triggers\n\nSmart contracts\n\nA conditional order is only as reliable as the entire execution system.\n\nDuring extreme volatility, the final price may differ substantially from the trigger price.\n\n### Token Contract Addresses\n\nToken names and symbols are not unique.\n\nAnyone may create a token using:\n\nThe name of a legitimate project\n\nA similar ticker symbol\n\nA copied logo\n\nFalse branding\n\nThe token contract address is the primary technical identifier.\n\nBefore swapping, confirm the address using reliable sources such as:\n\nThe project’s official documentation\n\nA reputable blockchain explorer\n\nA trusted token list\n\nSeveral verified official channels\n\nDo not rely only on:\n\nToken name\n\nLogo\n\nSearch-engine advertisement\n\nSocial-media message\n\nA link sent by a stranger\n\nBuying the wrong token is usually irreversible.\n\n### Counterfeit Tokens\n\nA counterfeit token may imitate a legitimate asset.\n\nPossible warning signs include:\n\nVery low liquidity\n\nRecently created contract\n\nNo verified official link\n\nUnusual transfer behaviour\n\nA large supply held by one wallet\n\nMissing or copied documentation\n\nInconsistent contract addresses\n\nThe DEX may display the token because its markets are permissionless.\n\nAppearance on the platform is not endorsement.\n\n### Honeypot Tokens\n\nA honeypot token allows users to buy but prevents or severely restricts selling.\n\nThe contract may contain malicious rules such as:\n\nOnly selected addresses may sell\n\nExtremely high selling taxes\n\nBlacklisting functions\n\nTransfer restrictions\n\nHidden administrator controls\n\nThe rising price can attract buyers because purchases occur while selling remains impossible.\n\nBefore trading an unfamiliar token, examine:\n\nContract code\n\nBuy and sell simulations\n\nExisting successful sell transactions\n\nHolder distribution\n\nAdministrator permissions\n\nIndependent security analysis\n\nAutomated scanners can help but may also fail to detect sophisticated contracts.\n\n### Transfer Taxes\n\nSome token contracts charge fees when tokens are transferred, bought or sold.\n\nThe fee may support:\n\nTreasury funding\n\nToken burning\n\nHolder rewards\n\nMarketing\n\nLiquidity\n\nIt may also be abusive.\n\nA token may impose:\n\nA moderate disclosed tax\n\nA changeable tax\n\nA very high selling tax\n\nA one-hundred-percent tax preventing exit\n\nDEX quotes may not always reflect unusual transfer mechanics correctly.\n\nUsers should understand the contract before increasing slippage to compensate.\n\n### Token Blacklists and Pausing\n\nA token contract may permit administrators to:\n\nFreeze addresses\n\nPause transfers\n\nChange fees\n\nRestrict trading\n\nMint additional tokens\n\nExclude selected wallets from restrictions\n\nThese functions may exist for regulatory or emergency reasons.\n\nThey may also enable abuse.\n\nThe user should determine:\n\nWhich powers exist\n\nWho controls them\n\nWhether they are limited\n\nWhether ownership has been transferred or renounced\n\nWhether renunciation claims are genuine and relevant\n\nA permissionless DEX cannot override restrictions coded into the token itself.\n\n### Malicious Approvals\n\nA fraudulent application may ask the user to approve a valuable token unrelated to the supposed transaction.\n\nOnce approved, the attacker may transfer the token from the wallet.\n\nWarning signs include:\n\nApproval requests for unexpected assets\n\nUnlimited permissions\n\nUnfamiliar contract addresses\n\nUrgent claims or migrations\n\nRequests to “verify” the wallet\n\nTransactions with unreadable or unexplained data\n\nThe wallet prompt should be reviewed before every approval.\n\n### Signature-Based Attacks\n\nNot every malicious action appears as an ordinary token transfer.\n\nA user may sign a message that authorises:\n\nA marketplace listing\n\nA token permit\n\nAn asset transfer\n\nAn order\n\nA broader delegated permission\n\nThe signature itself may not require a network fee, making it appear harmless.\n\nUsers should avoid signing messages they do not understand.\n\nA gas-free signature can still carry serious financial authority.\n\n### Fake DEX Interfaces\n\nAttackers may create counterfeit copies of well-known DEX websites.\n\nThe interface may look almost identical to the legitimate platform.\n\nThe fraudulent site may:\n\nRequest malicious approvals\n\nReplace destination addresses\n\nDisplay fake balances\n\nAsk for a seed phrase\n\nRedirect to malicious contracts\n\nSafer practices include:\n\nUsing a verified bookmark\n\nChecking the domain character by character\n\nAvoiding sponsored search links\n\nConfirming official links through several sources\n\nUsing a separate low-value wallet for experimentation','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,5,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-25-lesson-06','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Domain and Front-End Risk and Stablecoin Risk on DEXs','cmf-module-2-25','text','### Domain and Front-End Risk\n\nEven a legitimate DEX domain or interface may be compromised.\n\nPossible causes include:\n\nDomain hijacking\n\nWebsite-code compromise\n\nMalicious software updates\n\nFront-end developer attacks\n\nCompromised analytics or third-party scripts\n\nThe underlying smart contracts may remain secure while the interface directs users toward malicious transactions.\n\nExperienced users may verify contract addresses and transaction details independently.\n\nMost users should pause activity when the protocol reports front-end concerns.\n\n### Smart Contract Risk\n\nDEX contracts can be exploited through:\n\nCoding errors\n\nRe-entrancy\n\nIncorrect access controls\n\nArithmetic problems\n\nUpgrade vulnerabilities\n\nEconomic attacks\n\nOracle manipulation\n\nIntegration failures\n\nA mature DEX with substantial operating history may have lower relative risk than an unaudited new protocol.\n\nIt still cannot be considered risk-free.\n\nUsers may be exposed to the DEX contract only during a swap or for a longer period through token approvals and liquidity positions.\n\n### Upgradeable Contracts\n\nSome DEX contracts can be upgraded after deployment.\n\nUpgradeable designs allow developers to:\n\nFix vulnerabilities\n\nAdd features\n\nImprove efficiency\n\nRespond to network changes\n\nThey also create risks:\n\nMalicious upgrades\n\nCompromised administrator keys\n\nGovernance capture\n\nUnexpected rule changes\n\nUser inability to exit before implementation\n\nReview:\n\nWho controls upgrades\n\nWhether a multisignature is used\n\nWhether a timelock exists\n\nWhether changes are announced publicly\n\n### Emergency Controls\n\nA DEX may include powers to:\n\nPause trading\n\nDisable a pool\n\nBlock a token\n\nRestrict withdrawals\n\nChange fees\n\nRedirect protocol functions\n\nThese powers can protect users during an exploit.\n\nThey also demonstrate that operational control remains concentrated.\n\nThe existence of emergency controls is not automatically negative.\n\nThe important questions concern transparency, limits and who holds the authority.\n\n### Liquidity Risk\n\nA DEX market may appear active but contain limited actual liquidity.\n\nLow liquidity increases:\n\nPrice impact\n\nSlippage\n\nManipulation risk\n\nVolatility\n\nDifficulty exiting\n\nLiquidity can disappear if:\n\nProviders withdraw\n\nIncentives end\n\nA token loses value\n\nA smart contract concern emerges\n\nThe paired asset depegs\n\nUsers should review the specific pool, not only the DEX’s total liquidity.\n\n### Rug Pulls and Liquidity Removal\n\nA rug pull may occur when project creators or major liquidity providers withdraw valuable assets from a trading pool.\n\nToken holders may then be unable to sell except at extremely low prices.\n\nA liquidity lock may reduce immediate withdrawal risk.\n\nHowever, verify:\n\nWhich pool is locked\n\nHow much liquidity is locked\n\nWhen the lock expires\n\nWhether the team can create another pool\n\nWhether token minting remains possible\n\nWhether the paired asset has genuine value\n\nLocked liquidity does not prove that the token or project is legitimate.\n\n### Pool Imbalance\n\nA liquidity pool may become heavily imbalanced when traders prefer one asset over another.\n\nIn a stablecoin pool, this may indicate that participants are selling a stablecoin they no longer trust.\n\nThe pool may become filled with the weaker asset while the stronger assets are removed.\n\nA favourable exchange rate can therefore be a warning rather than an opportunity.\n\nUsers should investigate why a pool has become imbalanced before trading against it.\n\n### Oracle Risk on Advanced DEXs\n\nSimple AMMs derive prices from their internal asset balances.\n\nMore advanced DEXs and derivative platforms may use external price oracles.\n\nOracle failure can cause:\n\nIncorrect trade execution\n\nInvalid liquidations\n\nMispriced collateral\n\nProtocol losses\n\nUnfair settlement\n\nThe DEX’s design should explain:\n\nWhich oracle is used\n\nHow often prices update\n\nHow manipulation is prevented\n\nWhat happens when data becomes unavailable\n\n### Bridge and Wrapped-Asset Risk\n\nA DEX may trade assets that were bridged from another blockchain.\n\nThe wrapped token depends on:\n\nBridge security\n\nCustody\n\nValidator or signer integrity\n\nRedemption\n\nBacking reserves\n\nA bridged token can lose value relative to the original asset if the bridge is compromised or withdrawals become unavailable.\n\nThe DEX may continue quoting the token even when its backing is uncertain.\n\nConfirm whether the asset is native, wrapped or bridged.\n\n### Fake or Weak Wrapped Assets\n\nSeveral wrapped versions of the same asset may exist.\n\nThey may differ in:\n\nIssuer\n\nBridge\n\nCustody\n\nLiquidity\n\nRedemption rights\n\nSecurity\n\nA token symbol may not clearly communicate these differences.\n\nAlways verify the exact contract and backing mechanism.\n\nA cheaper wrapped token may be cheaper because market participants doubt its redeemability.\n\n### Stablecoin Risk on DEXs\n\nStablecoins are frequently used as DEX quote assets.\n\nIf a stablecoin depegs:\n\nToken prices quoted in it may appear distorted\n\nLiquidity pools may become imbalanced\n\nArbitrage may accelerate\n\nTraders may receive the weaker asset\n\nCollateral values may change\n\nA trade that appears profitable in stablecoin terms may lose value against national currency or another stable asset.\n\nCheck both assets in the trading pair.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,6,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
