INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-29-lesson-01','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','What Is a Layer 1 Blockchain? and Blockchain Throughput','cmf-module-2-29','text','### Learning Objectives\n\nBy the end of this module, you should be able to:\n\nDefine Layer 1 and Layer 2 blockchain networks\n\nExplain why blockchains face scalability constraints\n\nUnderstand the relationship between decentralisation, security and scalability\n\nDistinguish between execution, settlement, consensus and data availability\n\nExplain how sidechains differ from Layer 2 networks\n\nUnderstand the basic operation of optimistic and zero-knowledge rollups\n\nExplain transaction batching, state roots, fraud proofs and validity proofs\n\nIdentify bridges, sequencers and withdrawal mechanisms\n\nUnderstand the risks of wrapped and bridged assets\n\nCompare blockchain networks using security, cost, speed, liquidity and decentralisation\n\nRecognise fragmentation and interoperability risks\n\nSelect a network more carefully for a particular application or transaction\n\n### Introduction\n\nA blockchain may offer secure and decentralised settlement but still struggle to process large numbers of transactions quickly and cheaply.\n\nWhen activity increases, users may experience:\n\nHigher transaction fees\n\nSlower confirmations\n\nFailed transactions\n\nCompetition for block space\n\nReduced accessibility for small transactions\n\nDevelopers have created several methods to increase blockchain capacity.\n\nSome projects build entirely new base blockchains.\n\nOthers create additional systems that process activity away from the base chain while relying on it for part of their security or settlement.\n\nThese systems are commonly described as:\n\nLayer 1 networks\n\nLayer 2 networks\n\nSidechains\n\nRollups\n\nApplication-specific chains\n\nModular blockchains\n\nThe terminology is sometimes used inconsistently.\n\nA system may be marketed as a Layer 2 even when it relies heavily on separate validators or external data systems.\n\nThe important question is not only what the network calls itself.\n\nIt is:\n\nWhich functions does the network perform independently, which functions does it inherit, and what must users trust?\n\n### What Is a Layer 1 Blockchain?\n\nA Layer 1, or L1, is a base blockchain that operates its own consensus and records its own authoritative transaction history.\n\nA Layer 1 generally provides several core functions:\n\nTransaction execution\n\nConsensus\n\nSettlement\n\nData storage or availability\n\nNative asset issuance\n\nNetwork security\n\nExamples of Layer 1 designs may use:\n\nProof of work\n\nProof of stake\n\nVariations of Byzantine fault-tolerant consensus\n\nOther consensus mechanisms\n\nA Layer 1 normally has a native asset used for purposes such as:\n\nTransaction fees\n\nValidator or miner rewards\n\nStaking\n\nGovernance\n\nEconomic security\n\nApplications and tokens can be built directly on the Layer 1 if it supports programmable smart contracts.\n\n### Core Blockchain Functions\n\nTo compare Layer 1 and Layer 2 systems, it is useful to separate the main blockchain functions.\n\n### Execution\n\nExecution determines what transactions do.\n\nExamples include:\n\nTransferring tokens\n\nSwapping assets\n\nOpening a lending position\n\nUpdating a smart contract\n\nMinting a digital asset\n\n### Consensus\n\nConsensus allows network participants to agree on the valid order and history of transactions.\n\n### Settlement\n\nSettlement determines when transactions and state changes become authoritative and difficult to reverse.\n\n### Data Availability\n\nData availability ensures that the information required to verify the blockchain’s state can be accessed.\n\n### Storage\n\nStorage preserves transaction records, contract data and current blockchain state.\n\nTraditional Layer 1 blockchains may perform all these functions within one system.\n\nModular designs may distribute them across several layers.\n\n### The Blockchain Scalability Challenge\n\nA blockchain must allow many independent participants to:\n\nReceive transactions\n\nVerify rules\n\nStore data\n\nAgree on transaction order\n\nReject invalid activity\n\nThis creates computational and communication limits.\n\nA network could increase capacity by requiring validators to use more powerful hardware.\n\nHowever, higher hardware requirements may reduce the number of participants able to validate independently.\n\nThis can increase centralisation.\n\nScalability is therefore not only a software-performance problem.\n\nIt is also a governance, security and decentralisation problem.\n\n### The Blockchain Trilemma\n\nThe term blockchain trilemma describes the difficulty of maximising three characteristics simultaneously:\n\nDecentralisation\n\nSecurity\n\nScalability\n\n### Decentralisation\n\nA broad and diverse group can participate in validation and governance.\n\n### Security\n\nThe network resists fraud, attacks and invalid state changes.\n\n### Scalability\n\nThe network processes substantial activity quickly and affordably.\n\nA design that increases one characteristic may weaken another.\n\nFor example:\n\nLarger blocks may increase capacity but require more powerful hardware\n\nFewer validators may improve speed but reduce decentralisation\n\nStronger verification requirements may increase security but reduce throughput\n\nThe trilemma is a framework, not a mathematical law.\n\nDifferent systems make different trade-offs.\n\n### Blockchain Throughput\n\nThroughput describes how much activity a network can process during a period.\n\nIt may be measured through:\n\nTransactions per second\n\nComputation per second\n\nData processed per block\n\nUser operations completed\n\nValue settled\n\nSimple transaction counts can be misleading.\n\nOne complex smart contract transaction may require far more computation than one ordinary transfer.\n\nSome systems also combine many user operations into one on-chain transaction.\n\nComparisons should therefore consider what type of activity is being measured.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,1,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-29-lesson-02','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Latency and Finality and Layer 2 Security Inheritance','cmf-module-2-29','text','### Latency and Finality\n\n\n\n### Latency\n\nLatency is the time between submitting a transaction and receiving an initial confirmation or usable result.\n\n### Finality\n\nFinality describes when a transaction becomes extremely difficult or impossible to reverse under the protocol’s rules.\n\nA network may provide:\n\nFast initial confirmation\n\nSlower economic or protocol finality\n\nA user interface may show a transaction as completed before the strongest settlement guarantee has been reached.\n\nApplications involving large value may require more confirmation than low-value activities.\n\n### Block Space\n\nBlock space is the limited capacity available for transactions and data within a blockchain block.\n\nUsers compete for this capacity through transaction fees.\n\nWhen demand rises:\n\nFees may increase\n\nLower-fee transactions may wait\n\nApplications may become expensive\n\nSmall transactions may become uneconomic\n\nBlock space can be viewed as a scarce resource produced and secured by the network.\n\nLayer 2 systems attempt to use Layer 1 block space more efficiently by compressing or batching activity.\n\n### Scaling a Layer 1\n\nA Layer 1 can attempt to increase capacity through changes such as:\n\nLarger blocks\n\nShorter block times\n\nMore efficient execution\n\nParallel processing\n\nSharding\n\nImproved networking\n\nMore efficient consensus\n\nState compression\n\nThese approaches may improve performance.\n\nThey can also introduce trade-offs involving:\n\nHardware requirements\n\nValidator coordination\n\nSoftware complexity\n\nNetwork stability\n\nSecurity\n\nState growth\n\nThere is no single Layer 1 architecture that eliminates every trade-off.\n\n### Vertical Scaling\n\nVertical scaling improves the performance of individual network machines.\n\nIt may involve:\n\nFaster processors\n\nMore memory\n\nGreater storage\n\nHigher network bandwidth\n\nThis can increase throughput.\n\nHowever, if validation requires expensive infrastructure, fewer individuals may be able to run nodes.\n\nThe network may become more dependent on:\n\nData centres\n\nCloud providers\n\nProfessional operators\n\nLarge institutions\n\nA fast network is not necessarily decentralised.\n\n### Horizontal Scaling\n\nHorizontal scaling distributes work across multiple machines, chains or execution environments.\n\nPossible methods include:\n\nSharding\n\nParallel execution\n\nMultiple rollups\n\nApplication-specific chains\n\nInterconnected blockchain zones\n\nHorizontal scaling can expand capacity while keeping individual workloads manageable.\n\nIt also creates coordination and interoperability complexity.\n\nThe system must determine how separate components:\n\nCommunicate\n\nShare data\n\nTransfer assets\n\nResolve conflicting states\n\nMaintain security\n\n### Sharding\n\nSharding divides blockchain processing or data into separate parts called shards.\n\nInstead of every node processing every transaction, different groups may handle different subsets of activity.\n\nPotential benefits include:\n\nGreater parallel capacity\n\nReduced workload per participant\n\nImproved data availability\n\nPotential risks include:\n\nCross-shard communication complexity\n\nUneven security\n\nData reconstruction challenges\n\nMore complex validator coordination\n\nNew attack surfaces\n\nDifferent networks use the term sharding for different designs.\n\n### Monolithic Blockchains\n\nA monolithic blockchain performs most core functions within one integrated network.\n\nThese may include:\n\nExecution\n\nConsensus\n\nSettlement\n\nData availability\n\nPotential advantages include:\n\nSimpler user experience\n\nFewer external dependencies\n\nUnified liquidity\n\nDirect security model\n\nPotential disadvantages include:\n\nLimited scaling capacity\n\nHigher fees during congestion\n\nGreater state growth\n\nDifficult performance trade-offs\n\nMonolithic does not mean technically simple.\n\nIt means core blockchain functions remain combined within one primary system.\n\n### Modular Blockchains\n\nA modular blockchain design separates core functions across different systems.\n\nFor example:\n\nOne layer executes transactions\n\nAnother provides settlement\n\nAnother supplies data availability\n\nAnother provides consensus\n\nPotential advantages include:\n\nSpecialised optimisation\n\nGreater scaling flexibility\n\nMultiple execution environments\n\nReduced Layer 1 computation\n\nPotential risks include:\n\nAdditional dependencies\n\nBridge complexity\n\nFragmented liquidity\n\nNew data-availability assumptions\n\nMore difficult user analysis\n\nA modular system should be evaluated as a complete stack.\n\n### What Is a Layer 2 Network?\n\nA Layer 2, or L2, is a system built above a Layer 1 that processes transactions more efficiently while relying on the Layer 1 for one or more important security or settlement functions.\n\nA Layer 2 may:\n\nReceive user transactions\n\nExecute them outside the base chain’s normal execution process\n\nCombine or compress the results\n\nSubmit transaction data or commitments to the Layer 1\n\nUse the Layer 1 to settle disputes or verify correctness\n\nThe objective is to process more activity while consuming less Layer 1 block space per user transaction.\n\nNot every network connected to a Layer 1 is a true Layer 2.\n\nThe extent of inherited security must be examined.\n\n### Layer 2 Security Inheritance\n\nA Layer 2 is commonly expected to derive meaningful security from its underlying Layer 1.\n\nThis may include relying on the Layer 1 for:\n\nFinal settlement\n\nProof verification\n\nDispute resolution\n\nData publication\n\nAsset custody\n\nCensorship resistance\n\nA Layer 2 may still contain additional trust assumptions involving:\n\nSequencers\n\nProvers\n\nAdministrator keys\n\nGovernance\n\nData-availability committees\n\nBridges\n\nSecurity inheritance is rarely absolute.\n\nThe user should ask which failures the Layer 1 can prevent and which remain specific to the Layer 2.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,2,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-29-lesson-03','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Rollups and Validity Proofs','cmf-module-2-29','text','### Rollups\n\nA rollup processes many transactions outside normal Layer 1 execution and then submits compressed information to the Layer 1.\n\nThe Layer 1 may receive:\n\nTransaction data\n\nA state commitment\n\nA proof\n\nA batch summary\n\nBy combining many user transactions into one Layer 1 submission, the rollup distributes the Layer 1 cost across many users.\n\nThe two main rollup categories are:\n\nOptimistic rollups\n\nZero-knowledge rollups\n\nThey differ primarily in how they demonstrate that off-chain execution was correct.\n\n### Transaction Batching\n\nA batch combines many transactions into one submission.\n\nSuppose 5,000 user transactions are executed in a Layer 2.\n\nInstead of each transaction using a separate full Layer 1 transaction, the system may submit:\n\nOne compressed batch\n\nOne state update\n\nSupporting data\n\nThe Layer 1 fee is then spread across the users.\n\nBatching can reduce average transaction cost.\n\nActual savings depend on:\n\nLayer 1 fees\n\nBatch size\n\nCompression\n\nData requirements\n\nLayer 2 demand\n\nOperator pricing\n\nLow Layer 2 activity may reduce batching efficiency.\n\n### Blockchain State\n\nThe state is the current record of relevant blockchain information.\n\nIt may include:\n\nAccount balances\n\nSmart contract storage\n\nOwnership records\n\nOpen DeFi positions\n\nApplication data\n\nA Layer 2 executes transactions that change its state.\n\nIt then commits a representation of the updated state to the Layer 1.\n\nThis commitment allows the system to demonstrate that the Layer 2 has moved from one state to another.\n\n### State Roots\n\nA state root is a compact cryptographic commitment representing a much larger set of data.\n\nInstead of storing every balance inside one small value, the state root mathematically commits to the complete state.\n\nIf one balance changes, the resulting state root changes.\n\nState roots help Layer 1 contracts track Layer 2 updates efficiently.\n\nHowever, a state root alone does not explain whether the underlying transactions were valid.\n\nThe rollup must use a fraud-proof or validity-proof system.\n\n### Optimistic Rollups\n\nAn optimistic rollup generally assumes that submitted transaction batches are valid unless someone successfully challenges them.\n\nThe process is optimistic because it does not immediately prove every state transition through a validity proof.\n\nA simplified process is:\n\nA sequencer orders Layer 2 transactions\n\nThe transactions are executed\n\nA batch and state commitment are submitted to Layer 1\n\nA challenge period begins\n\nIndependent participants may identify an invalid transition\n\nA fraud-proof process resolves the dispute\n\nIf no successful challenge occurs, the state becomes final under the rollup’s rules.\n\n### Fraud Proofs\n\nA fraud proof demonstrates that a submitted optimistic-rollup state transition was invalid.\n\nA challenger may claim that:\n\nA transaction was executed incorrectly\n\nAn invalid state was accepted\n\nProtocol rules were violated\n\nThe Layer 1 contract then helps determine the correct result.\n\nAn effective optimistic rollup depends on at least one honest and capable participant monitoring the system and challenging fraud within the permitted period.\n\nThis creates an important assumption:\n\nInvalid activity must be detectable and challenged in time.\n\n### Challenge Periods\n\nThe challenge period is the time during which optimistic-rollup state updates can be disputed.\n\nIt may affect withdrawals from the Layer 2 to the Layer 1.\n\nA user withdrawing through the native bridge may need to wait until the challenge period ends.\n\nPotential consequences include:\n\nDelayed access to Layer 1 funds\n\nOpportunity cost\n\nExposure during the waiting period\n\nReliance on third-party liquidity providers for faster exits\n\nThe challenge period supports security but reduces withdrawal speed.\n\n### Fast Withdrawals\n\nThird-party bridge or liquidity services may offer faster withdrawals from an optimistic rollup.\n\nA provider may:\n\nGive the user funds on the destination chain immediately\n\nReceive the delayed native withdrawal later\n\nCharge a fee for the service\n\nThis reduces waiting time.\n\nIt introduces:\n\nCounterparty risk\n\nLiquidity risk\n\nBridge smart contract risk\n\nAdditional fees\n\nRoute complexity\n\nA faster withdrawal may rely on security assumptions different from the rollup’s native bridge.\n\n### Zero-Knowledge Rollups\n\nA zero-knowledge rollup, or ZK rollup, submits a cryptographic validity proof demonstrating that the new Layer 2 state was calculated according to the rules.\n\nA simplified process is:\n\nUsers submit transactions\n\nThe Layer 2 executes them\n\nA proving system creates a validity proof\n\nThe proof and required data are submitted to Layer 1\n\nThe Layer 1 verifies the proof\n\nThe state update is accepted\n\nThe Layer 1 does not need to re-execute every transaction.\n\nIt verifies the compact proof.\n\n### Validity Proofs\n\nA validity proof mathematically demonstrates that a computation satisfied defined rules.\n\nDepending on the proving system, the proof may show that:\n\nSignatures were valid\n\nBalances were sufficient\n\nState transitions followed protocol rules\n\nThe resulting state root was calculated correctly\n\nThe proof can be much smaller than the underlying computation.\n\nThis allows Layer 1 to verify large amounts of Layer 2 activity efficiently.\n\nThe security of the system depends on:\n\nCorrect circuit design\n\nSound cryptography\n\nSecure implementation\n\nReliable data availability\n\nProper verifier contracts','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,3,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-29-lesson-04','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Zero-Knowledge Does Not Always Mean Private and Validium','cmf-module-2-29','text','### Zero-Knowledge Does Not Always Mean Private\n\nThe term zero knowledge refers to a cryptographic proof property.\n\nIt does not automatically mean that all transaction details are hidden.\n\nA ZK rollup may publish transaction data publicly while using zero-knowledge proofs to verify correctness.\n\nPrivacy-focused systems may use related cryptography to conceal information.\n\nValidity and privacy are separate design choices.\n\n### Optimistic Versus ZK Rollups\n\n\n\n### Optimistic Rollups\n\nPotential advantages:\n\nSimpler compatibility with existing smart contract environments\n\nMature application infrastructure\n\nLess complex proving requirements\n\nPotential limitations:\n\nChallenge periods\n\nDelayed native withdrawals\n\nReliance on fraud monitoring\n\nPossible dispute complexity\n\n### ZK Rollups\n\nPotential advantages:\n\nCryptographic validity verification\n\nPotentially faster final settlement after proof acceptance\n\nStrong data compression\n\nNo ordinary fraud-challenge delay\n\nPotential limitations:\n\nComplex proof systems\n\nHigher proving requirements\n\nCircuit and compatibility challenges\n\nSpecialised prover infrastructure\n\nMore difficult upgrades\n\nBoth approaches contain trade-offs.\n\n### Sequencers\n\nA sequencer receives, orders and processes Layer 2 transactions.\n\nIt may provide users with fast preliminary confirmation.\n\nA sequencer can influence:\n\nTransaction ordering\n\nTransaction inclusion\n\nUser experience\n\nMEV\n\nTemporary censorship\n\nMany Layer 2 systems initially operate with one primary sequencer.\n\nThis may improve performance but creates centralisation risk.\n\nA Layer 2 can inherit settlement security from Layer 1 while still relying on a centralised ordering service.\n\n### Sequencer Censorship\n\nA sequencer may refuse or delay a user’s transaction.\n\nA well-designed Layer 2 may provide a mechanism for users to submit transactions through the Layer 1 directly.\n\nThis is sometimes described as a forced-inclusion mechanism.\n\nQuestions include:\n\nCan users bypass the sequencer?\n\nHow long does forced inclusion take?\n\nWhat fees apply?\n\nDoes the mechanism work if the front end is unavailable?\n\nCan administrators pause it?\n\nCensorship resistance should be evaluated operationally, not only theoretically.\n\n### Sequencer Downtime\n\nIf the sequencer stops operating:\n\nNew Layer 2 transactions may be delayed\n\nApplications may appear unavailable\n\nUsers may need Layer 1 fallback mechanisms\n\nTransaction ordering may pause\n\nWithdrawals may become more difficult\n\nAssets may remain secure while the network is temporarily unusable.\n\nAvailability and asset safety are different characteristics.\n\nA network can preserve funds but still fail to provide timely access.\n\n### Decentralised Sequencing\n\nSome Layer 2 designs aim to distribute transaction ordering among several participants.\n\nPotential benefits include:\n\nGreater censorship resistance\n\nReduced single-operator risk\n\nMore transparent MEV distribution\n\nImproved fault tolerance\n\nPotential challenges include:\n\nSlower coordination\n\nMore complex consensus\n\nNew token incentives\n\nAdditional validator requirements\n\nGovernance complexity\n\nSequencer decentralisation is a process rather than a simple switch.\n\n### Provers\n\nIn a validity-rollup system, provers generate cryptographic proofs.\n\nProof generation may require:\n\nSpecialised software\n\nSubstantial computation\n\nMemory\n\nHardware acceleration\n\nIf one prover dominates, the network may have operational centralisation even when anyone can theoretically verify the proof.\n\nQuestions include:\n\nCan several independent provers participate?\n\nWhat happens if the primary prover fails?\n\nCan users continue transacting?\n\nIs proof generation permissionless?\n\nAre incentives sufficient?\n\nVerification may be decentralised while proof production remains concentrated.\n\n### Data Availability\n\nUsers must be able to access enough data to reconstruct or verify the Layer 2 state.\n\nIf transaction data is unavailable, users may know that a state commitment exists without being able to determine their balances or construct withdrawals independently.\n\nData availability is therefore central to Layer 2 security.\n\nA rollup may publish data:\n\nDirectly to the Layer 1\n\nTo a specialised data-availability layer\n\nThrough a committee\n\nThrough another network\n\nThrough a hybrid system\n\nEach method creates different cost and trust assumptions.\n\n### On-Chain Data Availability\n\nWhen a rollup publishes its required transaction data to the Layer 1, it benefits from the Layer 1’s data availability and security.\n\nPotential advantages include:\n\nStronger ability to reconstruct state\n\nReduced dependence on external parties\n\nClearer security inheritance\n\nPotential disadvantage:\n\nHigher cost because Layer 1 data space is expensive\n\nRollup transaction fees are often strongly influenced by the cost of publishing data to the base chain.\n\n### Off-Chain Data Availability\n\nSome systems store transaction data outside the Layer 1.\n\nThis can reduce costs.\n\nHowever, users must trust that the data will remain available through:\n\nA committee\n\nExternal storage nodes\n\nA separate data-availability network\n\nAn operator\n\nIf data disappears, users may be unable to verify the state or withdraw independently.\n\nA system that uses external data availability may not have the same security as a fully on-chain rollup.\n\n### Validium\n\nA validium uses validity proofs for transaction correctness but stores data outside the base Layer 1.\n\nPotential advantages include:\n\nLower fees\n\nGreater throughput\n\nReduced Layer 1 data usage\n\nPotential risks include:\n\nData being withheld\n\nDependence on committees or external networks\n\nReduced ability for users to reconstruct state\n\nMore complex exit assumptions\n\nValidity proves that the computation followed the rules.\n\nIt does not automatically guarantee that users can access the required data.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,4,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-29-lesson-05','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Volition and Multisignature Governance','cmf-module-2-29','text','### Volition\n\nA volition system may allow users or applications to choose between:\n\nOn-chain data availability\n\nOff-chain data availability\n\nUsers seeking stronger security may pay more for on-chain data.\n\nUsers prioritising lower cost may choose external availability.\n\nThis flexibility can improve product design.\n\nIt also makes the risk model more difficult to understand because users on the same system may receive different guarantees.\n\n### Data-Availability Layers\n\nA specialised data-availability network focuses on publishing and distributing transaction data rather than executing every application.\n\nRollups may use such a network to reduce costs.\n\nPotential benefits include:\n\nScalable data capacity\n\nSpecialised infrastructure\n\nLower transaction fees\n\nPotential risks include:\n\nDependence on another validator set\n\nToken and governance risk\n\nNetwork outages\n\nBridge or message risk\n\nMore complex security assumptions\n\nThe rollup stack should be analysed across every layer it uses.\n\n### Rollup Bridges\n\nA native rollup bridge connects the Layer 1 and its Layer 2.\n\nIt may lock assets on the Layer 1 and issue or release corresponding assets on the Layer 2.\n\nFor a deposit:\n\nThe user sends an asset to the Layer 1 bridge contract\n\nThe contract locks or records the asset\n\nThe Layer 2 credits the user\n\nFor a withdrawal:\n\nThe Layer 2 records the withdrawal request\n\nThe rollup proves or finalises the state\n\nThe Layer 1 bridge releases the asset\n\nThe native bridge is a critical security component.\n\n### Canonical Assets\n\nA canonical asset is the officially recognised representation of a Layer 1 asset on a Layer 2.\n\nIt is usually created through the network’s native bridge.\n\nHowever, multiple versions of the same asset may exist on one Layer 2.\n\nThese may include:\n\nCanonical bridged token\n\nThird-party bridged token\n\nWrapped token\n\nExchange-issued token\n\nSynthetic token\n\nThey may have similar names and different contract addresses.\n\nThe user must verify which version is being used.\n\n### Third-Party Bridges\n\nA third-party bridge transfers assets between networks using a mechanism outside the native rollup bridge.\n\nPotential benefits include:\n\nFaster transfers\n\nMore supported networks\n\nImproved routing\n\nGreater convenience\n\nPotential risks include:\n\nSeparate validator or signer set\n\nSmart contract exploits\n\nLiquidity shortages\n\nWrapped-asset failure\n\nIncorrect message delivery\n\nCentralised custody\n\nA Layer 2 may be secure while a third-party bridge used to reach it is compromised.\n\n### Bridge Liquidity\n\nSome bridges provide transfers through liquidity pools.\n\nA liquidity provider supplies assets on several networks.\n\nThe user deposits on one chain and receives from a pool on another.\n\nThis can provide faster settlement.\n\nIt introduces:\n\nPool liquidity risk\n\nRebalancing risk\n\nProvider incentives\n\nSmart contract risk\n\nPrice and stablecoin risk\n\nA bridge quote should include:\n\nFee\n\nExchange rate\n\nMinimum received\n\nDestination asset\n\nContract route\n\nEstimated settlement time\n\n### Wrapped and Bridged Asset Risk\n\nA bridged token is a claim on or representation of another asset.\n\nIts value depends on:\n\nBridge security\n\nBacking assets\n\nRedemption\n\nCustody\n\nSigner integrity\n\nDestination-chain liquidity\n\nIf the bridge is compromised, the bridged token may lose value even though the original asset remains secure on its native network.\n\nThe user owns the representation, not necessarily the original asset directly.\n\n### Layer 2 Withdrawal Risk\n\nA Layer 2 withdrawal may be affected by:\n\nChallenge periods\n\nProof delays\n\nSequencer downtime\n\nBridge pauses\n\nNetwork congestion\n\nAdministrator action\n\nLiquidity shortages in fast bridges\n\nIncorrect destination addresses\n\nBefore moving substantial value, users should understand both:\n\nHow to enter\n\nHow to exit through the most secure available route\n\nEasy deposits can conceal difficult withdrawals.\n\n### Escape Hatches\n\nAn escape hatch is a mechanism intended to let users recover or withdraw funds when the normal Layer 2 operator is unavailable.\n\nIt may allow users to:\n\nSubmit transactions directly through Layer 1\n\nProve ownership\n\nForce state inclusion\n\nExit from a known state\n\nThe practical value depends on:\n\nData availability\n\nContract functionality\n\nUser knowledge\n\nLayer 1 fees\n\nWhether the system can be paused\n\nAvailability of supporting software\n\nAn escape mechanism that ordinary users cannot operate may provide limited practical protection.\n\n### Administrator Keys\n\nLayer 2 systems may use administrator keys to:\n\nUpgrade contracts\n\nPause bridges\n\nChange sequencers\n\nCorrect bugs\n\nModify proof systems\n\nControl emergency functions\n\nThese powers may be necessary during early development.\n\nThey also create risks involving:\n\nKey compromise\n\nMalicious upgrades\n\nGovernance capture\n\nUnexpected freezing\n\nReduced security inheritance\n\nUsers should understand whether administrators can access, freeze or redirect assets.\n\n### Multisignature Governance\n\nAdministrator powers may be controlled by a multisignature wallet.\n\nFor example, several signers may need to approve an upgrade.\n\nThis reduces single-key risk.\n\nIt does not eliminate:\n\nSigner collusion\n\nCompromised devices\n\nShared organisational control\n\nLegal pressure\n\nPoor transparency\n\nReview:\n\nNumber of signers\n\nRequired approvals\n\nSigner independence\n\nTimelock duration\n\nPublic monitoring','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,5,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-29-lesson-06','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Timelocks and Layer 3 Networks','cmf-module-2-29','text','### Timelocks\n\nA timelock delays contract upgrades or governance actions.\n\nThis may allow users to:\n\nReview the proposed change\n\nWithdraw funds\n\nRaise security concerns\n\nPrepare for new rules\n\nA meaningful timelock improves user protection.\n\nHowever, emergency functions may bypass it.\n\nUsers should determine:\n\nWhich actions are delayed\n\nWhich can occur immediately\n\nWhether notifications are reliable\n\nWhether withdrawals remain possible during the delay\n\n### Training Wheels\n\nThe phrase training wheels is sometimes used for additional safety or control mechanisms present while a Layer 2 is still developing.\n\nThese may include:\n\nSecurity councils\n\nAdministrator overrides\n\nCentralised sequencers\n\nRestricted provers\n\nEmergency upgrade powers\n\nTraining wheels can reduce early technical risk.\n\nThey also mean the system has not yet reached its intended decentralisation.\n\nA network should be evaluated according to its current controls, not only its future roadmap.\n\n### Sidechains\n\nA sidechain is a separate blockchain connected to another network through a bridge.\n\nIt normally operates its own:\n\nConsensus\n\nValidator set\n\nSecurity budget\n\nBlock production\n\nGovernance\n\nA sidechain may offer:\n\nLow fees\n\nFast transactions\n\nApplication flexibility\n\nHowever, it does not necessarily inherit the base chain’s security.\n\nAssets bridged to the sidechain depend on both:\n\nSidechain security\n\nBridge security\n\nA sidechain should not automatically be classified as a Layer 2.\n\n### Layer 2 Versus Sidechain\n\n\n\n### Layer 2\n\nGenerally relies on a base Layer 1 for meaningful settlement or verification.\n\n### Sidechain\n\nGenerally relies on its own consensus and validators.\n\nA useful question is:\n\nCan the base Layer 1 detect or prevent invalid state transitions on the connected network?\n\nIf the answer is no, the network may function more like an independent chain or sidechain.\n\nMarketing terminology should not replace security analysis.\n\n### Child Chains\n\nA child chain is a secondary blockchain connected to a parent chain.\n\nThe term may describe several architectures.\n\nA child chain may rely on the parent for:\n\nCheckpoints\n\nSettlement\n\nAsset custody\n\nValidator coordination\n\nOr it may operate largely independently.\n\nThe precise mechanism matters more than the label.\n\n### State Channels\n\nA state channel allows participants to conduct many interactions away from the blockchain and settle the final result on-chain.\n\nA simplified process is:\n\nParticipants lock assets in a smart contract\n\nThey exchange signed state updates privately\n\nOnly the final state is submitted to the blockchain\n\nA dispute mechanism handles invalid claims\n\nState channels can offer:\n\nFast interactions\n\nLow per-transaction costs\n\nReduced on-chain activity\n\nLimitations include:\n\nParticipants may need to remain available\n\nCapital may be locked\n\nChannels are less flexible for open multi-user applications\n\nRouting can be complex\n\n### Payment Channels\n\nA payment channel is a state channel designed primarily for repeated payments.\n\nTwo parties can update balances off-chain many times.\n\nOnly opening and closing transactions need to reach the base blockchain.\n\nA network of payment channels may route payments through intermediaries.\n\nPotential risks include:\n\nInsufficient routing liquidity\n\nChannel management\n\nCounterparty availability\n\nWatchtower requirements\n\nLocked capital\n\nFailed routes\n\nPayment channels solve a different problem from general-purpose rollups.\n\n### Plasma\n\nPlasma refers to a family of scaling designs using child chains and Layer 1 exit mechanisms.\n\nUsers may need to monitor the system and challenge invalid exits.\n\nPotential advantages historically included:\n\nReduced Layer 1 activity\n\nGreater transaction capacity\n\nPotential limitations include:\n\nComplex exits\n\nData-availability problems\n\nDifficult support for general smart contracts\n\nLong withdrawal periods\n\nMany newer systems favour rollup architectures, but Plasma concepts remain useful in understanding Layer 2 development.\n\n### Application-Specific Chains\n\nAn application-specific chain is built for a particular product, community or function.\n\nExamples of purposes may include:\n\nTrading\n\nGaming\n\nPayments\n\nSocial applications\n\nData services\n\nPotential advantages include:\n\nCustom fees\n\nSpecialised execution\n\nDedicated capacity\n\nApplication-controlled upgrades\n\nPotential risks include:\n\nSmaller validator set\n\nLimited liquidity\n\nBridge dependence\n\nWeak economic security\n\nApplication-specific governance\n\nAn application chain may be a Layer 1, sidechain or rollup depending on its architecture.\n\n### Rollup-as-a-Service\n\nRollup-as-a-service providers help projects deploy customised rollups.\n\nThey may supply:\n\nSequencer infrastructure\n\nBridge contracts\n\nData availability\n\nExplorer tools\n\nDevelopment software\n\nMonitoring\n\nThis lowers the technical barrier to launching an application-specific rollup.\n\nIt can also create dependence on:\n\nOne infrastructure provider\n\nStandardised contracts\n\nHosted sequencers\n\nExternal upgrade systems\n\nShared security assumptions\n\nA custom rollup is not automatically decentralised because it uses rollup technology.\n\n### Layer 3 Networks\n\nThe term Layer 3 may refer to additional systems built above Layer 2 networks.\n\nPossible purposes include:\n\nApplication-specific execution\n\nPrivacy\n\nCustom scaling\n\nSpecialised settlement\n\nGaming environments\n\nThe term is not standardised.\n\nA Layer 3 may inherit security through a Layer 2, use separate data availability or operate more independently.\n\nAdditional layers may improve customisation while increasing complexity and dependency.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,6,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-29-lesson-07','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Interoperability and Layer 2 Tokens','cmf-module-2-29','text','### Interoperability\n\nInteroperability allows blockchains and Layer 2 networks to exchange:\n\nAssets\n\nMessages\n\nData\n\nContract instructions\n\nInteroperability can improve user experience and capital efficiency.\n\nIt also creates a large security challenge.\n\nA cross-chain system must determine:\n\nWhich state is valid\n\nWho confirms messages\n\nHow reorganisation is handled\n\nWhat happens if one chain stops\n\nHow assets remain backed\n\nA cross-chain message can create losses even without moving a conventional token.\n\n### Message Bridges\n\nA message bridge allows one blockchain to send instructions to another.\n\nFor example, a governance vote on one chain may trigger an action on another.\n\nMessage bridges may rely on:\n\nValidators\n\nOracles\n\nLight clients\n\nMultisignatures\n\nZero-knowledge proofs\n\nOptimistic verification\n\nA malicious message can cause:\n\nToken minting\n\nContract execution\n\nTreasury transfers\n\nGovernance changes\n\nCross-chain messaging can be more powerful—and more dangerous—than simple asset bridging.\n\n### Liquidity Fragmentation\n\nWhen activity spreads across several Layer 2 networks and chains, liquidity becomes fragmented.\n\nThe same asset may exist in separate pools on:\n\nLayer 1\n\nSeveral rollups\n\nSidechains\n\nApplication chains\n\nFragmentation can lead to:\n\nDifferent prices\n\nLower pool depth\n\nHigher slippage\n\nMore bridging\n\nGreater operational complexity\n\nHarder portfolio tracking\n\nScaling increases total capacity but can divide users and capital.\n\n### Shared Liquidity\n\nSome systems attempt to provide shared liquidity across multiple networks.\n\nPossible approaches include:\n\nCross-chain routers\n\nUnified sequencers\n\nIntent-based trading\n\nLiquidity networks\n\nShared bridges\n\nCommon settlement layers\n\nThe objective is to make separate networks feel more like one market.\n\nThese systems introduce their own:\n\nSmart contracts\n\nOperators\n\nSolvers\n\nMessage systems\n\nEconomic assumptions\n\nShared liquidity can reduce fragmentation while concentrating dependency.\n\n### Intents\n\nAn intent-based system allows a user to specify a desired outcome rather than every transaction step.\n\nFor example:\n\n“Exchange Asset A on Network X for Asset B on Network Y.”\n\nSpecialised participants called solvers may compete to fulfil the request.\n\nPotential benefits include:\n\nSimplified cross-chain transactions\n\nBetter routing\n\nReduced user complexity\n\nPotential MEV protection\n\nPotential risks include:\n\nSolver centralisation\n\nIncorrect settlement\n\nSmart contract risk\n\nDelayed execution\n\nUnclear fee extraction\n\nDependency on order-flow systems\n\nA simpler interface may conceal a complex transaction route.\n\n### Account Abstraction\n\nAccount abstraction allows blockchain accounts to support more flexible transaction rules.\n\nPossible features include:\n\nSocial recovery\n\nBatched transactions\n\nSession keys\n\nSpending limits\n\nSponsored fees\n\nMultisignature controls\n\nPayment of fees in different tokens\n\nThis can improve Layer 2 user experience.\n\nIt may also introduce:\n\nSmart wallet contract risk\n\nBundler dependence\n\nPaymaster risk\n\nRecovery-governance complexity\n\nNew signature models\n\nImproved usability does not eliminate the need to understand authorisation.\n\n### Transaction Fees on Layer 2\n\nA Layer 2 fee may include several components:\n\nLayer 2 execution cost\n\nLayer 1 data-publication cost\n\nSequencer fee\n\nProof-generation cost\n\nCongestion premium\n\nProtocol surcharge\n\nFees can change according to:\n\nLayer 1 demand\n\nLayer 2 activity\n\nBatch efficiency\n\nData compression\n\nAsset price\n\nOperator policy\n\nA low-fee network under ordinary conditions may become more expensive during congestion.\n\n### Fee Tokens\n\nA network may charge transaction fees in:\n\nThe Layer 1 native asset\n\nA Layer 2-specific token\n\nAnother accepted token\n\nA sponsored fee system\n\nUsers should maintain enough of the required fee asset to:\n\nTrade\n\nRepay loans\n\nAdjust collateral\n\nWithdraw\n\nRevoke permissions\n\nRespond to emergencies\n\nAssets can become effectively trapped when the user lacks the appropriate gas token.\n\n### Fee Abstraction\n\nFee abstraction allows users to pay transaction costs through an asset other than the network’s traditional native token.\n\nPotential benefits include:\n\nEasier onboarding\n\nReduced need to acquire several gas assets\n\nImproved application experience\n\nPotential risks include:\n\nAdditional smart contracts\n\nExchange-rate mark-ups\n\nPaymaster dependence\n\nHidden fees\n\nTransaction failure when sponsorship ends\n\nA fee may appear absent while being subsidised or included elsewhere.\n\n### Layer 2 Revenue\n\nA Layer 2 may earn revenue from:\n\nTransaction fees\n\nSequencer fees\n\nMEV\n\nBridge fees\n\nApplication charges\n\nToken incentives\n\nCosts may include:\n\nLayer 1 data publication\n\nProof generation\n\nValidator or sequencer infrastructure\n\nUser incentives\n\nDevelopment\n\nSecurity\n\nHigh transaction volume does not automatically mean high profitability.\n\nA network may subsidise activity heavily to attract users.\n\n### Layer 2 Tokens\n\nSome Layer 2 networks issue tokens.\n\nPossible uses include:\n\nGovernance\n\nIncentives\n\nSequencer staking\n\nProtocol fees\n\nEcosystem grants\n\nSecurity\n\nData availability\n\nA Layer 2 token is not automatically required for the network to operate.\n\nThe network may still use the Layer 1 asset for transaction fees.\n\nWhen analysing the token, ask:\n\nWhat function does it perform?\n\nDoes usage create demand?\n\nWho receives fees?\n\nCan governance change critical contracts?\n\nHow concentrated is supply?\n\nAre major unlocks approaching?\n\nNetwork success and token-holder value are not always the same.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,7,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-29-lesson-08','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Layer 2 Token Value Capture and Full Nodes','cmf-module-2-29','text','### Layer 2 Token Value Capture\n\nA successful Layer 2 may process substantial activity without creating direct economic value for its governance token.\n\nPossible value-capture mechanisms include:\n\nFee payment\n\nStaking\n\nSequencer participation\n\nRevenue distribution\n\nGovernance over valuable treasury assets\n\nCollateral use\n\nIf the token is used only for governance, demand may depend heavily on speculation and political influence.\n\nEvaluate the actual rights and obligations attached to the token.\n\n### Layer 1 Value Capture\n\nLayer 2 growth may affect the underlying Layer 1.\n\nPotential benefits to the Layer 1 may include:\n\nData-publication fees\n\nSettlement demand\n\nGreater ecosystem usage\n\nIncreased demand for the native asset\n\nMore application development\n\nPotential concerns include:\n\nActivity and user fees moving away from Layer 1 execution\n\nLayer 2 operators capturing most revenue\n\nFragmented liquidity\n\nWeaker direct user relationships\n\nThe economic relationship between Layer 1 and Layer 2 is complex.\n\nHigher Layer 2 activity does not guarantee proportional Layer 1 token appreciation.\n\n### Network Effects\n\nA blockchain network may become more valuable as it attracts:\n\nUsers\n\nDevelopers\n\nApplications\n\nLiquidity\n\nInfrastructure\n\nWallets\n\nStablecoins\n\nValidators\n\nLayer 2 networks can strengthen a Layer 1 ecosystem by making it cheaper and more accessible.\n\nThey can also compete with one another for:\n\nUsers\n\nLiquidity\n\nDevelopers\n\nSequencer revenue\n\nApplication exclusivity\n\nNetwork effects can develop at several layers simultaneously.\n\n### Composability\n\nComposability describes the ability of applications and smart contracts to interact.\n\nApplications on one blockchain can often combine within the same transaction.\n\nCross-network composability is more difficult because:\n\nMessages take time\n\nFinality differs\n\nBridges create risk\n\nLiquidity is fragmented\n\nTransactions may fail on one side\n\nScaling through many networks can reduce the seamless composability available within one shared execution environment.\n\n### Synchronous and Asynchronous Composability\n\n\n\n### Synchronous Composability\n\nSeveral smart contracts interact within one transaction and receive an immediate shared result.\n\n### Asynchronous Composability\n\nInteractions occur across different networks or times and may require messages, waiting periods and separate confirmations.\n\nSynchronous composability supports complex DeFi transactions.\n\nAsynchronous systems can scale more broadly but require careful failure handling.\n\nA cross-chain action may complete on one network and fail on another.\n\n### Atomic Transactions\n\nAn atomic transaction either completes all required operations or none of them.\n\nWithin one blockchain, smart contracts can often provide atomic execution.\n\nAcross chains, atomicity is more difficult.\n\nPossible risks include:\n\nPartial completion\n\nBridge delay\n\nPrice movement\n\nMessage failure\n\nDestination-chain congestion\n\nCross-chain interfaces may appear to offer one action while several non-atomic steps occur behind the scenes.\n\n### Finality Differences\n\nDifferent networks reach finality through different mechanisms and timeframes.\n\nA bridge or application must decide when to accept a source-chain transaction as final.\n\nAccepting too early can create risk if the transaction is reorganised.\n\nWaiting longer reduces risk but delays the user experience.\n\nCross-network systems must balance:\n\nSpeed\n\nSecurity\n\nCapital efficiency\n\nA “completed” status may represent different levels of certainty on different networks.\n\n### Chain Reorganisations\n\nA chain reorganisation occurs when the accepted sequence of recent blocks changes.\n\nShort reorganisations may be part of normal consensus.\n\nLong or unexpected reorganisations can threaten:\n\nBridge messages\n\nDeposits\n\nWithdrawals\n\nExchange confirmations\n\nCross-chain applications\n\nLayer 2 and bridge systems must define how they respond when the Layer 1 or connected chain reorganises.\n\n### Reorganisation Risk for Layer 2 Networks\n\nA Layer 2 may provide fast preliminary confirmations before its data and state commitments are final on Layer 1.\n\nIf the Layer 1 reorganises, some Layer 2 submissions may need to be resubmitted or adjusted.\n\nThe user may experience:\n\nDelayed settlement\n\nChanged transaction ordering\n\nTemporary uncertainty\n\nFast Layer 2 confirmation should not be confused with final Layer 1 settlement.\n\n### Network Outages\n\nA blockchain or Layer 2 can experience:\n\nSequencer outages\n\nValidator failures\n\nSoftware bugs\n\nConsensus pauses\n\nNetwork congestion\n\nInfrastructure attacks\n\nDuring an outage:\n\nNew transactions may stop\n\nApplications may display stale data\n\nLiquidations may be delayed\n\nOracles may fail to update\n\nBridges may pause\n\nFunds may remain recorded but inaccessible.\n\nAvailability is an important component of financial risk.\n\n### Decentralisation Assessment\n\nA network’s decentralisation can be evaluated across several areas.\n\n### Validator or Sequencer Distribution\n\nHow many independent operators exist?\n\n### Hardware Requirements\n\nCan ordinary participants run nodes?\n\n### Client Diversity\n\nDoes the network depend on one software implementation?\n\n### Governance\n\nWho can change protocol rules?\n\n### Token Distribution\n\nIs control concentrated among insiders?\n\n### Infrastructure\n\nDoes activity depend on one cloud provider or interface?\n\n### Bridge Control\n\nWho can release or freeze bridged assets?\n\nA network may be decentralised in one area and centralised in another.\n\n### Full Nodes\n\nA full node independently verifies blockchain rules and transactions.\n\nRunning a node may require:\n\nStorage\n\nBandwidth\n\nProcessing power\n\nTechnical maintenance\n\nA network with low node requirements may support broader independent verification.\n\nA network requiring expensive infrastructure may achieve high performance while reducing the diversity of node operators.\n\nValidator count alone does not reveal the complete decentralisation picture.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,8,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-29-lesson-09','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Light Clients and Exchange Deposits and Withdrawals','cmf-module-2-29','text','### Light Clients\n\nA light client verifies selected blockchain information without downloading or processing the complete chain state.\n\nIt may rely on:\n\nBlock headers\n\nCryptographic proofs\n\nFull nodes\n\nData-availability sampling\n\nLight clients can improve accessibility for:\n\nMobile wallets\n\nBridges\n\nCross-chain verification\n\nResource-limited devices\n\nTheir security depends on the proof model and data assumptions.\n\n### State Growth\n\nAs a blockchain processes more activity, its stored state can grow.\n\nLarge state increases:\n\nStorage requirements\n\nNode synchronisation time\n\nInfrastructure costs\n\nLong-term maintenance complexity\n\nScaling transaction throughput without controlling state growth may weaken decentralisation over time.\n\nNetworks may use:\n\nState expiry\n\nPruning\n\nCompression\n\nRent\n\nArchival nodes\n\nEach method creates trade-offs for users and developers.\n\n### Data Compression\n\nLayer 2 networks reduce costs partly by compressing transaction data.\n\nCompression may remove:\n\nRepeated information\n\nUnnecessary formatting\n\nRedundant signatures\n\nFull transaction details that can be represented more efficiently\n\nBetter compression allows more user activity per unit of Layer 1 data.\n\nHowever, the data must remain sufficient for:\n\nVerification\n\nState reconstruction\n\nDispute resolution\n\nUser exits\n\nCheaper data should not make the system unverifiable.\n\n### Privacy on Layer 2\n\nLayer 2 systems may support privacy through:\n\nZero-knowledge proofs\n\nShielded transactions\n\nEncrypted state\n\nPrivate application logic\n\nPrivacy can protect users and commercial information.\n\nIt can also create challenges involving:\n\nCompliance\n\nAuditability\n\nKey recovery\n\nProof generation\n\nSelective disclosure\n\nA ZK-based scaling network should not be assumed to provide transaction privacy unless the design explicitly includes it.\n\n### Smart Contract Compatibility\n\nSome Layer 2 systems aim to support the same programming environment as their Layer 1.\n\nThis can make it easier for developers to:\n\nMove applications\n\nReuse code\n\nUse existing wallets\n\nMaintain tooling\n\nCompatibility may not be perfect.\n\nDifferences can exist in:\n\nGas calculation\n\nOpcode support\n\nFinality\n\nPrecompiled contracts\n\nBlock timing\n\nData access\n\nBridging\n\nApplications should be tested on the specific network rather than assumed to behave identically.\n\n### Native Versus Ported Applications\n\nA ported application adapts an existing protocol to another network.\n\nA native application is designed specifically for the new network.\n\nA familiar brand on a Layer 2 may use:\n\nDifferent contracts\n\nDifferent governance\n\nDifferent liquidity\n\nDifferent administrators\n\nDifferent oracle providers\n\nDo not assume that using the same interface or name creates identical risk across networks.\n\nVerify the exact deployment.\n\n### Forked Applications\n\nA developer may copy open-source application code and deploy it on another network.\n\nThe new application may look identical to the original.\n\nIt may lack:\n\nThe original team\n\nSecurity audits\n\nGovernance\n\nLiquidity\n\nOperational history\n\nBug fixes\n\nOpen-source similarity is not proof of equivalent security.\n\n### Network Liquidity\n\nA network may have strong technology and weak liquidity.\n\nUsers may face:\n\nHigh slippage\n\nFew stablecoins\n\nWeak bridge capacity\n\nLimited lending markets\n\nPoor exchange support\n\nNetwork selection should consider whether sufficient liquidity exists for the intended activity.\n\nLow transaction fees do not compensate for an inability to exit efficiently.\n\n### Stablecoin Liquidity Across Networks\n\nThe same stablecoin symbol may represent different assets on different networks.\n\nIt may be:\n\nNatively issued\n\nCanonically bridged\n\nThird-party bridged\n\nWrapped\n\nSynthetic\n\nLiquidity and redemption can differ substantially.\n\nBefore receiving a stablecoin on a Layer 2, verify:\n\nContract address\n\nIssuer\n\nBridge\n\nRedemption path\n\nMarket depth\n\nExchange support\n\n### Oracles Across Networks\n\nA DeFi application deployed on several networks may use different oracle systems on each one.\n\nOne deployment may have:\n\nDeep market data\n\nFrequent updates\n\nEstablished safeguards\n\nAnother may rely on:\n\nFewer exchanges\n\nLower-liquidity pairs\n\nSlower updates\n\nAdditional bridges\n\nThe protocol name remains the same, but the market and oracle risks differ by network.\n\n### Choosing a Network for a Transaction\n\nThe cheapest network is not always the best choice.\n\nConsider:\n\nSecurity\n\nTransaction cost\n\nConfirmation speed\n\nLiquidity\n\nApplication quality\n\nBridge requirements\n\nStablecoin type\n\nWallet support\n\nExchange withdrawal support\n\nExit route\n\nA low-fee network may become expensive when the user must bridge several times or accept poor liquidity.\n\n### Choosing a Network for DeFi\n\nFor a DeFi position, examine:\n\nProtocol deployment\n\nContract addresses\n\nSmart contract audits\n\nOracle quality\n\nLiquidator activity\n\nStablecoin liquidity\n\nBridge dependencies\n\nNetwork uptime\n\nGas requirements\n\nGovernance differences\n\nA lending protocol on one network should not automatically be considered identical to its deployment elsewhere.\n\n### Choosing a Network for Long-Term Asset Storage\n\nLong-term storage priorities may differ from application priorities.\n\nConsider:\n\nWhether the asset is native or bridged\n\nWithdrawal dependence\n\nNetwork security\n\nAdministrator powers\n\nBridge design\n\nHardware-wallet support\n\nRecovery plan\n\nLong-term network viability\n\nHolding a bridged representation for convenience may introduce unnecessary long-term bridge risk.\n\n### Exchange Deposits and Withdrawals\n\nCentralised exchanges may support only particular networks for an asset.\n\nSending an asset through the wrong network can result in:\n\nDelayed recovery\n\nAdditional fees\n\nPermanent loss\n\nDependence on exchange support\n\nBefore transferring, confirm:\n\nAsset\n\nNetwork\n\nAddress\n\nMemo or tag\n\nDeposit status\n\nMinimum amount\n\nConfirmation requirements\n\nThe token symbol alone is insufficient.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,9,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-29-lesson-10','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Address Compatibility and Security Council Risk','cmf-module-2-29','text','### Address Compatibility\n\nSome networks use similar-looking address formats.\n\nThis can create false confidence.\n\nAn address may be syntactically valid on several networks while the receiving platform supports only one.\n\nA transaction can succeed on the blockchain and still fail to credit on the intended service.\n\nAlways confirm the network separately from the address.\n\n### Test Transactions\n\nBefore transferring substantial value to a new network or bridge:\n\nVerify the application and contracts\n\nConfirm the source and destination networks\n\nCheck the destination asset\n\nSend a small amount\n\nWait for final confirmation\n\nConfirm receipt and usability\n\nTest part of the return route where practical\n\nA test transaction reduces operational risk.\n\nIt does not eliminate smart contract or future bridge risk.\n\n### Bridge Approval Risk\n\nBridging may require token approval.\n\nA malicious or compromised bridge contract could use this approval to transfer tokens.\n\nReview:\n\nSpender address\n\nApproval amount\n\nOfficial bridge interface\n\nContract verification\n\nExisting permissions\n\nRevoke unused approvals where practical.\n\n### Cross-Chain Address Poisoning\n\nAttackers may send small transactions from addresses resembling addresses previously used by the victim.\n\nThe victim may later copy the malicious address from transaction history.\n\nCross-chain activity increases the number of addresses and networks a user must manage.\n\nVerify addresses through a trusted source rather than relying only on recent history.\n\n### Network Switching Attacks\n\nA malicious application may request that the wallet switch to an unfamiliar network.\n\nIt may then ask for:\n\nToken approvals\n\nAsset transfers\n\nFraudulent signatures\n\nUsers should confirm:\n\nNetwork name\n\nChain identifier\n\nCurrency symbol\n\nExplorer\n\nApplication legitimacy\n\nA wallet’s successful network switch does not prove that the network or application is safe.\n\n### Layer 2 Explorer\n\nA blockchain explorer allows users to inspect:\n\nTransactions\n\nBlocks\n\nWallet balances\n\nContracts\n\nToken transfers\n\nBridge activity\n\nLayer 2 users may need both:\n\nLayer 2 explorer\n\nLayer 1 explorer\n\nFor example, a deposit may begin on Layer 1 and complete on Layer 2.\n\nUnderstanding both records helps verify the full process.\n\n### Transaction Status Across Layers\n\nA cross-layer transaction may move through several states:\n\nSubmitted on source chain\n\nConfirmed on source chain\n\nRelayed\n\nCredited on destination\n\nIncluded in a batch\n\nProven or challenged\n\nFinalised on settlement layer\n\nInterfaces may simplify these stages into one status.\n\nFor high-value transfers, identify which stage has actually been reached.\n\n### Layer 2 Security Maturity\n\nLayer 2 systems can differ significantly in maturity.\n\nA network may still depend on:\n\nCentralised proposers\n\nAdministrator-controlled upgrades\n\nLimited fraud proofs\n\nRestricted provers\n\nUnproven escape mechanisms\n\nSmall operating history\n\nA project roadmap may describe future decentralisation.\n\nThe current risk depends on the mechanisms operating today.\n\n### Adoption Versus Security\n\nA network can attract:\n\nHigh transaction volume\n\nPopular applications\n\nLarge total value locked\n\nStrong token performance\n\nwhile retaining meaningful technical or governance risks.\n\nAdoption demonstrates demand.\n\nIt does not prove that every security dependency has been resolved.\n\nSimilarly, technically strong architecture does not guarantee users, liquidity or economic sustainability.\n\n### Total Value Locked on Layer 2\n\nLayer 2 TVL may include:\n\nBridged assets\n\nStablecoins\n\nDeFi deposits\n\nApplication collateral\n\nTVL may be measured according to different methods.\n\nIt can be distorted by:\n\nToken-price changes\n\nDouble counting\n\nNative versus externally bridged assets\n\nIncentive-driven deposits\n\nRestaked positions\n\nTVL is an activity indicator, not a complete security or valuation measure.\n\n### Transaction Count\n\nA high transaction count may result from:\n\nGenuine users\n\nBots\n\nGames\n\nAirdrop activity\n\nSpam\n\nVery low fees\n\nRepeated internal operations\n\nTransaction count should be considered alongside:\n\nActive users\n\nFees paid\n\nApplication diversity\n\nEconomic value\n\nRetention\n\nRevenue\n\nMore transactions do not automatically mean more useful adoption.\n\n### Active Addresses\n\nActive addresses count wallet addresses that transact during a period.\n\nThe metric does not equal the number of human users.\n\nOne person or bot can control many addresses.\n\nAn exchange can represent many users through a limited number of wallets.\n\nActive addresses can provide context but should not be interpreted as a direct user count.\n\n### Layer 2 Economic Sustainability\n\nA network may subsidise user activity through:\n\nToken incentives\n\nFee discounts\n\nGrants\n\nSequencer subsidies\n\nAirdrop campaigns\n\nSubsidies can help build adoption.\n\nLong-term sustainability depends on whether:\n\nUsers remain after rewards decline\n\nApplications generate genuine demand\n\nFee revenue covers operating costs\n\nSecurity remains adequately funded\n\nDevelopers continue building\n\nTemporary usage spikes should not be confused with durable network effects.\n\n### Security Council Risk\n\nA security council may have authority to intervene during emergencies.\n\nIt may be able to:\n\nPause contracts\n\nUpgrade the system\n\nReplace components\n\nProtect bridge assets\n\nPotential benefits include rapid incident response.\n\nPotential risks include:\n\nCentralised control\n\nSigner compromise\n\nCollusion\n\nLegal pressure\n\nLimited transparency\n\nThe council’s structure and powers should be disclosed.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,10,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-29-lesson-11','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Governance Token Concentration and Step 8: Record the Complete Route','cmf-module-2-29','text','### Governance Token Concentration\n\nLayer 2 governance may be concentrated among:\n\nFounders\n\nEarly investors\n\nFoundations\n\nDelegates\n\nExchanges\n\nVenture funds\n\nThese groups may control:\n\nTreasury\n\nUpgrades\n\nIncentives\n\nSequencer policy\n\nToken issuance\n\nA decentralised transaction system can still have concentrated political control.\n\n### Network Upgrades\n\nBlockchain and Layer 2 networks require upgrades for:\n\nSecurity\n\nPerformance\n\nNew features\n\nCompatibility\n\nBug fixes\n\nUpgrades can create:\n\nSoftware errors\n\nChain splits\n\nApplication incompatibility\n\nTemporary outages\n\nGovernance conflict\n\nUsers with significant exposure should monitor major upgrades and protocol announcements.\n\n### Chain Splits\n\nA chain split occurs when participants follow different rule sets or histories.\n\nIt may be intentional, as with a governance fork, or accidental because of software disagreement.\n\nA split can affect:\n\nToken ownership\n\nApplication state\n\nBridges\n\nOracles\n\nExchange support\n\nReplay protection\n\nLayer 2 systems must determine which Layer 1 history they recognise.\n\n### Replay Risk\n\nReplay risk occurs when a transaction signed for one chain can be valid on another related chain.\n\nModern networks often use chain identifiers or replay protection.\n\nUsers should still be cautious during:\n\nNetwork forks\n\nTestnet and mainnet confusion\n\nCross-chain signing\n\nWallet network changes\n\nA signature should be understood in the context of the selected chain.\n\n### Layer 1 and Layer 2 Risk Map\n\nA Layer 2 position may include several layers of exposure:\n\nWallet risk\n\nApplication smart contract risk\n\nLayer 2 execution risk\n\nSequencer risk\n\nProver or fraud-monitoring risk\n\nData-availability risk\n\nBridge risk\n\nLayer 1 settlement risk\n\nStablecoin or token risk\n\nGovernance and administrator risk\n\nA low transaction fee does not describe these dependencies.\n\n### Evaluating a Layer 1 Network\n\nA structured assessment may include:\n\n### Consensus\n\nHow does the network agree on transactions?\n\nWhat economic cost protects it?\n\n### Validator or Miner Distribution\n\nHow concentrated is block production?\n\nWhat hardware is required?\n\n### Security History\n\nHas the network experienced major failures or reorganisations?\n\n### Performance\n\nWhat capacity, latency and finality does it provide?\n\n### Decentralisation\n\nCan users run nodes independently?\n\nIs infrastructure concentrated?\n\n### Development\n\nIs the network actively maintained?\n\nAre multiple clients available?\n\n### Economics\n\nHow are validators rewarded?\n\nWhat is the supply and inflation model?\n\n### Ecosystem\n\nAre useful applications, stablecoins and liquidity available?\n\n### Evaluating a Layer 2 Network\n\nAdditional questions include:\n\n### Settlement\n\nWhich Layer 1 settles the system?\n\n### Proof Model\n\nDoes it use fraud proofs or validity proofs?\n\nAre those systems fully operational?\n\n### Data Availability\n\nWhere is transaction data published?\n\nCan users reconstruct the state?\n\n### Sequencer\n\nWho orders transactions?\n\nCan users bypass it?\n\n### Bridge\n\nHow are assets deposited and withdrawn?\n\nWhat waiting periods apply?\n\n### Upgrades\n\nWho can change contracts?\n\nIs there a timelock?\n\n### Escape Mechanism\n\nCan users exit if the operator fails?\n\n### Maturity\n\nWhich controls remain centralised?\n\nHow long has the network operated?\n\n### Economics\n\nWhere do fees go?\n\nWhat function does any Layer 2 token perform?\n\n### Evaluating a Sidechain\n\nQuestions include:\n\nWho validates the chain?\n\nHow much value is staked?\n\nHow concentrated is validation?\n\nDoes the Layer 1 verify sidechain correctness?\n\nWho controls the bridge?\n\nCan the bridge freeze withdrawals?\n\nWhat happens if validators collude?\n\nWhich asset pays fees?\n\nIs liquidity sufficient?\n\nA sidechain’s low fees may result from a smaller or more centralised security system.\n\n### Selecting Between Layer 1 and Layer 2\n\nA user may choose Layer 1 when prioritising:\n\nStronger direct settlement\n\nNative asset ownership\n\nReduced bridge dependence\n\nLong-term storage\n\nHigh-value transactions\n\nA user may choose Layer 2 when prioritising:\n\nLower fees\n\nFaster application use\n\nHigh transaction frequency\n\nGaming or social activity\n\nSmaller DeFi transactions\n\nThe correct choice depends on:\n\nAmount\n\nPurpose\n\nTime horizon\n\nSecurity tolerance\n\nLiquidity\n\nExit plan\n\n### Transaction Cost Versus Total Cost\n\nA low visible network fee may be offset by:\n\nBridge fees\n\nSlippage\n\nPoor liquidity\n\nAsset conversion\n\nWithdrawal delays\n\nAdditional approvals\n\nExchange charges\n\nThe total cost of using a network should include the complete journey.\n\nFor example:\n\nExchange withdrawal\n\nBridge deposit\n\nAsset swap\n\nApplication fee\n\nExit swap\n\nBridge withdrawal\n\nExchange deposit\n\nOne cheap transaction can be part of an expensive process.\n\n### A Network Selection Process\n\n\n\n### Step 1: Define the Activity\n\nIs the objective:\n\nStorage\n\nPayment\n\nTrading\n\nLending\n\nGaming\n\nStaking\n\nApplication use\n\n### Step 2: Identify the Required Asset\n\nDetermine whether the asset is:\n\nNative\n\nWrapped\n\nBridged\n\nSynthetic\n\n### Step 3: Evaluate Security\n\nReview:\n\nConsensus\n\nSettlement\n\nValidators\n\nSequencer\n\nProof system\n\nAdministrator powers\n\n### Step 4: Evaluate Liquidity\n\nCheck:\n\nExchanges\n\nDEX pools\n\nStablecoins\n\nBridge capacity\n\nExit routes\n\n### Step 5: Calculate Total Cost\n\nInclude:\n\nNetwork fees\n\nBridge fees\n\nSlippage\n\nProtocol fees\n\nExchange charges\n\n### Step 6: Review Operational Risk\n\nConfirm:\n\nWallet support\n\nCorrect network\n\nGas token\n\nExplorer\n\nWithdrawal mechanism\n\n### Step 7: Test With a Small Amount\n\nVerify both entry and exit where practical.\n\n### Step 8: Record the Complete Route\n\nDocument contract addresses, networks and transaction identifiers.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,11,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-29-lesson-12','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Layer 1 and Layer 2 Checklist and Module Summary','cmf-module-2-29','text','### Layer 1 and Layer 2 Checklist\n\nBefore transferring assets to a network, ask:\n\nIs this a Layer 1, Layer 2, sidechain or another architecture?\n\nWhich functions does the network perform independently?\n\nWhich Layer 1, if any, provides settlement?\n\nDoes the base chain verify transaction correctness?\n\nIs the system optimistic or validity-proof based?\n\nAre fraud or validity proofs fully operational?\n\nWhere is transaction data stored?\n\nCan users reconstruct the state independently?\n\nWho operates the sequencer?\n\nCan users bypass the sequencer?\n\nWhat happens if the sequencer goes offline?\n\nWho generates proofs?\n\nWho can upgrade contracts?\n\nIs a timelock used?\n\nWhich emergency powers exist?\n\nCan administrators freeze or redirect assets?\n\nWhich bridge will be used?\n\nIs it the canonical bridge or a third-party bridge?\n\nWhat withdrawal period applies?\n\nIs a fast withdrawal dependent on a liquidity provider?\n\nIs the destination asset native, wrapped or bridged?\n\nWho guarantees its backing?\n\nIs sufficient liquidity available?\n\nWhich token is required for network fees?\n\nDo I have enough gas for emergency transactions?\n\nIs the receiving exchange or wallet compatible with the network?\n\nWhat is the total cost of entering and exiting?\n\nHow mature is the network?\n\nHas it experienced outages or security incidents?\n\nCan I test the route with a small amount?\n\nIs the network appropriate for the value and purpose of the transaction?\n\n### Common Layer 1 and Layer 2 Mistakes\n\n\n\n### Choosing Only by Transaction Fee\n\nSecurity, liquidity and exit risk are ignored.\n\n### Assuming Every Connected Chain Is a Layer 2\n\nA sidechain may rely on its own smaller validator set.\n\n### Treating Fast Confirmation as Final Settlement\n\nThe transaction may not yet be final on the settlement layer.\n\n### Using the Wrong Asset Representation\n\nThe user accepts an unsupported or weakly backed bridged token.\n\n### Using an Unverified Bridge\n\nA counterfeit or insecure bridge contract receives the assets.\n\n### Ignoring Withdrawal Delays\n\nThe user expects immediate return to Layer 1.\n\n### Holding No Gas Token\n\nAssets cannot be moved during an emergency.\n\n### Assuming the Same Application Has Identical Risk on Every Network\n\nContracts, liquidity and oracles can differ.\n\n### Treating a Familiar Token Symbol as Proof of Authenticity\n\nSeveral versions may exist on the same network.\n\n### Ignoring Administrator Powers\n\nA small group may be able to upgrade or pause the system.\n\n### Believing ZK Automatically Means Private\n\nValidity proofs and privacy are separate concepts.\n\n### Confusing High Transaction Count With High-Quality Adoption\n\nBots and incentives may create temporary activity.\n\n### Common Misunderstandings\n\n#### “Layer 2 Transactions Occur Completely Off-Chain”\n\nThey are processed outside ordinary Layer 1 execution but may publish data and commitments to the Layer 1.\n\n#### “Every Layer 2 Has the Same Security as Its Layer 1”\n\nSequencers, bridges, administrators and data systems introduce additional assumptions.\n\n#### “A Sidechain Is Simply Another Type of Rollup”\n\nA sidechain generally relies on its own consensus rather than Layer 1 verification.\n\n#### “Optimistic Rollups Are Insecure Because They Assume Validity”\n\nThey use challenge and fraud-proof mechanisms, though these must operate effectively.\n\n#### “ZK Rollups Have No Risks”\n\nProof systems, circuits, provers, bridges and administrators can fail.\n\n#### “Zero Knowledge Means Nobody Can See Transactions”\n\nA validity proof can be zero knowledge while transaction data remains public.\n\n#### “Low Fees Mean the Network Is More Efficient in Every Way”\n\nLow fees may reflect different security, demand or decentralisation trade-offs.\n\n#### “A Transaction Is Final When the Wallet Says Confirmed”\n\nInitial Layer 2 confirmation may precede final Layer 1 settlement.\n\n#### “Canonical Bridged Assets and Third-Party Wrapped Assets Are Identical”\n\nThey may depend on different contracts, custodians and redemption paths.\n\n#### “High TVL Proves a Layer 2 Is Safe”\n\nTVL measures deposited value, not proof quality or governance decentralisation.\n\n#### “More Layers Always Improve Scalability Without Cost”\n\nEvery additional layer creates new dependencies and coordination risks.\n\n#### “Layer 2 Growth Automatically Makes Its Token Valuable”\n\nThe token may capture little or none of the network’s economic activity.\n\n### Module Summary\n\nA Layer 1 is a base blockchain that operates its own consensus and authoritative transaction history.\n\nIt may provide:\n\nExecution\n\nConsensus\n\nSettlement\n\nData availability\n\nSecurity\n\nA Layer 2 processes activity more efficiently while relying on a Layer 1 for important settlement or verification functions.\n\nRollups batch many transactions and submit compressed information to a Layer 1.\n\nOptimistic rollups generally assume batches are valid unless challenged through fraud proofs.\n\nZero-knowledge rollups use cryptographic validity proofs to demonstrate correct execution.\n\nLayer 2 networks may depend on:\n\nSequencers\n\nProvers\n\nFraud monitors\n\nData-availability systems\n\nBridges\n\nAdministrator keys\n\nGovernance\n\nA sidechain differs from a Layer 2 because it generally relies on its own consensus and validator set rather than inheriting the base chain’s transaction-validity security.\n\nScaling can reduce fees and increase capacity.\n\nIt can also create:\n\nLiquidity fragmentation\n\nBridge risk\n\nAdditional governance layers\n\nData-availability risk\n\nComplex withdrawal procedures\n\nNew centralisation points\n\nA network should not be selected according to transaction fees alone.\n\nUsers should evaluate:\n\nSecurity\n\nSettlement\n\nData availability\n\nLiquidity\n\nAsset representation\n\nBridge design\n\nAdministrator powers\n\nWithdrawal path\n\nTotal transaction cost\n\nLayer 1 and Layer 2 systems are not competitors in every case.\n\nThey can form a layered architecture in which the Layer 1 provides high-value settlement and Layer 2 networks provide more affordable execution.\n\nThe strength of that architecture depends on whether every layer remains verifiable, accessible and secure.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,12,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-29-lesson-13','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Key Takeaway','cmf-module-2-29','text','### Key Takeaway\n\nLayer 2 networks increase blockchain capacity by moving execution away from the base chain while continuing to rely on it for selected security, data or settlement functions.\n\nThe lower fee is only the visible benefit.\n\nThe complete risk depends on sequencers, proofs, data availability, bridges, asset backing, administrators and the route back to the settlement layer.\n\nBefore moving value to any network, determine exactly which layer secures the transaction, which parties can interrupt it and how the assets can be recovered if the normal system fails.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,'',NULL,13,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-29-lesson-14','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Check your understanding','cmf-module-2-29','text','### Check your understanding\n\nAnswer these questions to self-assess your understanding before moving on.\n\n1. What is a Layer 1 blockchain?\n\n2. Which core functions may a Layer 1 provide?\n\n3. What is blockchain execution?\n\n4. What is settlement?\n\n5. What is data availability?\n\n6. What does the blockchain trilemma describe?\n\n7. Why can higher hardware requirements reduce decentralisation?\n\n8. What is block space?\n\n9. How does vertical scaling differ from horizontal scaling?\n\n10. What is sharding?\n\n11. How does a modular blockchain differ from a monolithic blockchain?\n\n12. What is a Layer 2 network?\n\n13. What does security inheritance mean?\n\n14. What is a rollup?\n\n15. Why does transaction batching reduce average user costs?\n\n16. What is a state root?\n\n17. How does an optimistic rollup operate?\n\n18. What is a fraud proof?\n\n19. Why do optimistic-rollup withdrawals sometimes involve a delay?\n\n20. What is a zero-knowledge rollup?\n\n21. What is a validity proof?\n\n22. Why does zero knowledge not automatically mean transaction privacy?\n\n23. What is a sequencer?\n\n24. How can sequencer centralisation affect users?\n\n25. What is a forced-inclusion mechanism?\n\n26. What role does a prover perform?\n\n27. Why is data availability necessary?\n\n28. How does a validium differ from a conventional rollup using on-chain data?\n\n29. What is a data-availability layer?\n\n30. What is a canonical bridge?\n\n31. How does a third-party bridge add risk?\n\n32. What is an escape hatch?\n\n33. Why do administrator keys reduce complete decentralisation?\n\n34. What is a sidechain?\n\n35. How does a sidechain differ from a Layer 2?\n\n36. What is a state channel?\n\n37. What is an application-specific chain?\n\n38. What is liquidity fragmentation?\n\n39. How does synchronous composability differ from asynchronous composability?\n\n40. What is an atomic transaction?\n\n41. Why can finality differ between networks?\n\n42. How can a chain reorganisation affect bridges?\n\n43. Why may an L2 application differ from the same application on another network?\n\n44. Why must users distinguish between native, wrapped and bridged assets?\n\n45. What factors should be considered when selecting a network?\n\n46. Why should total cost include more than the network fee?\n\n47. What should be tested before transferring substantial value?\n\n48. Why does high transaction count not automatically prove genuine adoption?\n\n49. How can Layer 2 growth affect its underlying Layer 1?\n\n50. Why does network success not automatically create value for a network token?','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,14,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `course_sections` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`position`,`created_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-30','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Module 2.30: Personal Digital Asset Investment Framework',30,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-30-lesson-01','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','What Is an Investment Framework? and Define Measurable Objectives','cmf-module-2-30','text','### Learning Objectives\n\nBy the end of this module, you should be able to:\n\nExplain what a personal digital asset investment framework is\n\nDefine clear financial objectives and investment constraints\n\nDistinguish between risk tolerance, risk capacity and risk requirements\n\nEstablish criteria for selecting and rejecting digital assets\n\nDevelop written investment theses for portfolio holdings\n\nCreate rules for portfolio allocation, position sizing and diversification\n\nDefine entry, accumulation, reduction and exit procedures\n\nIntegrate custody, liquidity, tax and regulatory considerations\n\nUse scenario analysis and stress testing\n\nRecognise behavioural biases that can weaken investment decisions\n\nDevelop a repeatable research and portfolio-review process\n\nCreate a personal investment policy statement for digital assets\n\n### Introduction\n\nThroughout Course 2, we have examined:\n\nCryptocurrency market structure\n\nMarket cycles\n\nFundamental analysis\n\nProject teams and roadmaps\n\nTokenomics\n\nToken supply and unlocks\n\nPortfolio construction\n\nDiversification\n\nPosition sizing\n\nRisk-to-reward\n\nTechnical analysis\n\nDecentralised finance\n\nStaking\n\nLending\n\nLayer 1 and Layer 2 networks\n\nThe final step is to combine these subjects into one coherent decision-making system.\n\nWithout a framework, cryptocurrency participation can become reactive.\n\nDecisions may be driven by:\n\nSocial-media enthusiasm\n\nFear of missing out\n\nRecent price movements\n\nInfluencer opinions\n\nMarket panic\n\nPersonal attachment to a project\n\nThe desire to recover previous losses\n\nA personal digital asset investment framework establishes rules before emotion becomes intense.\n\nIt helps answer:\n\nWhy am I investing?\n\nHow much can I afford to expose?\n\nWhich assets qualify for consideration?\n\nWhat evidence is required before buying?\n\nHow large may each position become?\n\nWhat would invalidate the investment thesis?\n\nWhen should the portfolio be reviewed?\n\nHow will assets be secured?\n\nHow will taxes and records be managed?\n\nWhat happens if the market falls severely?\n\nThe framework cannot eliminate uncertainty or guarantee profit.\n\nIts purpose is to improve consistency, control risk and reduce avoidable errors.\n\nThis module is educational and does not provide personalised financial advice.\n\n### What Is an Investment Framework?\n\nAn investment framework is a structured set of principles, criteria and procedures used to make and review investment decisions.\n\nIt can include:\n\nObjectives\n\nTime horizon\n\nRisk limits\n\nAsset-selection standards\n\nPortfolio-allocation rules\n\nPosition-sizing limits\n\nEntry and exit criteria\n\nSecurity requirements\n\nMonitoring procedures\n\nRecord-keeping practices\n\nA useful framework should be:\n\nWritten\n\nUnderstandable\n\nRepeatable\n\nEvidence-based\n\nRealistic\n\nAdaptable\n\nConsistently applied\n\nThe framework should guide decisions before, during and after an investment.\n\n### Framework Versus Prediction\n\nAn investment framework does not attempt to predict every market movement.\n\nIt establishes how the investor will respond to uncertainty.\n\nFor example, a framework may state:\n\nNo single speculative token may exceed a defined portfolio percentage\n\nEvery investment requires a written thesis\n\nAssets with unverifiable token supply will be rejected\n\nPurchases will occur in stages rather than through one emotional entry\n\nPortfolio allocations will be reviewed quarterly\n\nLong-term holdings will use a defined custody structure\n\nThese rules remain useful even when the investor does not know what the market will do next.\n\nPrediction attempts to control the outcome.\n\nA framework controls the process.\n\n### Begin With Personal Financial Foundations\n\nDigital asset investing should not be separated from the participant’s broader financial circumstances.\n\nBefore allocating capital, consider:\n\nEssential living expenses\n\nEmergency savings\n\nDebt obligations\n\nInsurance requirements\n\nRetirement funding\n\nFamily responsibilities\n\nIncome stability\n\nExisting investments\n\nNear-term cash needs\n\nCapital required for essential obligations should not depend on cryptocurrency market performance.\n\nA financially sound framework begins by protecting necessities before pursuing uncertain returns.\n\n### Define the Purpose of the Portfolio\n\nThe portfolio should have a clearly stated purpose.\n\nPossible objectives include:\n\nLong-term exposure to digital asset adoption\n\nDiversification within a broader investment portfolio\n\nLearning through limited practical participation\n\nCapital growth\n\nIncome generation\n\nExposure to blockchain infrastructure\n\nTactical participation in market cycles\n\nA portfolio with several conflicting purposes may become difficult to manage.\n\nFor example, a long-term investment portfolio should not be treated like a high-frequency trading account.\n\nComplete the statement:\n\nThe purpose of my digital asset portfolio is to ________________________________.\n\nThe answer should guide every later decision.\n\n### Define Measurable Objectives\n\nA useful objective should be more specific than:\n\n“I want to make money.”\n\nPossible elements include:\n\nIntended investment horizon\n\nMaximum capital allocated\n\nTarget portfolio role\n\nAcceptable volatility\n\nLiquidity requirements\n\nReview schedule\n\nAn example educational objective might be:\n\n“To maintain limited long-term exposure to established digital asset networks while restricting speculative positions and preserving sufficient liquidity for personal financial obligations.”\n\nThe objective does not need to contain a price target.\n\nIt should define what the portfolio is intended to accomplish.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,1,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-30-lesson-02','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Establish the Time Horizon and Establish Maximum Position Sizes','cmf-module-2-30','text','### Establish the Time Horizon\n\nThe time horizon is the period during which capital can remain invested.\n\nPossible horizons include:\n\nShort term: less than one year\n\nMedium term: one to three years\n\nLong term: more than three years\n\nDifferent positions may have different horizons.\n\nFor example:\n\nA core network asset may have a multi-year thesis\n\nA tactical sector position may have a shorter horizon\n\nA trading position may last days or weeks\n\nEach position should be labelled honestly.\n\nA failed short-term trade should not be reclassified automatically as a long-term investment.\n\n### Liquidity Requirements\n\nLiquidity requirements describe when and how quickly funds may be needed.\n\nConsider whether capital may be required for:\n\nEmergency expenses\n\nTax payments\n\nProperty purchases\n\nEducation\n\nBusiness needs\n\nDebt repayment\n\nRetirement income\n\nAssets with:\n\nLock-up periods\n\nUnbonding delays\n\nWithdrawal queues\n\nThin markets\n\nBridge dependence\n\nmay be unsuitable for money needed at short notice.\n\nThe portfolio should contain enough accessible liquidity to avoid forced selling during adverse market conditions.\n\n### Risk Tolerance\n\nRisk tolerance is the investor’s emotional willingness to experience uncertainty and loss.\n\nA participant may believe they tolerate high risk during a bull market.\n\nTheir actual tolerance may change when the portfolio falls:\n\nTwenty percent\n\nFifty percent\n\nEighty percent\n\nQuestions include:\n\nCan I remain rational during severe volatility?\n\nWould a large decline disrupt my sleep?\n\nWould I abandon the plan during panic?\n\nWould I take excessive risk to recover losses?\n\nRisk tolerance should be assessed during realistic adverse scenarios, not only during rising markets.\n\n### Risk Capacity\n\nRisk capacity is the financial ability to absorb loss.\n\nIt depends on:\n\nIncome stability\n\nSavings\n\nDebt\n\nDependants\n\nAge\n\nTime horizon\n\nOther investments\n\nFuture obligations\n\nA person may emotionally enjoy risk but lack the financial capacity to lose essential capital.\n\nRisk capacity should generally place the stronger limit on portfolio exposure.\n\nEnthusiasm cannot replace financial resilience.\n\n### Risk Requirement\n\nRisk requirement describes the amount of risk theoretically needed to achieve a financial objective.\n\nSuppose a person expects an unrealistically high return to meet an underfunded goal.\n\nThis does not justify taking extreme cryptocurrency risk.\n\nIt may indicate that the objective, savings rate or timeline must change.\n\nInvestment risk should not be increased simply because the financial target is difficult.\n\n### Establish Maximum Digital Asset Exposure\n\nDetermine the maximum percentage of the broader financial portfolio that may be allocated to digital assets.\n\nThe decision should consider:\n\nPotential severe drawdowns\n\nCorrelation with other investments\n\nExisting technology or business exposure\n\nIncome stability\n\nTime horizon\n\nFinancial obligations\n\nA cryptocurrency portfolio may appear diversified internally while still representing excessive concentration in the person’s total wealth.\n\nThe allocation limit should be decided before a market rally creates pressure to increase it.\n\n### Separate Investment Capital From Essential Money\n\nInvestment capital should not include:\n\nEmergency funds\n\nRent or mortgage payments\n\nTax money\n\nEducation funds needed soon\n\nMedical reserves\n\nShort-term debt payments\n\nBorrowed money that cannot tolerate loss\n\nCryptocurrency prices can decline rapidly.\n\nPlatforms can suspend withdrawals.\n\nDeFi positions can become inaccessible.\n\nThe investor should be able to lose the allocated capital without threatening essential financial security.\n\n### Define Portfolio Categories\n\nA personal framework may divide holdings into categories.\n\nPossible categories include:\n\n### Core Holdings\n\nRelatively established and liquid assets intended for longer-term exposure.\n\n### Growth Holdings\n\nProjects with developing adoption and greater uncertainty.\n\n### Speculative Holdings\n\nEarly-stage or high-risk positions where complete loss is considered possible.\n\n### Liquidity Reserve\n\nCash or carefully evaluated liquid assets available for flexibility.\n\n### Experimental Capital\n\nA very limited allocation used for learning about new protocols or technologies.\n\nCategories help ensure that every holding has a defined role.\n\n### Establish Category Limits\n\nEach category should have:\n\nA target allocation\n\nA maximum allocation\n\nA permitted range\n\nA review rule\n\nAn illustrative structure could state:\n\nCore category: largest portion of the crypto allocation\n\nGrowth category: smaller controlled exposure\n\nSpeculative category: strictly limited\n\nLiquidity reserve: maintained for flexibility\n\nExperimental capital: minimal and isolated\n\nThe exact percentages depend on personal circumstances.\n\nThe important principle is that higher uncertainty should have a smaller financial influence.\n\n### Establish Maximum Position Sizes\n\nDefine limits for:\n\nOne core asset\n\nOne growth asset\n\nOne speculative token\n\nOne stablecoin\n\nOne blockchain ecosystem\n\nOne exchange\n\nOne DeFi protocol\n\nOne custodian\n\nPosition limits help prevent one failure from dominating the portfolio.\n\nA maximum position should account for related holdings.\n\nFor example, exposure to one blockchain may include:\n\nIts native token\n\nApplications built on it\n\nA liquid-staking token\n\nDeFi positions using it as collateral\n\nTokens bridged through its ecosystem\n\nThe aggregate exposure may be much larger than one line item suggests.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,2,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-30-lesson-03','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Define Permitted Assets and Evaluate Custody and Technical Risk','cmf-module-2-30','text','### Define Permitted Assets\n\nA framework can state which asset types are eligible.\n\nPossible eligible categories may include:\n\nEstablished blockchain networks\n\nSmart contract platforms\n\nInfrastructure protocols\n\nDeFi applications\n\nStablecoins\n\nTokenised real-world assets\n\nLimited speculative projects\n\nThe framework may also exclude assets that do not meet defined standards.\n\nFor example:\n\nUnverifiable supply\n\nAnonymous teams without compensating transparency\n\nExtremely concentrated ownership\n\nNo meaningful liquidity\n\nUnclear token utility\n\nMalicious contract permissions\n\nGuaranteed-return claims\n\nAn exclusion list prevents attractive marketing from bypassing basic risk standards.\n\n### Create a Minimum Research Standard\n\nEvery asset considered for investment should pass a minimum research process.\n\nThe review may include:\n\nProject purpose\n\nProblem addressed\n\nTechnology\n\nTeam\n\nRoadmap\n\nAdoption\n\nCompetition\n\nToken utility\n\nSupply schedule\n\nVesting and unlocks\n\nGovernance\n\nSecurity\n\nLiquidity\n\nRegulation\n\nValuation\n\nThe depth of research should increase with position size.\n\nA large allocation requires stronger evidence than a small experimental position.\n\n### Understand the Project’s Purpose\n\nThe investor should be able to explain:\n\nWhat the project does\n\nWho uses it\n\nWhy a blockchain or token is necessary\n\nWhat problem it solves\n\nHow it differs from alternatives\n\nIf the project cannot be explained in clear language, the investor may not understand it sufficiently.\n\nTechnical complexity should not be used to hide weak economic value.\n\n### Evaluate Product and Adoption\n\nResearch should distinguish between:\n\nA concept\n\nA working product\n\nUsers\n\nPaying users\n\nSustainable economic activity\n\nPossible adoption evidence includes:\n\nActive users\n\nTransaction fees\n\nDeveloper activity\n\nIntegrations\n\nRevenue\n\nRetention\n\nNetwork usage\n\nMetrics must be interpreted cautiously.\n\nActivity may be inflated through:\n\nIncentives\n\nBots\n\nAirdrop farming\n\nWash trading\n\nMultiple addresses controlled by one participant\n\nAdoption quality matters more than one large number.\n\n### Evaluate the Team\n\nTeam analysis may consider:\n\nRelevant experience\n\nTechnical ability\n\nBusiness execution\n\nPublic accountability\n\nPast projects\n\nCommunication\n\nGovernance behaviour\n\nSecurity response\n\nAn anonymous team is not automatically fraudulent.\n\nIt creates additional verification challenges.\n\nA famous team is not automatically competent or trustworthy.\n\nEvidence of delivery deserves more weight than reputation alone.\n\n### Evaluate the Roadmap\n\nA roadmap should contain:\n\nClear milestones\n\nRealistic timelines\n\nDefined priorities\n\nEvidence of progress\n\nUpdates when assumptions change\n\nWarning signs include:\n\nConstant delays without explanation\n\nVague promises\n\nFrequent changes in direction\n\nPromotional partnerships replacing product delivery\n\nRepeated movement of deadlines\n\nDependence on future technology that does not yet exist\n\nA roadmap is a plan, not proof of execution.\n\n### Evaluate Token Utility\n\nAsk why the token exists.\n\nPossible functions include:\n\nTransaction fees\n\nStaking\n\nGovernance\n\nCollateral\n\nAccess\n\nIncentives\n\nRevenue participation\n\nNetwork security\n\nThen ask whether the function creates durable demand.\n\nA token may be useful within a protocol without being a strong investment.\n\nIf users can access the product without holding the token, value capture may be weak.\n\n### Evaluate Token Supply\n\nReview:\n\nCirculating supply\n\nTotal supply\n\nMaximum supply\n\nInflation\n\nEmissions\n\nBurns\n\nTreasury holdings\n\nFounder allocations\n\nInvestor allocations\n\nUnlock schedule\n\nA low current supply can create an attractive-looking market capitalisation while substantial future dilution remains.\n\nSupply analysis should extend beyond today’s circulating amount.\n\n### Evaluate Vesting and Unlocks\n\nFor every major allocation, identify:\n\nRecipient\n\nNumber of tokens\n\nCliff\n\nVesting period\n\nUnlock dates\n\nAcquisition cost\n\nGovernance rights\n\nStaking rewards\n\nCompare future unlocks with:\n\nCirculating supply\n\nTrading volume\n\nMarket depth\n\nProject demand\n\nAn unlock does not guarantee selling.\n\nIt creates the ability to sell and may alter governance concentration.\n\n### Evaluate Value Capture\n\nA protocol may generate substantial activity without transferring value to its token.\n\nInvestigate:\n\nWho receives fees\n\nWhether token holders receive economic benefits\n\nWhether the token is required\n\nWhether supply grows faster than demand\n\nWhether governance controls valuable resources\n\nWhether revenue distribution is legally or technically enforceable\n\nNetwork success and token-holder return are separate questions.\n\n### Evaluate Valuation\n\nValuation may consider:\n\nMarket capitalisation\n\nFully diluted valuation\n\nRevenue\n\nFees\n\nUsage\n\nTreasury assets\n\nComparable networks\n\nSupply growth\n\nExpected adoption\n\nA strong project can still be a poor investment at an excessive valuation.\n\nA falling price can still be expensive when fundamentals deteriorate faster.\n\nValuation should compare price with realistic future economic potential.\n\n### Evaluate Liquidity\n\nBefore investing, determine:\n\nWhere the asset trades\n\nGenuine volume\n\nBid-ask spread\n\nOrder-book depth\n\nDEX pool liquidity\n\nWithdrawal access\n\nMarket-maker concentration\n\nA token may have a high displayed value and little practical exit liquidity.\n\nPosition size should be limited by the amount that can realistically be sold.\n\n### Evaluate Custody and Technical Risk\n\nDetermine:\n\nWhich wallets support the asset\n\nWhether hardware-wallet support exists\n\nWhich blockchain is used\n\nWhether the asset is native or bridged\n\nWhich smart contracts are required\n\nWhether administrator powers exist\n\nHow recovery will work\n\nA valuable asset that cannot be secured or recovered appropriately may be unsuitable.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,3,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-30-lesson-04','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Evaluate Regulatory and Legal Risk and Avoid Chasing Price','cmf-module-2-30','text','### Evaluate Regulatory and Legal Risk\n\nConsider:\n\nToken classification\n\nTrading restrictions\n\nTax treatment\n\nSanctions exposure\n\nStablecoin rules\n\nLending or staking regulation\n\nGeographic availability\n\nPlatform legal status\n\nRegulation can affect:\n\nExchange access\n\nLiquidity\n\nToken utility\n\nCustody\n\nProject operations\n\nTax obligations\n\nRules vary across jurisdictions and may change.\n\nProfessional guidance may be necessary.\n\n### Write an Investment Thesis\n\nAn investment thesis is a concise explanation of why an asset is expected to produce an acceptable return relative to its risk.\n\nA thesis should include:\n\nWhat the project does\n\nWhy demand may grow\n\nWhy the token may capture value\n\nExpected time horizon\n\nMain risks\n\nValuation view\n\nEvidence required\n\nInvalidation conditions\n\nA thesis should be written before purchasing.\n\nWriting forces assumptions to become visible.\n\n### Example Investment-Thesis Structure\n\nA thesis may follow this format:\n\n### Asset\n\nName and network.\n\n### Portfolio Role\n\nCore, growth, speculative or experimental.\n\n### Investment Case\n\nWhy the asset may create or capture value.\n\n### Evidence\n\nAdoption, security, development, economics and competitive position.\n\n### Time Horizon\n\nExpected period for the thesis to develop.\n\n### Principal Risks\n\nTechnical, regulatory, governance, liquidity and tokenomic risks.\n\n### Invalidation\n\nSpecific evidence that would weaken or disprove the thesis.\n\n### Maximum Allocation\n\nThe largest permitted portfolio percentage.\n\nThe thesis should be updated only when the evidence changes—not whenever the price moves.\n\n### Define Thesis Invalidation\n\nInvalidation means identifying what would demonstrate that the investment reasoning is no longer credible.\n\nPossible invalidation events include:\n\nCritical security failure\n\nLoss of developer activity\n\nPersistent decline in genuine users\n\nToken utility removed\n\nUnexpected supply inflation\n\nGovernance capture\n\nRegulatory prohibition\n\nLiquidity collapse\n\nA superior competitor taking the market\n\nFailure to deliver essential technology\n\nAn invalidated thesis requires review.\n\nThe decision may be to:\n\nExit\n\nReduce\n\nPause further buying\n\nContinue with a smaller position\n\nReplace the asset\n\nA price decline alone does not necessarily invalidate a thesis.\n\nA thesis failure should not be ignored merely because the price has declined.\n\n### Define Evidence That Strengthens the Thesis\n\nA framework should also identify evidence that may justify increased confidence.\n\nExamples include:\n\nGrowing organic usage\n\nImproved security\n\nSustainable fee revenue\n\nDecentralised validator growth\n\nSuccessful roadmap delivery\n\nStronger liquidity\n\nReduced token inflation\n\nBetter governance distribution\n\nMeaningful institutional or developer adoption\n\nImproving evidence may justify a position increase, subject to portfolio limits and valuation.\n\nPrice appreciation by itself is not sufficient evidence.\n\n### Distinguish Price From Value\n\nPrice reflects the latest market transaction.\n\nValue is an estimate based on future usefulness, scarcity, cash flows, security and demand.\n\nPrice can rise while value deteriorates.\n\nPrice can fall while long-term value improves.\n\nA framework should avoid using:\n\nRising price as proof of quality\n\nFalling price as proof of value\n\nThe relevant question is:\n\nWhat has changed in the relationship between price, fundamentals and risk?\n\n### Establish Entry Criteria\n\nEntry criteria define the conditions required before capital is committed.\n\nThey may include:\n\nFundamental thesis completed\n\nMinimum liquidity satisfied\n\nToken contract verified\n\nSupply and unlock schedule reviewed\n\nValuation within an acceptable range\n\nPosition size calculated\n\nCustody plan prepared\n\nNo unresolved security concern\n\nTechnical criteria may also be used, such as:\n\nTrend alignment\n\nSupport response\n\nBreakout confirmation\n\nFavourable risk-to-reward\n\nReduced momentum after a correction\n\nEntry criteria should match the investment strategy.\n\n### Staged Entries\n\nInstead of purchasing the full position at once, the investor may enter through several stages.\n\nPotential benefits include:\n\nReduced timing risk\n\nTime to reassess the thesis\n\nLower emotional pressure\n\nCapital available for volatility\n\nA staged plan should define:\n\nMaximum total position\n\nNumber of stages\n\nConditions for each stage\n\nPrice or evidence requirements\n\nEvents that cancel further buying\n\nStaged buying should not become unlimited averaging down.\n\n### Dollar-Cost Averaging\n\nDollar-cost averaging involves investing a fixed amount at regular intervals.\n\nPotential benefits include:\n\nReduced dependence on one entry price\n\nSimpler execution\n\nLower emotional timing pressure\n\nConsistent savings discipline\n\nPotential limitations include:\n\nContinued buying into a failing asset\n\nIgnoring valuation\n\nIncreasing concentration\n\nFees\n\nNo protection from permanent loss\n\nThe asset should still be reviewed periodically.\n\nAutomatic buying should stop when the thesis is invalidated.\n\n### Value Averaging and Conditional Accumulation\n\nA conditional accumulation plan may purchase only when specified criteria are met.\n\nThese might include:\n\nValuation threshold\n\nAllocation below target\n\nFundamental progress\n\nDefined technical support\n\nMarket drawdown\n\nThis approach can be more selective than fixed periodic buying.\n\nIt also requires more judgement and may produce fewer purchases.\n\nThe criteria should be defined before the decision.\n\n### Avoid Chasing Price\n\nChasing occurs when an investor buys after a rapid increase because they fear missing further gains.\n\nRisks include:\n\nPoor risk-to-reward\n\nEmotional decision-making\n\nBuying near short-term exhaustion\n\nOversized positions\n\nAbandoning valuation discipline\n\nA framework may include rules such as:\n\nNo purchase after an extreme short-term rise without reassessment\n\nNo position increase beyond the category limit\n\nA waiting period after major promotional announcements\n\nRecalculation of valuation after rapid appreciation\n\nA missed opportunity is less damaging than an undisciplined loss.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,4,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-30-lesson-05','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Position-Sizing Rules and Trading Versus Investing Accounts','cmf-module-2-30','text','### Position-Sizing Rules\n\nThe framework should define how position size is calculated.\n\nFor long-term investments, factors may include:\n\nMaximum acceptable loss\n\nAsset quality\n\nVolatility\n\nLiquidity\n\nToken concentration\n\nThesis strength\n\nPortfolio correlation\n\nFor shorter-term trades, the formula may use:\n\nPosition size = Maximum capital at risk ÷ Percentage distance to invalidation\n\nThe purpose is to ensure that failure remains manageable.\n\n### Position Size by Failure Scenario\n\nFor a speculative token, the framework may assume a one-hundred-percent loss.\n\nFor a more established asset, it may model a severe decline such as:\n\nFifty percent\n\nSeventy percent\n\nEighty percent\n\nThe scenario should be realistic for cryptocurrency markets.\n\nIf the assumed loss would create unacceptable harm, reduce the position.\n\n### Aggregate Exposure Rules\n\nPositions should be grouped by shared dependencies.\n\nPossible exposure categories include:\n\nBlockchain ecosystem\n\nStablecoin\n\nCustodian\n\nExchange\n\nBridge\n\nOracle\n\nDeFi protocol\n\nSector narrative\n\nFor example, several different tokens may all depend on one Layer 1 network.\n\nThe framework should set an aggregate limit for that ecosystem.\n\n### Diversification Rules\n\nA diversification policy may include limits across:\n\nAsset types\n\nNetworks\n\nUse cases\n\nTokenomics\n\nCustodians\n\nStablecoins\n\nProtocols\n\nDiversification should reduce dependence on one failure.\n\nIt should not add weak assets merely to increase the number of holdings.\n\nEvery position must still pass the investment criteria.\n\n### Concentration Rules\n\nA framework should define when concentration becomes excessive.\n\nPossible triggers include:\n\nOne asset exceeding its maximum percentage\n\nOne ecosystem dominating the portfolio\n\nOne exchange holding too much value\n\nOne stablecoin supporting several strategies\n\nOne DeFi protocol carrying excessive exposure\n\nConcentration may increase through price appreciation even without new buying.\n\nThe portfolio should be reviewed when limits are exceeded.\n\n### Define Rebalancing Rules\n\nRebalancing restores the portfolio toward intended allocations.\n\nPossible methods include:\n\n### Calendar-Based Review\n\nMonthly, quarterly, semi-annually or annually.\n\n### Threshold-Based Review\n\nTriggered when an allocation moves outside a permitted band.\n\n### Thesis-Based Review\n\nTriggered when material evidence changes.\n\nA combined method may work best.\n\nRebalancing should not be performed blindly.\n\nFundamentals must be reviewed before buying more of a declining asset.\n\n### Allocation Bands\n\nAn allocation band defines an acceptable range around a target.\n\nFor example:\n\nTarget: 20 percent\n\nLower band: 15 percent\n\nUpper band: 25 percent\n\nA review occurs when the position moves outside the band.\n\nThe response may include:\n\nSelling part of an overweight asset\n\nDirecting new capital toward underweight categories\n\nUpdating the target if evidence has changed\n\nExiting if the thesis is invalid\n\nBands reduce unnecessary trading while limiting uncontrolled drift.\n\n### Define Reduction Rules\n\nA position may be reduced when:\n\nIt exceeds its maximum allocation\n\nValuation becomes excessive\n\nLiquidity deteriorates\n\nToken unlock risk increases\n\nEvidence weakens\n\nPersonal financial circumstances change\n\nPortfolio concentration becomes too high\n\nReduction does not require the complete thesis to fail.\n\nIt may simply restore appropriate risk.\n\n### Define Exit Rules\n\nExit criteria may include:\n\nThesis invalidation\n\nSecurity failure\n\nFraud\n\nGovernance capture\n\nPermanent loss of adoption\n\nUnacceptable regulatory risk\n\nLiquidity collapse\n\nBetter risk-adjusted opportunity\n\nAchievement of the original objective\n\nAn exit rule should focus on current evidence and future prospects.\n\nThe purchase price should not control the decision.\n\nThe market does not know where the investor bought.\n\n### Avoid the Break-Even Trap\n\nInvestors often refuse to sell until an asset returns to their acquisition price.\n\nThis is known as anchoring.\n\nThe appropriate question is not:\n\nWill it return to my purchase price?\n\nIt is:\n\nWould I buy this asset today at its current price, given the current evidence?\n\nIf the answer is no, holding purely to reach break even may be irrational.\n\n### Profit-Taking Rules\n\nA framework may define profit-taking according to:\n\nAllocation limits\n\nValuation\n\nPredefined targets\n\nMarket-cycle conditions\n\nPersonal financial goals\n\nThesis maturity\n\nPossible methods include:\n\nRebalancing excess gains\n\nSelling in stages\n\nRecovering initial capital\n\nReducing speculative positions\n\nMaintaining a core holding\n\nProfit-taking should not depend on identifying the exact market top.\n\nThe objective is to manage risk and convert some uncertain market value into realised financial benefit.\n\n### Trailing Exit Rules\n\nA trailing exit adjusts as the asset price rises.\n\nIt may use:\n\nMarket structure\n\nMoving averages\n\nPercentage declines\n\nVolatility measures\n\nAllocation thresholds\n\nPotential benefits include:\n\nRetaining exposure to a trend\n\nProtecting part of the gain\n\nReducing emotional decisions\n\nPotential limitations include:\n\nExit during ordinary volatility\n\nDelayed reaction during sudden crashes\n\nDifferent performance across market regimes\n\nThe method should be defined and tested before use.\n\n### Trading Versus Investing Accounts\n\nSome participants may separate:\n\nLong-term investment holdings\n\nTactical positions\n\nShort-term trading capital\n\nThis separation can prevent:\n\nTrading losses from affecting core holdings\n\nLong-term assets being used as leverage\n\nA failed trade becoming an unplanned investment\n\nConfusion over time horizon\n\nEach account should have its own:\n\nObjectives\n\nPosition limits\n\nRisk rules\n\nReview procedures','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,5,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-30-lesson-06','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Leverage Policy and Information Sources','cmf-module-2-30','text','### Leverage Policy\n\nA personal framework should state whether leverage is permitted.\n\nPossible policy choices include:\n\nNo leverage\n\nLeverage allowed only in a separate trading account\n\nMaximum effective leverage\n\nMaximum liquidation risk\n\nProhibition on borrowing against core holdings\n\nProhibition on recursive lending\n\nLeverage increases:\n\nLoss speed\n\nLiquidation risk\n\nEmotional pressure\n\nDependency on exchanges and protocols\n\nNo position should use leverage merely because the platform makes it available.\n\n### DeFi Participation Policy\n\nA DeFi policy may define:\n\nApproved protocols\n\nMaximum exposure per protocol\n\nMinimum operating history\n\nAudit requirements\n\nProhibited leverage\n\nPermitted stablecoins\n\nWallet separation\n\nApproval-revocation practices\n\nExit procedures\n\nEvery DeFi position should identify:\n\nYield source\n\nSmart contracts\n\nCollateral\n\nOracle\n\nBridge\n\nGovernance\n\nWithdrawal conditions\n\nThe displayed yield should never replace this analysis.\n\n### Staking Policy\n\nA staking policy may include:\n\nPermitted assets\n\nValidator-selection rules\n\nMaximum custodial exposure\n\nUnbonding limits\n\nLiquid-staking-token limits\n\nRestaking restrictions\n\nSlashing review\n\nReward-recording procedures\n\nThe framework should aggregate:\n\nNative tokens\n\nStaked tokens\n\nLiquid-staking tokens\n\nRestaked positions\n\nas related underlying exposure.\n\n### Lending and Borrowing Policy\n\nA lending policy may define:\n\nApproved protocols\n\nPermitted collateral\n\nMaximum supplier exposure\n\nMinimum withdrawal liquidity\n\nStablecoin standards\n\nRequired reserve analysis\n\nA borrowing policy may define:\n\nMaximum LTV\n\nMinimum health factor\n\nEmergency repayment reserve\n\nProhibition on borrowing for speculation\n\nMaximum variable interest rate\n\nNo borrowing near liquidation thresholds\n\nBorrowing should have a clear purpose and repayment plan.\n\n### Stablecoin Policy\n\nStablecoins may be used for:\n\nTrading liquidity\n\nDeFi\n\nPortfolio reserves\n\nPayments\n\nThe framework should evaluate:\n\nIssuer\n\nReserve assets\n\nRedemption\n\nRegulation\n\nBlockchain\n\nBridge\n\nLiquidity\n\nFreezing powers\n\nPossible rules include:\n\nMaximum exposure to one stablecoin\n\nPreference for native rather than bridged versions\n\nNo long-term reserve in unaudited or weakly backed tokens\n\nDepeg-response procedures\n\nStablecoins should not be treated as identical to insured bank deposits.\n\n### Custody Framework\n\nCustody should match:\n\nPosition size\n\nHolding period\n\nTransaction frequency\n\nTechnical ability\n\nRecovery needs\n\nA custody structure may separate:\n\n### Long-Term Wallet\n\nFor assets that rarely interact with applications.\n\n### Active Wallet\n\nFor regular transactions.\n\n### DeFi Wallet\n\nFor approved smart contract activity.\n\n### Experimental Wallet\n\nFor small, high-risk interactions.\n\n### Exchange Balance\n\nOnly for capital needed for trading or short-term operations.\n\nThe objective is to reduce single points of failure.\n\n### Exchange Exposure Limits\n\nAssets held on an exchange are exposed to:\n\nInsolvency\n\nHacking\n\nWithdrawal suspension\n\nAccount restriction\n\nRegulatory action\n\nOperational failure\n\nA framework may limit:\n\nMaximum value per exchange\n\nDuration of exchange custody\n\nAssets permitted to remain\n\nWithdrawal-test frequency\n\nAuthentication requirements\n\nExchange convenience should not create unlimited counterparty exposure.\n\n### Wallet Security Standards\n\nSecurity requirements may include:\n\nHardware wallet for significant holdings\n\nOffline recovery backup\n\nStrong device security\n\nSeparate passwords\n\nMultifactor authentication\n\nAddress verification\n\nSmall test transactions\n\nNo storage of seed phrases in cloud notes\n\nRegular approval review\n\nA documented inheritance or recovery plan\n\nSecurity should be designed before the portfolio becomes large.\n\n### Recovery Planning\n\nA recovery plan should address:\n\nLost device\n\nDamaged hardware wallet\n\nForgotten password\n\nDeath or incapacity\n\nCompromised seed phrase\n\nFire or theft\n\nWallet software failure\n\nThe plan must balance:\n\nSecurity\n\nAccessibility\n\nPrivacy\n\nSimplicity\n\nA recovery method that is so complex that the owner cannot use it is not effective.\n\nDo not store all recovery components in one vulnerable location.\n\n### Transaction Procedures\n\nA personal transaction checklist may require:\n\nVerify the recipient address\n\nVerify the blockchain network\n\nConfirm the asset contract\n\nCheck any memo or tag\n\nSend a small test amount\n\nConfirm receipt\n\nSend the remaining amount\n\nRecord the transaction\n\nFor smart contract interactions:\n\nVerify the application\n\nVerify the contract\n\nReview approvals\n\nCheck minimum received\n\nExamine fees and slippage\n\nConfirm the wallet request\n\nRevoke unnecessary permissions later\n\nA repeatable procedure reduces operational mistakes.\n\n### Tax and Record-Keeping Framework\n\nThe framework should record:\n\nPurchases\n\nSales\n\nSwaps\n\nTransfers\n\nFees\n\nStaking rewards\n\nLending interest\n\nAirdrops\n\nLiquidity-provider transactions\n\nLiquidations\n\nWallet ownership\n\nCost basis\n\nRecords should include:\n\nDate\n\nQuantity\n\nAsset\n\nMarket value\n\nTransaction identifier\n\nPlatform\n\nPurpose\n\nTax treatment differs by jurisdiction.\n\nRecord-keeping should begin with the first transaction rather than after the portfolio becomes complex.\n\n### Regulatory Review\n\nThe investor should establish a schedule for reviewing:\n\nTax rules\n\nExchange restrictions\n\nStablecoin regulations\n\nStaking treatment\n\nDeFi access\n\nReporting requirements\n\nSecurities classification\n\nForeign exchange controls\n\nRegulatory changes can alter:\n\nAsset liquidity\n\nPlatform availability\n\nTax cost\n\nCustody options\n\nProject viability\n\nThe framework should allow adaptation without panic.\n\n### Information Sources\n\nA strong research process uses several source types.\n\nPossible sources include:\n\nOfficial documentation\n\nSource-code repositories\n\nBlockchain explorers\n\nGovernance forums\n\nAudit reports\n\nDevelopment updates\n\nIndependent research\n\nRegulatory publications\n\nFinancial statements\n\nOn-chain data\n\nAvoid relying only on:\n\nPromotional videos\n\nInfluencer posts\n\nAnonymous screenshots\n\nCommunity rumours\n\nPrice predictions\n\nReferral-driven content\n\nPrimary evidence should receive greater weight than commentary.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,6,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-30-lesson-07','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Source Verification and Sunk-Cost Fallacy','cmf-module-2-30','text','### Source Verification\n\nBefore accepting information, ask:\n\nWho produced it?\n\nWhat incentives do they have?\n\nIs the data independently verifiable?\n\nIs it current?\n\nDoes another credible source confirm it?\n\nIs the claim based on evidence or opinion?\n\nA project’s own documentation is useful for understanding its stated design.\n\nIt should not be treated as independent proof that the design will succeed.\n\n### Research Frequency\n\nDifferent information requires different review frequency.\n\n### Frequent Monitoring\n\nMay apply to:\n\nLeveraged positions\n\nDeFi collateral\n\nSecurity incidents\n\nLiquidation levels\n\nMajor governance proposals\n\n### Periodic Monitoring\n\nMay apply to:\n\nAdoption\n\nDevelopment\n\nToken unlocks\n\nPortfolio allocations\n\nRegulatory changes\n\n### Event-Driven Monitoring\n\nMay apply when:\n\nA major upgrade occurs\n\nThe project is exploited\n\nLeadership changes\n\nA stablecoin depegs\n\nA major unlock approaches\n\nMonitoring should match the position’s risk and time horizon.\n\n### Investment Journal\n\nAn investment journal records the reasoning behind decisions.\n\nEntries may include:\n\nDate\n\nAsset\n\nThesis\n\nEvidence\n\nValuation\n\nEntry reason\n\nPosition size\n\nRisks\n\nInvalidation\n\nEmotional state\n\nExpected time horizon\n\nPlanned review date\n\nLater updates can record:\n\nNew evidence\n\nChanges to the thesis\n\nPosition adjustments\n\nOutcome\n\nLessons learned\n\nThe purpose is to evaluate decision quality—not merely whether the price rose.\n\n### Decision Quality Versus Outcome\n\nA good decision can produce a loss.\n\nA poor decision can produce a profit.\n\nFor example:\n\nA disciplined, researched position may fail because of an unexpected event\n\nAn impulsive meme-token purchase may rise through luck\n\nJudging decisions only by outcomes encourages poor habits.\n\nEvaluate whether the decision:\n\nFollowed the framework\n\nUsed reliable evidence\n\nApplied appropriate sizing\n\nConsidered alternatives\n\nManaged risk\n\nThe goal is a process capable of producing acceptable results across many decisions.\n\n### Behavioural Biases\n\nInvestors are influenced by predictable psychological tendencies.\n\nCommon biases include:\n\nFear of missing out\n\nLoss aversion\n\nAnchoring\n\nConfirmation bias\n\nRecency bias\n\nOverconfidence\n\nHerd behaviour\n\nSunk-cost fallacy\n\nOutcome bias\n\nNarrative bias\n\nA written framework creates distance between emotional reactions and financial actions.\n\n### Fear of Missing Out\n\nFear of missing out, or FOMO, occurs when rising prices create pressure to buy immediately.\n\nPossible signs include:\n\nIgnoring valuation\n\nIncreasing position size suddenly\n\nBuying without research\n\nAbandoning category limits\n\nBelieving the opportunity will never return\n\nA framework may require:\n\nA waiting period\n\nCompletion of the research checklist\n\nPosition-size calculation\n\nNo purchase beyond the maximum allocation\n\nUrgency is often a marketing technique rather than an investment advantage.\n\n### Loss Aversion\n\nLoss aversion describes the tendency to feel losses more strongly than equivalent gains.\n\nIt may cause investors to:\n\nHold failing assets too long\n\nSell winners too early\n\nAvoid necessary rebalancing\n\nRefuse to acknowledge thesis failure\n\nA predefined invalidation rule can reduce this bias.\n\nThe purpose is not to eliminate discomfort.\n\nIt is to prevent discomfort from overriding evidence.\n\n### Confirmation Bias\n\nConfirmation bias causes people to search for information supporting their existing belief while dismissing contrary evidence.\n\nTo counter it:\n\nWrite the main risks\n\nSearch deliberately for criticism\n\nIdentify what would disprove the thesis\n\nReview opposing analysis\n\nSeparate community enthusiasm from evidence\n\nAn investment thesis that cannot be questioned is closer to an identity or belief system than an analysis.\n\n### Anchoring\n\nAnchoring occurs when one number influences judgement excessively.\n\nCommon anchors include:\n\nPurchase price\n\nPrevious all-time high\n\nInfluencer target\n\nInitial market capitalisation\n\nA round-number forecast\n\nThe previous price does not determine future value.\n\nEvery review should use current evidence and realistic future scenarios.\n\n### Recency Bias\n\nRecency bias gives excessive importance to recent events.\n\nDuring a bull market, investors may believe prices will continue rising.\n\nDuring a crash, they may believe recovery is impossible.\n\nA framework should use:\n\nSeveral market cycles\n\nLong-term data\n\nScenario analysis\n\nPredefined allocation limits\n\nRecent performance is one data point, not a permanent law.\n\n### Overconfidence\n\nOverconfidence may develop after a series of profitable decisions.\n\nIt can lead to:\n\nLarger positions\n\nIncreased leverage\n\nReduced research\n\nIgnored risk limits\n\nExcessive trading\n\nProfits do not prove that the method cannot fail.\n\nPosition limits should not increase automatically after short-term success.\n\n### Herd Behaviour\n\nHerd behaviour occurs when participants follow the crowd because many others appear convinced.\n\nThe crowd can provide useful information.\n\nIt can also produce:\n\nBubbles\n\nPanic\n\nMispricing\n\nCrowded trades\n\nLiquidity traps\n\nThe relevant question is not how many people believe the story.\n\nIt is whether the evidence and valuation support it.\n\n### Sunk-Cost Fallacy\n\nThe sunk-cost fallacy causes investors to continue committing resources because they have already invested time or money.\n\nExamples include:\n\nBuying more to rescue a failing position\n\nRefusing to exit because research took months\n\nSupporting a project because of community involvement\n\nHolding because the loss is already large\n\nPast costs cannot be recovered through loyalty.\n\nFuture decisions should be based on future expected value.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,7,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-30-lesson-08','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Narrative Bias and Material Events','cmf-module-2-30','text','### Narrative Bias\n\nCryptocurrency markets frequently organise around compelling stories.\n\nExamples may involve:\n\nNew financial systems\n\nArtificial intelligence\n\nGaming\n\nTokenisation\n\nDigital ownership\n\nPrivacy\n\nInstitutional adoption\n\nA narrative may attract capital before genuine value is demonstrated.\n\nThe framework should require measurable evidence that the project can benefit from the narrative.\n\nA good story does not guarantee a good token.\n\n### Social-Media Policy\n\nA personal framework may include rules for social-media information.\n\nFor example:\n\nNo purchases based solely on one post\n\nDisclose whether the promoter owns the token\n\nVerify claims through primary sources\n\nAvoid anonymous direct-message opportunities\n\nNever reveal seed phrases to support accounts\n\nDo not treat follower count as expertise\n\nRecord the actual research independently\n\nSocial media can identify ideas.\n\nIt should not complete the due-diligence process.\n\n### Cooling-Off Period\n\nA cooling-off period is a deliberate delay between discovering an opportunity and investing.\n\nIt may be:\n\nSeveral hours\n\nOne day\n\nSeveral days\n\nThe length can depend on:\n\nPosition size\n\nAsset risk\n\nMarket conditions\n\nA delay allows:\n\nEmotional intensity to decline\n\nClaims to be verified\n\nRisks to be reviewed\n\nPosition size to be calculated\n\nTruly durable opportunities usually survive a reasonable period of analysis.\n\n### Scenario Analysis\n\nScenario analysis considers several possible futures rather than one forecast.\n\nPossible scenarios include:\n\n### Bear Case\n\nAdoption weakens\n\nToken supply increases\n\nRegulation becomes restrictive\n\nPrice declines substantially\n\n### Base Case\n\nProject develops gradually\n\nAdoption grows moderately\n\nValuation remains reasonable\n\n### Bull Case\n\nStrong network effects develop\n\nRevenue and usage increase\n\nThe project gains meaningful market share\n\nAssigning probabilities can help compare opportunities.\n\nThe estimates remain uncertain and should be conservative.\n\n### Expected Value\n\nA simplified expected value can be calculated as:\n\nExpected value = Sum of each outcome multiplied by its probability\n\nSuppose:\n\nBear case: 40-percent probability, 70-percent loss\n\nBase case: 40-percent probability, 50-percent gain\n\nBull case: 20-percent probability, 300-percent gain\n\nExpected return:\n\n0.40 × −70 + 0.40 × 50 + 0.20 × 300\n\n−28 + 20 + 60 = 52 percent\n\nThis does not mean the investment will return fifty-two percent.\n\nIt reveals how assumptions combine.\n\nOverly optimistic probabilities can make any investment appear attractive.\n\n### Stress Testing\n\nStress testing examines how the portfolio behaves under severe conditions.\n\nPossible tests include:\n\nCore assets fall fifty percent\n\nSpeculative assets fall ninety percent\n\nA stablecoin depegs\n\nAn exchange freezes withdrawals\n\nA DeFi protocol is exploited\n\nA Layer 2 bridge fails\n\nNetwork fees rise dramatically\n\nIncome is lost\n\nTax becomes payable during a bear market\n\nAsk:\n\nWhat is the total loss?\n\nCan essential obligations still be met?\n\nWhich positions share the same risk?\n\nCan assets be accessed?\n\nWhich actions would be required?\n\nA portfolio should be survivable under more than the optimistic scenario.\n\n### Drawdown Planning\n\nA drawdown is a decline from the portfolio’s previous peak.\n\nThe investor should estimate how they would respond to:\n\nTwenty-percent drawdown\n\nForty-percent drawdown\n\nSixty-percent drawdown\n\nEighty-percent drawdown\n\nThe plan may specify:\n\nNo emotional selling without thesis review\n\nNo increased leverage\n\nReassess asset quality\n\nRebalance only when criteria remain satisfied\n\nPreserve emergency liquidity\n\nThe purpose is to prepare before the emotional event occurs.\n\n### Bear-Market Plan\n\nA bear-market plan may include:\n\nReviewing every thesis\n\nEliminating weak or fraudulent assets\n\nReducing unnecessary platform exposure\n\nMonitoring token unlocks\n\nPreserving liquidity\n\nAvoiding forced yield strategies\n\nMaintaining security\n\nContinuing only predefined accumulation plans\n\nUpdating tax records\n\nA bear market can reveal which projects depend on incentives and speculation.\n\nFalling price does not automatically mean every asset is attractive.\n\n### Bull-Market Plan\n\nA bull-market plan may include:\n\nRebalancing oversized positions\n\nReducing speculative concentration\n\nTaking staged profits\n\nAvoiding excessive leverage\n\nReviewing valuation\n\nStrengthening custody\n\nPreparing for tax obligations\n\nResisting FOMO\n\nRising markets create a different form of risk: overconfidence.\n\nA framework should protect capital during both fear and euphoria.\n\n### Market-Cycle Awareness\n\nCryptocurrency markets often move through phases involving:\n\nAccumulation\n\nTrend development\n\nEuphoria\n\nDistribution\n\nDecline\n\nCapitulation\n\nRecovery\n\nCycle identification is uncertain.\n\nThe framework should not require perfect timing.\n\nInstead, it may adjust:\n\nPosition size\n\nProfit-taking\n\nSpeculative exposure\n\nLiquidity reserve\n\nResearch standards\n\nMarket-cycle awareness should support risk management rather than absolute prediction.\n\n### Review Schedule\n\nA portfolio-review schedule may include:\n\n### Monthly Operational Review\n\nCustody\n\nTransactions\n\nDeFi positions\n\nSecurity alerts\n\nLiquidation risk\n\n### Quarterly Investment Review\n\nAllocation\n\nThesis\n\nAdoption\n\nTokenomics\n\nValuation\n\nRebalancing\n\n### Annual Policy Review\n\nFinancial objectives\n\nRisk capacity\n\nTax\n\nRegulation\n\nPortfolio limits\n\nCustody plan\n\nEvent-driven reviews should occur after material developments.\n\n### Material Events\n\nEvents that may trigger immediate review include:\n\nSecurity exploit\n\nStablecoin depeg\n\nExchange insolvency concern\n\nFounder departure\n\nMajor governance proposal\n\nToken-supply change\n\nUnexpected unlock\n\nRegulatory action\n\nNetwork outage\n\nBridge failure\n\nLoss of important integration\n\nNot every social-media rumour deserves immediate action.\n\nMaterial events should be verified through credible sources.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,8,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-30-lesson-09','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Portfolio Dashboard and 5. Asset Allocation','cmf-module-2-30','text','### Portfolio Dashboard\n\nA dashboard may contain:\n\nAsset\n\nCategory\n\nQuantity\n\nMarket value\n\nCurrent allocation\n\nTarget allocation\n\nMaximum allocation\n\nCost basis\n\nCustody location\n\nLiquidity rating\n\nRisk rating\n\nThesis status\n\nNext review date\n\nUpcoming unlocks\n\nMajor dependencies\n\nDo not include:\n\nPrivate keys\n\nSeed phrases\n\nPasswords\n\nAuthentication codes\n\nThe dashboard should support decisions without compromising security.\n\n### Risk Register\n\nA risk register identifies major portfolio risks.\n\nPossible columns include:\n\nRisk\n\nAssets affected\n\nProbability\n\nPotential impact\n\nWarning signs\n\nMitigation\n\nAction trigger\n\nReview date\n\nExamples may include:\n\nStablecoin issuer failure\n\nExchange insolvency\n\nBridge exploit\n\nRegulatory restriction\n\nToken inflation\n\nGovernance capture\n\nWallet compromise\n\nA risk register makes hidden dependencies visible.\n\n### Watchlist Rules\n\nA watchlist should not be a substitute for a portfolio.\n\nFor each watchlist asset, record:\n\nReason for monitoring\n\nRequired evidence\n\nAttractive valuation range\n\nMain risk\n\nEvent that would qualify it\n\nEvent that would remove it\n\nA token should not be purchased merely because it remains on the watchlist for a long time.\n\n### Pre-Investment Checklist\n\nBefore buying, ask:\n\nWhat does the project do?\n\nWhy is the token necessary?\n\nWho uses the product?\n\nWhat evidence shows genuine adoption?\n\nWho built it?\n\nWhat has the team delivered?\n\nHow does the token capture value?\n\nWhat are the circulating, total and maximum supplies?\n\nWhat inflation and unlocks are expected?\n\nWho controls governance?\n\nHave the contracts or network been audited?\n\nWhat are the main security risks?\n\nWhere does the asset trade?\n\nIs liquidity sufficient?\n\nIs the asset native, wrapped or bridged?\n\nWhat is the current valuation?\n\nWhat assumptions support the valuation?\n\nWhat is the investment thesis?\n\nWhat would invalidate it?\n\nWhat is the time horizon?\n\nWhat portfolio role will the asset serve?\n\nWhat is the maximum position size?\n\nHow will the asset be secured?\n\nWhat tax and regulatory issues may apply?\n\nAm I acting from evidence or urgency?\n\n### Position-Increase Checklist\n\nBefore adding to a position, ask:\n\nHas the thesis strengthened?\n\nHas valuation improved?\n\nHas the price fallen because of temporary volatility or permanent deterioration?\n\nWill the new purchase exceed category limits?\n\nHas token supply changed?\n\nAre major unlocks approaching?\n\nHas liquidity improved or weakened?\n\nAm I averaging down to recover an emotional loss?\n\nWould I make this purchase if I did not already own the asset?\n\nExisting ownership should not lower the research standard.\n\n### Position-Reduction Checklist\n\nBefore reducing, ask:\n\nHas the thesis weakened?\n\nIs the position overweight?\n\nHas valuation become excessive?\n\nHas liquidity deteriorated?\n\nHas portfolio risk changed?\n\nAre tax consequences understood?\n\nIs the decision driven by evidence or short-term fear?\n\nDoes the sale improve the overall portfolio?\n\nReduction can be appropriate even when the asset remains attractive.\n\nRisk management and investment belief can coexist.\n\n### Exit Checklist\n\nBefore exiting, ask:\n\nHas the thesis been invalidated?\n\nIs the project permanently impaired?\n\nHas governance become unacceptable?\n\nHas security failed?\n\nIs liquidity disappearing?\n\nIs there a better risk-adjusted use of capital?\n\nIs the sale part of rebalancing?\n\nAm I reacting to market panic without reviewing the evidence?\n\nCan the transaction be executed safely?\n\nHave tax records been prepared?\n\nAn exit should follow the framework where possible.\n\nEmergency events may require rapid action.\n\n### Post-Decision Review\n\nAfter a position is closed or materially changed, review:\n\nOriginal thesis\n\nInformation available at entry\n\nPosition size\n\nEntry quality\n\nRisk management\n\nExit reason\n\nEmotional behaviour\n\nWhat worked\n\nWhat failed\n\nWhich rule should change, if any\n\nDo not change the framework after every individual loss.\n\nLook for repeated patterns across several decisions.\n\n### When to Change the Framework\n\nThe framework should evolve when:\n\nFinancial circumstances change\n\nInvestment knowledge improves\n\nRegulations change\n\nNew technology changes risk\n\nRepeated evidence reveals a weakness\n\nThe original objectives change\n\nIt should not change simply because:\n\nA recent investment lost money\n\nA speculative token rose without you\n\nSocial media promotes a new strategy\n\nA bull market makes risk appear unnecessary\n\nAdaptation should be evidence-based.\n\n### Simplicity\n\nA framework should be detailed enough to manage risk but simple enough to follow.\n\nExcessive complexity can create:\n\nConflicting rules\n\nAdministrative burden\n\nSelective interpretation\n\nDecision paralysis\n\nFalse precision\n\nA clear framework consistently applied is generally more useful than an elaborate one ignored during emotional markets.\n\n### Personal Investment Policy Statement\n\nA personal investment policy statement, or IPS, summarises the framework.\n\nIt may include:\n\n### 1. Purpose\n\nWhy the digital asset portfolio exists.\n\n### 2. Financial Context\n\nHow the portfolio fits into broader finances.\n\n### 3. Time Horizon\n\nWhen capital may be required.\n\n### 4. Risk Limits\n\nMaximum total exposure, drawdown tolerance and prohibited activities.\n\n### 5. Asset Allocation\n\nTarget categories and allocation bands.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,9,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-30-lesson-10','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','6. Position Limits and Allowing Exceptions for Exciting Opportunities','cmf-module-2-30','text','### 6. Position Limits\n\nMaximum exposure to one asset, network, platform or protocol.\n\n### 7. Selection Criteria\n\nMinimum research and eligibility standards.\n\n### 8. Entry and Exit Rules\n\nConditions for buying, adding, reducing and selling.\n\n### 9. Custody and Security\n\nWallets, exchanges, recovery and transaction procedures.\n\n### 10. Monitoring and Rebalancing\n\nReview schedule and event triggers.\n\n### 11. Tax and Records\n\nDocumentation responsibilities.\n\n### 12. Behavioural Controls\n\nCooling-off periods, social-media rules and leverage restrictions.\n\nThe IPS should be dated and reviewed periodically.\n\n### Example Educational Investment Policy Statement\n\nThe following is an illustration and not a personalised recommendation.\n\n### Purpose\n\nThe portfolio exists to provide limited long-term exposure to digital asset networks and applications without threatening essential financial security.\n\n### Capital\n\nOnly surplus capital that is not required for near-term obligations may be invested.\n\n### Risk\n\nThe investor accepts substantial volatility but will not use borrowed money or uncontrolled leverage.\n\n### Allocation\n\nThe digital asset portfolio will contain core, growth, speculative and liquidity categories.\n\nSpeculative and experimental assets will remain strictly limited.\n\n### Selection\n\nEvery meaningful position requires a written thesis, supply analysis, liquidity review and custody plan.\n\n### Position Size\n\nNo asset, platform, stablecoin or protocol may exceed its predefined limit.\n\nRelated ecosystem exposures will be aggregated.\n\n### Entry\n\nPositions may be entered in stages after the research checklist is completed.\n\n### Exit\n\nPositions will be reduced or closed when the thesis is invalidated, security fails or allocation limits are exceeded.\n\n### Custody\n\nLong-term holdings will be separated from active DeFi and trading wallets.\n\n### Review\n\nAllocations will be reviewed quarterly and after material events.\n\n### Records\n\nAll transactions, fees, rewards and transfers will be recorded.\n\n### Behaviour\n\nNo investment will be made solely because of social-media urgency or recent price appreciation.\n\n### Building Your Framework Step by Step\n\n\n\n### Step 1: Define Your Purpose\n\nWrite one sentence describing why the portfolio exists.\n\n### Step 2: Review Your Financial Position\n\nIdentify essential funds, liabilities and liquidity needs.\n\n### Step 3: Set Total Exposure\n\nDefine the maximum portion of broader wealth allocated to digital assets.\n\n### Step 4: Establish Categories\n\nCreate core, growth, speculative and liquidity categories as appropriate.\n\n### Step 5: Set Limits\n\nDefine maximum asset, sector, network, platform and protocol exposures.\n\n### Step 6: Define Research Standards\n\nCreate a minimum due-diligence checklist.\n\n### Step 7: Write Thesis Requirements\n\nSpecify what every investment thesis must contain.\n\n### Step 8: Define Entry Rules\n\nEstablish valuation, evidence and technical conditions.\n\n### Step 9: Define Position-Sizing Rules\n\nConnect allocation to possible loss and liquidity.\n\n### Step 10: Define Reduction and Exit Rules\n\nState what will trigger action.\n\n### Step 11: Build the Custody Plan\n\nSeparate long-term, active and experimental risks.\n\n### Step 12: Establish Monitoring\n\nCreate monthly, quarterly and annual review schedules.\n\n### Step 13: Prepare Stress Scenarios\n\nModel severe market, protocol and personal events.\n\n### Step 14: Establish Behavioural Controls\n\nInclude cooling-off periods and leverage restrictions.\n\n### Step 15: Document Everything\n\nCreate the policy statement, journal, dashboard and risk register.\n\n### Personal Framework Checklist\n\nBefore finalising the framework, ask:\n\nIs the portfolio purpose clearly defined?\n\nIs the investment time horizon realistic?\n\nAre essential funds protected?\n\nWhat is the maximum total digital asset exposure?\n\nWhat is my true financial risk capacity?\n\nWhich asset categories are permitted?\n\nWhich asset types are prohibited?\n\nWhat is the maximum position size?\n\nWhat is the maximum ecosystem exposure?\n\nWhat is the maximum exchange or custodian exposure?\n\nWhat is the maximum DeFi protocol exposure?\n\nWhich stablecoins are permitted?\n\nWhat minimum research is required?\n\nWhat must an investment thesis contain?\n\nWhat evidence invalidates a thesis?\n\nWhat conditions permit a position increase?\n\nHow will entries be staged?\n\nWhat rebalancing method will be used?\n\nWhat triggers a reduction or exit?\n\nIs leverage permitted?\n\nWhich staking, lending or DeFi activities are allowed?\n\nHow will assets be secured?\n\nHow will wallets be separated?\n\nIs a recovery and inheritance plan available?\n\nHow will transactions be verified?\n\nHow will taxes and records be managed?\n\nWhich sources of information are acceptable?\n\nHow often will positions be reviewed?\n\nWhich material events trigger immediate review?\n\nHow will behavioural biases be controlled?\n\nWhat happens if the portfolio falls fifty percent?\n\nWhat happens if an exchange freezes withdrawals?\n\nWhat happens if a stablecoin depegs?\n\nWhat happens if a DeFi protocol is exploited?\n\nIs the framework simple enough to follow consistently?\n\n### Common Framework Mistakes\n\n\n\n### Starting With Token Selection\n\nAssets are chosen before objectives and risk limits are defined.\n\n### Setting Rules During a Crisis\n\nThe participant waits until emotions are intense before deciding what to do.\n\n### Using Vague Objectives\n\nThe portfolio has no measurable purpose.\n\n### Ignoring Broader Finances\n\nCrypto exposure is evaluated separately from debt, savings and obligations.\n\n### Failing to Aggregate Related Risks\n\nSeveral tokens create hidden concentration in one ecosystem.\n\n### Writing a Thesis Without Invalidation\n\nThe investment can never be proven wrong.\n\n### Changing the Time Horizon After a Loss\n\nA failed trade becomes an indefinite holding.\n\n### Treating Security as an Afterthought\n\nCustody planning begins only after the portfolio becomes valuable.\n\n### Overcomplicating the Framework\n\nThe rules become too difficult to use.\n\n### Changing Rules After Every Outcome\n\nRandom gains and losses create constant strategy changes.\n\n### Ignoring Tax and Records\n\nThe investor cannot reconstruct transactions later.\n\n### Allowing Exceptions for Exciting Opportunities\n\nThe framework is abandoned precisely when it is most needed.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,10,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-30-lesson-11','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Common Misunderstandings and Key Takeaway','cmf-module-2-30','text','### Common Misunderstandings\n\n#### “A Framework Guarantees Better Returns”\n\nIt improves process and risk control but cannot guarantee market outcomes.\n\n#### “Long-Term Investing Means I Never Sell”\n\nA long-term thesis still requires invalidation and review.\n\n#### “A Good Project Deserves an Unlimited Allocation”\n\nProject quality does not remove valuation, liquidity or unexpected risk.\n\n#### “Diversification Means Owning Many Tokens”\n\nTrue diversification requires different underlying risk drivers.\n\n#### “A Falling Price Means I Should Buy More”\n\nThe decline may reflect permanent deterioration.\n\n#### “A Rising Price Confirms the Thesis”\n\nPrice can rise through speculation while fundamentals remain weak.\n\n#### “Profit-Taking Shows a Lack of Conviction”\n\nReducing concentration can be responsible risk management.\n\n#### “Self-Custody Removes All Risk”\n\nIt replaces exchange risk with key-management and operational responsibility.\n\n#### “Stablecoins Are the Cash Portion of a Portfolio”\n\nThey remain exposed to issuer, reserve, regulatory, smart contract and bridge risk.\n\n#### “Yield Improves Every Investment”\n\nYield may be funded by inflation or accompanied by greater risk.\n\n#### “The Framework Should Never Change”\n\nIt should evolve when evidence, circumstances or objectives change.\n\n#### “Rules Remove Emotion Completely”\n\nThey provide structure, but discipline is still required to follow them.\n\n### Module Summary\n\nA personal digital asset investment framework is a written system for making and reviewing investment decisions.\n\nIt should begin with:\n\nFinancial objectives\n\nTime horizon\n\nLiquidity needs\n\nRisk tolerance\n\nRisk capacity\n\nMaximum digital asset exposure\n\nThe portfolio should define:\n\nAsset categories\n\nTarget allocations\n\nMaximum position sizes\n\nEcosystem and platform limits\n\nPermitted and prohibited activities\n\nEvery meaningful investment should have a written thesis describing:\n\nProject purpose\n\nAdoption\n\nToken utility\n\nValue capture\n\nValuation\n\nRisks\n\nTime horizon\n\nInvalidation\n\nThe framework should establish rules for:\n\nResearch\n\nEntry\n\nStaged accumulation\n\nPosition sizing\n\nRebalancing\n\nProfit-taking\n\nReduction\n\nExit\n\nIt should also include:\n\nCustody\n\nWallet separation\n\nExchange limits\n\nRecovery planning\n\nTransaction procedures\n\nTax records\n\nRegulatory monitoring\n\nScenario analysis and stress testing prepare the investor for:\n\nSevere drawdowns\n\nStablecoin failure\n\nExchange insolvency\n\nDeFi exploits\n\nBridge failures\n\nPersonal liquidity needs\n\nBehavioural controls help reduce:\n\nFear of missing out\n\nLoss aversion\n\nConfirmation bias\n\nAnchoring\n\nOverconfidence\n\nHerd behaviour\n\nSunk-cost thinking\n\nThe framework cannot predict the market or eliminate loss.\n\nIt creates a disciplined process in which:\n\nCapital exposure is deliberate\n\nRisk has limits\n\nDecisions require evidence\n\nSecurity is planned\n\nMistakes remain survivable\n\n### Key Takeaway\n\nA successful investment process is not built around finding one perfect token, indicator or market prediction.\n\nIt is built around a repeatable system.\n\nDefine why you are investing, limit how much can be lost, require evidence before buying, secure every asset appropriately and decide in advance what would make you change your mind.\n\nMarkets will remain uncertain.\n\nYour process does not have to be.\n\nThis completes Course 2: Crypto Mastery — Markets and Applications.\n\nThe next stage of the pathway is Course 3: Crypto Mastery — Advanced Digital Asset Strategy.','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,4,0,0,0,'',NULL,11,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `lessons` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`section_id`,`lesson_type`,`content`,`content_format`,`video_key`,`primary_asset_id`,`intro_asset_id`,`duration_minutes`,`is_preview`,`available_after_days`,`required_watch_percent`,`transcript`,`experience_json`,`position`,`updated_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-30-lesson-12','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Check your understanding','cmf-module-2-30','text','### Check your understanding\n\nAnswer these questions to self-assess your understanding before moving on.\n\n1. What is a personal digital asset investment framework?\n\n2. How does a framework differ from a market prediction?\n\n3. Why should broader personal finances be reviewed before investing?\n\n4. What should the portfolio’s purpose statement explain?\n\n5. What is the difference between risk tolerance and risk capacity?\n\n6. What is risk requirement?\n\n7. Why should essential money remain outside cryptocurrency investments?\n\n8. What is the purpose of portfolio categories?\n\n9. Why should speculative assets normally receive smaller allocations?\n\n10. What is aggregate ecosystem exposure?\n\n11. Why should maximum exchange and protocol exposures be defined?\n\n12. What should a minimum research standard include?\n\n13. Why is project usage different from token value capture?\n\n14. Why must current market capitalisation be compared with future supply?\n\n15. What should be reviewed in a token unlock schedule?\n\n16. What is an investment thesis?\n\n17. What should thesis invalidation describe?\n\n18. Why should price movement not automatically change the thesis?\n\n19. What are entry criteria?\n\n20. What are the benefits and limitations of staged entries?\n\n21. Why can automatic dollar-cost averaging be dangerous?\n\n22. How should position size relate to potential loss?\n\n23. What is an allocation band?\n\n24. Why should rebalancing include fundamental review?\n\n25. What events may justify reducing a position?\n\n26. Why is waiting for break even a form of anchoring?\n\n27. What are possible profit-taking methods?\n\n28. Why may trading and investment accounts be separated?\n\n29. What should a leverage policy contain?\n\n30. Which risks should be included in a DeFi participation policy?\n\n31. Why should staked and liquid-staking assets be aggregated?\n\n32. What should a stablecoin policy evaluate?\n\n33. Why should long-term, active and experimental wallets be separated?\n\n34. What should a recovery plan address?\n\n35. Why should every large transfer begin with a test transaction?\n\n36. Which cryptocurrency activities may require tax records?\n\n37. Why should primary sources receive more weight than promotional content?\n\n38. What is the purpose of an investment journal?\n\n39. How can a good decision produce a loss?\n\n40. What is confirmation bias?\n\n41. What is the sunk-cost fallacy?\n\n42. How can a cooling-off period reduce FOMO?\n\n43. What is scenario analysis?\n\n44. What is the purpose of stress testing?\n\n45. What should a bear-market plan contain?\n\n46. Why is a bull-market plan also necessary?\n\n47. What information can be included in a portfolio dashboard?\n\n48. What is a risk register?\n\n49. What should a personal investment policy statement contain?\n\n50. When should an investment framework be changed?','markdown',NULL,NULL,NULL,6,0,0,0,'',NULL,12,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
--> statement-breakpoint
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO `course_sections` (`id`,`course_id`,`title`,`position`,`created_at`) SELECT 'cmf-module-2-31','cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production','Module 2.31: Completion Crypto Mastery  Markets and Applications',31,1785297600000 WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `courses` WHERE `id`='cognizen-crypto-mastery-foundations-production');
